<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-89 2349EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-SFQuake-Universal     10-20 0644</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SF Quake-Universal,0667</SECOND>
<HEAD>SF Quake Veterans, Others Left Unshaken by Studio Tour's Simulated
Temblor</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-SF Quake, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN ROGERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNIVERSAL CITY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As northern Californians added up
earthquake repair bills in the billions of dollars, Southern
Californians lined up to plop down $21 apiece to be shaken and
scared by a fake shake.
   The attraction: the Universal Studios Tours' simulated
earthquake, which officials had closed for two days after Tuesday's
deadly temblor devastated the San Francisco Bay area.
   When the attraction reopened Friday morning, thousands braved a
light, chilly rain to clamber aboard trams and see what they might
have missed.
   Or, in the case of northern Californian Ruth Hitchcock, to be
shaken again.
   ``It bounced me all over my driveway,'' she said of Tuesday's
quake that rattled her Livermore home. ``I've lived in that house
for 32 years and it's the strongest one I've ever felt.''
   But it wasn't enough to keep her from canceling a trip to
Southern California and a long-planned visit to the Universal
Studios Tour and its simulated earthquake ride.
   ``I came clear down here to see this,'' Ms. Hitchcock said
excitedly afterward. ``If they had canceled it, I would have been
very disappointed.''
   None of those interviewed Friday seemed bothered that the fake
quake is supposed to happen in San Francisco, or that they had just
witnessed a giant tanker truck hurled through the air as a roadway
fell in a staged scene similar to Tuesday's deadly collapse of
Oakland's Nimitz Freeway.
   Francis McClaskey, who went through Los Angeles' Sylmar quake in
1971, dismissed the irony with a wave of his hand.
   ``Nah, it's all in fun,'' said the retired trucker who now lives
in Boulder, Colo. ``This place is all make-believe. People can
separate reality from fantasy.''
   ``I thought it was great, especially when the (freeway) bridge
came down,'' said Jim Tolent, one of a group of teen-agers who
bounded from the tour tram talking excitedly about the ride. ``But
I do feel sorry for the people of San Francisco.''
   Curtis Marshall of Tracy said he was ``kind of sad'' he hadn't
been home in northern California for the real thing. He was at
Disneyland on Tuesday.
   Surin Hutawaniatana of Bangkok, Thailand, said he would have
missed the attraction if the real quake hadn't hit.
   ``We were going to San Francisco,'' he said of his tour group.
``But when they canceled that part of the trip we got to come here
instead.''
   He added he was thrilled with the ride.
   ``I had heard it's great, and it was,'' he said.
   Even so, tour operators were taking no chances at offending
anyone.
   While visitors were threatened by a robotic giant shark from the
movie ``Jaws,'' shot at by actors dressed as space aliens, and
buried in a make-believe avalanche, the comic patter of tour guides
ran apace.
   But it halted as the tram was about to enter a sound stage made
to look like a Bay Area Rapid Transit subway tunnel.
   ``For those of you who do not want to experience this, we
perfectly understand,'' a tour guide said solemnly over a
microphone as he gave any of the more than 200 tram riders an
opportunity to get off. One woman did.
   ``That is not a regular thing,'' Universal spokeswoman Joan
Bullard said of halting the tram before the fake quake. ``We are
doing it today and perhaps this weekend.''
   When the tram finally entered the set, several people braced
themselves.
   ``It's only make-believe,'' one woman cautioned her son.
   Several riders applauded when the quake was over, but some
veterans of real quakes expressed mild disappoint. They noted the
ride didn't last long enough or shake violently enough to match the
real thing.
   ``I liked the avalanche better because it really gave you the
feeling you were falling,'' Tolent said.
</TEXT>
