<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-89 2352EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-RedArmyBanned     10-20 0318</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Red Army Banned,0327</SECOND>
<HEAD>Joint Appearance of Red Army, Navy Bands Nixed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATIA BLACKBURN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pentagon nixed two joint performances by the
Soviet Red Army Band and Navy bands, but promoters say they don't
see the concerts causing a security breach and are fighting to
reverse the decision.
   The 200-member Red Army Song and Dance Ensemble, including the
40-piece band, is scheduled to perform Oct. 24 in the Seattle
Center Arena during its first tour of the United States.
   Easterday Promotions suggested that the 35-piece Sand Point Navy
Band appear in a free Seattle performance with the Red Army Band
the same day, said owner Kris Easterday.
   She also worked to arrange a joint appearance of the Soviet band
with the 35-piece Fairchild Air National Guard band in Spokane on
Oct. 26.
   Both Sand Point and Fairchild authorities were enthusiastic,
Easterday said, but Cmdr. James Britt at Sand Point said officials
had to submit the proposal to the Pentagon.
   On Wednesday, about two weeks after Easterday started promoting
the events, the Navy rejected the joint appearances.
   Britt said he didn't know why the Navy rejected the idea.
Easterday said a Pentagon official, Capt. Doug McUrrach, told her
the two countries had restrictions on the movement of military
personnel in each other's countries.
   The promoters were baffled.
   ``It's just an innocent half hour for the bands to get
together,'' said Easterday spokeswoman Kerry Coughlin. ``It seeme
really strange.''
   Easternday asked the office of Sen. Slade Gorton for help and
the Republican lawmaker's Seattle office started contacting Navy
officials on Friday.
   ``Slade is convinced that this is a good event to have and we're
seeking to have the decision reviewed at the least and at best
reversed,'' said Gorton aide Chuck Nordhoff. ``We're hoping that
message has gotten through but we don't know.''
   McUrrach could not be reached for comment Friday evening.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
