<FIRST>u a AM-Deputies-Shot 2ndLd-Writethru a0854 10-20 0272</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Deputies-Shot, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0854,0276</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sheriff's Deputy Killed, Another Wounded, By Gunman</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf to UPDATE with Manzella charged with murder.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN F. BONFATTI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLARENCE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A sheriff's deputy was killed and his
partner wounded Friday as they tried to arrest a man on a drug
charge, and the suspect held police at bay for nearly nine hours,
authorities said.
   Rudy Manzella, 30, whose home in this Buffalo suburb was
surrounded by more than 100 law enforcement officers, surrendered
at 10:20 p.m., ending a standoff that began at 1:30 p.m.
   Manzella was charged with first-degree murder, said Erie County
sheriff's Sgt. John Fox.
   Manzella, who was inside the house alone, had been talking by
telephone with police negotiators, but contact was broken off at 8
p.m., said county Undersheriff William Payne. As the standoff
continued, power to the neighborhood was shut off.
   The dead deputy was identified as William Dillemuth, 45, of
Depew. His partner, Deputy David Carlson, 34, of Angola, was in
serious condition with a gunshot wound at Millard Fillmore Suburban
Hospital, hospital officials said.
   Both officers were shot at while trying to arrest Manzella for
possession of marijuana in the city of Tonawanda, according to
Thomas Staebell, chief of patrol for the sheriff's department.
   Both deputies were apparently hit by gunfire outside the house,
Payne said. While Carlson was able to get away from the home,
Dillemuth fell on the driveway. Authorities say it was some time
before officers, fearful of being shot themselves, were able to
remove Dillemuth's body.
   Staebell said Manzella had faced drug charges in the past.
</TEXT>
