<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-89 0027EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-IllegalLegal     10-20 0269</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Illegal Legal,0277</SECOND>
<HEAD>Florida Supreme Court Outlaws Legal-Size Paper in Court Documents</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CURT ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state Supreme Court has decided
long briefs are on the way out for Florida attorneys and court
clerks.
   But the high court wasn't making a fashion statement Thursday.
   Beginning in January 1991, the state's court system will no
longer use legal-sized paper _ 8{ by 14 inches _ in any documents,
including lawsuits, pleadings, notices, opinions, judgments and
motions. The change mirrors rules in the federal courts and at
least 36 other states.
   The new rule actually takes effect in January 1990, but the
Supreme Court decided to allow a one-year grace period during which
the state's courts can accept either the legal size or standard
8{-by-11 paper.
   For years, a group called Eliminate Legal-Size Files _ or ELF _
has campaigned to get government to use the standard size.
   Walt Mullarkey, a retired certified records manager for the
state Division of Library Services, was chairman of ELF for five
years.
   ``It's just standardization. If everybody in the army fired a
different size weapon, they'd have a hell of a time fighting a
war,'' Mullarkey said.
   He said advantages to using just one size include having uniform
filing cabinets and savings from buying a single size in bulk
rather than two sizes.
   When the state Supreme Court first proposed the rule in April,
there was some understandable criticism, said Sid White, clerk of
the Supreme Court.
   ``It seems like most of the opposition came from people who were
selling legal-size paper and cabinets,'' White said.
</TEXT>
