<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-89 0029EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Korea-BlackMarket Bjt   10-20 0602</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Korea-Black Market, Bjt,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Scotch, SPAM and Rice are Big Black-Market Sellers in South Korea</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. military personnel in South Korea buy six
times as much Chivas Regal scotch as the much larger U.S. force in
Europe _ but instead of drinking it, they're selling it on the
Korean black market, a study says.
   SPAM, Aqua Net hair spray and rice are among other favorites
selling in huge quantities at U.S. military commissaries in South
Korea, apparently bound for the black market, the General
Accounting Office said Thursday.
   Such sales far exceed what would normally be consumed by the
70,000 authorized buyers stationed there, and U.S. taxpayers are
footing part of the bill, GAO witnesses said at a Senate hearing.
The GAO is Congress' investigative arm.
   The Defense Department exports duty-free goods to bases in Korea
and other countries for sale at cut-rate prices in the commissaries
and exchanges.
   In 1988, commissaries in South Korea sold 1.1 million cans of
SPAM, or almost 12 pounds per person per year; 34 pounds or 816
American cheese slices for every man, woman and child, and 170
pounds of rice for every consumer.
   ``If one person consumed 170 pounds of rice a year, that would
be a little over 14 pounds of rice a month or just under a half a
pound of rice a day,'' said Sen. Carl Levin, D-Mich., chairman of
the Senate Governmental Affairs subcommittee on government
oversight and management.
   ``There would be little room in a person's diet for anything
else but rice,'' he said.
   Black marketeers recruit U.S. service members or their
dependents to buy the products for later resale or enlist the help
of cashiers and sales clerks, mostly Koreans.
   The investigators concluded that most of the Chivas Regal scotch
purchased for sale, including the 12-year-old bottle and
21-year-old bottle, ends up in the black market. In 1988, service
members in Korea bought 314,748 liters of the scotch.
   ``Fewer military members in Korea _ 15 percent of the total in
Europe _ purchased more than six times the number of Chivas Regal
bottles purchased in Europe,'' the investigators said.
   In addition, the meat merchant who services the Osan Air Base
told investigators that 70,000 pounds of oxtails are supplied per
month to the commissary.
   Donna Heivilin, director of logistics issues for the GAO, said
Korean tariffs make the price of legally imported U.S. goods very
expensive.
   Heivilin told the subcommittee the cost of serving the black
market was about $7 million a year, assuming that 20 percent of the
$250.4 million worth of items sold in Korea in 1988 ended up in the
cupboards of unauthorized individuals.
   ``This is totally abhorrent, totally unacceptable,'' said Levin,
who has called for a reduction of U.S. forces in Korea.
   Sandra Kristoff, an assistant U.S. trade representative for Asia
and the Pacific, acknowledged that Korea's restrictive import
practices have fueled the black market.
   But she stressed that the Korean black market has been in
existence for some time, and the United States is taking steps to
reduce the illegal sales.
   ``In July of 1988 our cigarette agreement with Korea went into
effect, permitting the importation of cigarettes without
restraint,'' she said. ``Black market activity in this product has
dropped off significantly since then.''
   To solve the problem, Levin has suggested elimination of the
ration control system in which service members with no dependents
are limited to $500 per month and those with dependents $800 per
month.
   Another option is convincing South Korea ``to open its doors to
these high-demand consumer goods,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891020-0014 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-89 0031EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-ColombianSentence     10-20 0256</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Colombian Sentence,0262</SECOND>
<HEAD>Colombian Drug Trafficker's Sentence Overturned on Nationality Issue</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court overturned the
12-year prison sentence of a Colombian drug trafficker on grounds
that a lower-court judge wrongly considered the man's nationality
in determining punishment.
   The three-member appeals panel on Thursday returned the case of
Mauricio Borrero-Isaza to U.S. District Judge William D. Keller for
resentencing.
   The 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ruled that a sentence may
not be based even partly on a defendant's nationality, noting that
Keller penalized Borrero more harshly than a non-Colombian
co-defendant.
   Borrero was convicted of conspiracy and possession with intent
to distribute cocaine after he was arrested in 1986 with more than
two pounds of the drug in his car.
   During sentencing, Keller repeatedly told the defense attorney
that he wanted to show people in cocaine-exporting countries that
they would be harshly punished if they shipped drugs to the United
States.
   ``Somehow the people who are selling narcotics, particularly
from source countries, have to know that we in the United States
mean business, and we are going to put a stop to this,'' Keller
said at the time. ``I want people in Colombia to know it is not
going to be tolerated.''
   The appeals court said that while it is appropriate to consider
``the fact that a criminal has trafficked in drugs originating from
a source country like Colombia,'' a defendant's nationality is
irrelevant.
   Thomas Lind, a co-defendant who pleaded guilty in the case,
received a seven-year sentence from Keller.
</TEXT>
