<FIRST>r i PM-BRF--Hungary-Samizdat     10-20 0142</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Hungary-Samizdat,0145</SECOND>
<HEAD>Interior Ministry: Confiscated Samizdat To Be Returned</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Interior Ministry says it will
return all samizdat materials and printing machines that police
seized from independent writers and publishers between 1983 and
1988.
   The ministry did not say how much equipment or samizdat had been
confiscated. It said, however, that just one copy of each
confiscated samizdat work remained in the archives as the rest had
been destroyed.
   Many of Hungary's long-time leading dissidents are members of
opposition groups that have in the past 18 months gained full legal
and political recognition as the country transforms itself into a
Western-style democracy.
   One of the best known underground or samizdat journals,
Beszeloe, is now legally sold on Hungarian newsstands and published
regularly.
   The announcement was made Thursday in a communique carried by
the official MTI news agency.
</TEXT>
