<DOCNO> AP891020-0021 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-89 0100EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-PerestroikaBeckons     10-20 0620</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Perestroika Beckons,610</SECOND>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON TODAY: American Businesses are Ready to Cash In</HEAD>
<BYLINE>An AP News Analysis</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration doesn't share the
enthusiasm of U.S. businesses eager to jump in for profit and
excitement as Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev seeks to reform a
Marxist system lagging in productivity and consumer goods.
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III, speaking this week to the
private Foreign Policy Association in New York, again stressed the
view that lasting economic change must come from within; it cannot
and should not be provided by the West.
   Consumer shortages are unlikely to be relieved nor productivity
increased without a stable currency, free and competitive markets,
private property and real prices, Baker said. ``The very logic of
perestroika requires that the Soviets themselves must solve their
own problems in a comprehensive, organic way,'' he said.
   But American businesses are charging in nonetheless. Fifty new
posts are being added to the U.S. Embassy in Moscow to assist them
in grappling with Soviet bureaucracy and a legal system that is in
such flux that entrepreneurs are having a rough time seizing
capitalistic opportunities.
   Gorbachev may be changing the way Soviet bureaucrats and
ordinary citizens think about the marketplace, but historically
people who have lived all their lives under Marxism are not
risk-takers.
   The Soviets also do not have the cash to pay for American-built
enterprises, nor the goods to barter for them _ with the exception
of such items as oil, gold, diamonds and furs that the Soviets
prefer to sell for themselves on world markets.
   And yet about 4,000 American companies are trying to do business
in the Soviet Union, compared to less than 100 before Gorbachev
assumed power in 1985. A thousand joint ventures have been signed
and registered, but only a dozen or so deals have been struck. The
most picturesque: McDonald's and Pizza Hut soon will be selling
fast food to Russians.
   The foreign investment is relatively small, averaging about $1
million a venture.
   Still, American businessmen look at the Soviet Union as the last
great untapped market, said Richard N. Dean, the Coudert Brothers
lawyer who last year opened the first Moscow office for an American
law firm. Dean said Thursday that under Gorbachev the Soviets have
bent over backwards to liberalize their joint venture laws.
   But he described other laws that govern American investors as
``very uncertain territory.'' Often, he said, Soviet laws are not
available to the public. ``Either they are state secrets or nobody
can find them,'' Dean said at a forum on U.S.-Soviet trade
relations.
   Getting approval for projects also is a huge problem for
Westerners. ``This is a business culture that is sort of fused with
a political culture,'' Dean said.
   Moreover, the general atmosphere in the Soviet Union is hazy.
Soviet law is in the midst of a major overhaul. The right to
strike, ownership of property, freedom of assembly and speech are
among the fundamental issues being debated in the Supreme Soviet.
This carries a risk for American businesses, which prefer stability
and certainty.
   And yet, there is a trend under Gorbachev to promote domestic
benefits for the Soviet people. The City Council in Moscow is
prepared to give up a hotel site if the foreign partner is willing
to arrange financing to rebuild a factory outside the capital, Dean
said.
   ``This is a good thing, and it offers some opportunities,'' said
the American lawyer. ``It gets at an awful problem that they have.
The deterioration in the standard of living of the Soviet people is
becoming a greater and greater concern.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: Barry Schweid reports on U.S. foreign policy for
The Associated Press.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
