<FIRST>r a PM-StudentsRally     10-20 0290</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Students Rally,0298</SECOND>
<HEAD>After Rally, Damage to Statehouse and, Possibly, Students' Cause</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN GALVIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opponents of cuts in education funds said a huge
Statehouse demonstration showed the strength of their cause, and
students volunteered to replace mums that were trampled when the
rally turned unruly.
   About 15,000 state college and university students gathered at
the Capitol Wednesday, but organizers lost control of the protest.
Four people were arrested and two injured in the melee.
   ``The fact that so many people came out was extraordinary and
sent a very clear message that they care about the quality of their
education,'' Paul Tsongas, chairman of the Board of Regents in
Higher Education, said Thursday. ``But, like I remember during my
youth, the excesses of a handful always get more attention than
what I believe was the remarkably good (behavior) of the vast, vast
majority.''
   Horticulture students from the University of Massachusetts at
Amherst volunteered Thursday to plant chrysanthemums to replace the
ones trampled by students in front of the Capitol, said state Rep.
Stanley Rosenberg.
   Doors and windows inside the building were broken and a
drainpipe was knocked down by students who climbed to the roof. The
maintenance office said the front lawn would need to be reseeded.
   Rep. Jacqueline Lewis was caught in the crunch of students and
shaken up as she tried to enter the chamber to answer a roll-call
vote. But she said she wouldn't hold the ``ill-behaved and
outrageous'' minority against the students' cause.
   The higher education budget, already strapped by earlier cuts,
is set to be stripped of $25 million more during the next round of
budget reductions. The protesters were calling for the programmed
cuts to be restored.
</TEXT>
