<DOCNO> AP891020-0027 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-89 0143EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-AgricultureNomination     10-20 0520</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Agriculture Nomination,510</SECOND>
<HEAD>Environmentalists Vow Continued Fight Against Controversial Nominee</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Environmentalists who failed to stop a Senate
committee from approving James Cason's nomination to a top natural
resources post will take their fight against him to the Senate
floor.
   ``We are disappointed we didn't win the committee vote,'' Reid
Wilson of the SierraClub said after the Agriculture Committee's
12-7 vote Thursday in favor of Cason. ``But we think it was close
enough to set up a tight struggle on the Senate floor and we are
going to go all out.''
   ``Once the senators hear in depth about this man's record they
are going to be concerned,'' Wilson said.
   Agriculture Committee Chairman Patrick Leahy, D-Vt., urged a
vote against Cason, saying his record in the Interior Department
under President Reagan showed an ``unwillingness to protect the
environment.''
   But committee Republicans, joined by Democratic Sens. Howell
Heflin of Alabama, David Pryor of Arkansas and David Boren of
Oklahoma, voted to send the full Senate Cason's nomination to be
assistant secretary of agriculture for natural resources.
   Boren and Pryor said, however, they might vote against Cason
after the floor debate.
   Sen. Kent Conrad, D-N.D., argued against Cason's confirmation
and said he might try to block a full Senate vote unless he is
convinced Cason can be trusted to protect the public over private
interests.
   Conrad criticized Cason's decision at Interior in 1986 to sell
federal land at ``fire sale prices'' of $2.50 an acre. He said the
government made $17,000 on the sale to private interests who weeks
later resold it for $37 million.
   ``When Congress was considering legislation stopping those
transactions, Mr. Cason went to Colorado and urged investors to
file claims before Congress acted,'' Conrad said.
   Conrad also said Cason cut back on audits of companies buying
oil from wells on public and Indian land. He said the change in
procedures cost the government and the tribes ``tens, perhaps
hundreds of millions of dollars.''
   Sen. Richard Lugar of Indiana, the ranking Republican on the
committee, said his earlier reservations about Cason were answered
when Secretary of Agriculture Clayton Yeutter assured him Cason
would take orders from Yeutter.
   The committee unanimously approved Yeutter's nomination earlier
this year and has supported his work at the Agriculture Department.
   Lugar also said he believed Cason had become much more sensitive
to environmental concerns during the committee's confirmation
hearings.
   Cason appeared before the committee for two days as senators
questioned him about decisions favoring private interests he made
while at Interior during the Reagan administration.
   After the hearings, Leahy called on Bush to withdraw the
nomination.
   Among other problems, Leahy said evidence showed Cason
suppressed a report in 1986 that warned of irreversible
environmental damage, including survival of the spotted owl, if
logging was allowed in certain areas of the Pacific Northwest.
Cason said he withheld the report because he wanted more
information.
   Cason, who has held various high posts at Interior since the
early 1980s, would be in charge of the U.S. Forest Service, if
confirmed. He also would oversee conservation programs affecting
agricultural land.
 
</TEXT>
