<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-89 0149EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-StudentLoans     10-20 0491</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Student Loans,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Defaults in Supplemental Student Loans Jump 1,664 percent</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TAMARA HENRY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A government audit shows defaults on loans
from a new federal student financial aid program skyrocketed by
1,664 percent in three years, and defaults are getting just as bad
with borrowers from trade schools.
   The General Accounting Office found loan defaults in the
Supplemental Loans to Students (SLS) programs increased from $14
million in fiscal year 1987 to $40 million in 1988, and to $247
million in 1989.
   The amount of SLS loans doubled in that time, the GAO said in a
report released Thursday.
   ``Students attending proprietary (profit-making) schools
generally have higher default rates. These figures are not
dissimilar to what we have seen with the other student aid
programs,'' William Gainer, director of education and employment
for the GAO.
   Gainer said more than $3.2 billion in the Supplemental Loans to
Students (SLS) program have been guaranteed by nine lenders _
mainly banks, credit unions and savings and loan associations _ in
the last three years.
   Students defaulted on $310.6 million during that period, the
nine agencies reported.
   The SLS program, enacted in 1986, provides market-rate loans.
Higher education students are eligible for an SLS loan, after first
meeting more stringent eligibility requirements of other
government-guaranteed loans, such as Pell grants and Stafford
loans, formerly called guaranteed student loans.
   Although the main purpose of the loan is to supplement other
aid, Gainer said the audit found 419,434 student borrowers received
only SLS loans during the three years compared to 673,458 who
received both SLS and Stafford loans.
   Sen. Edward Kennedy, D-Mass., and Rep. Pat Williams, D-Mont.,
requested the GAO study.
   Under the SLS program, graduate students and those
undergraduates responsible for their own financial support are
allowed to borrow up to $4,000 per year, to a maximum of $20,000.
Unlike the Stafford loans and Pell grants, eligibility is not based
on a borrowers' financial resources.
   SLS loans have variable interest rates, adjusted annually
according to Treasury Department borrowing rates. Repayment must
generally begin within 60 days of the last loan disbursement for
each year a loan is received.
   According to the Education Department, the loan volume increased
from $564 million in the 1987 fiscal year to $1.347 billion in the
1988 fiscal year, and dropped slightly to $1.294 billion in 1989.
   The amount of loans to proprietary or trade school borrowers
increased from 55 percent to about 60 percent from the 1987 to 1989
fiscal years, the GAO found. At the same time, the amount of loans
to freshmen borrowers increased from 40 percent of SLS loans 1987
to about 63 percent in the fiscal year that ended Sept. 30.
   Loan defaults from freshmen increased from 12 percent of all
defaults in 1987 to 85 percent in 1989.
   Similarly, defaults from proprietary school borrowers increased
from 12 percent of SLS loan defaults in 1987 to 86 percent in 1989.
</TEXT>
