<FIRST>r a PM-SFQuake-880History     10-20 0593</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SF Quake-880 History,0611</SECOND>
<HEAD>Collapsed Freeway Had History of Minor Problems, Some Repairs</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-SF Quake Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDAN RILEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 32-year-old Oakland freeway
reduced to dust and debris by this week's earthquake had a history
of minor problems, including some that weren't fixed promptly,
according to state inspection reports.
   The California Transportation Department reports, made available
Thursday, include one from 1966 describing a sagging road deck that
made it difficult for drivers to control cars.
   A 1961 report talked of ``above-average cracks'' in several deck
sections and a 1980 report suggested about $455,000 worth of
repairs such as resealing joints and replacing expansion beams. The
work wasn't immediately done and was suggested again in a 1983
report.
   Other problems ranged from hairline cracks and clogged drains to
auto damage to rails, flaking concrete, bent spans and a cracked
girder.
   ``(But) there was no problem of structural failure at all,''
state Transportation Director Robert Best said of the reports.
   Best also said engineers delayed strengthening the section of
freeway because they believed it would survive a major quake.
   ``We didn't know 10 years ago this was subject to this type of
earthquake damage. We did not know there was any possibility it
would collapse,'' he said.
   Best said he was unaware of a private engineer's report from
1975 saying that the section of Interstate 880 that collapsed had
an outdated design that made it vulnerable to such quakes.
   ``I've been assured there were no experts, no studies, no data
that suggested in any way that it would fall,'' Best said.
   A 1\-mile-long stretch of the two-tiered interstate, also called
the Nimitz Freeway, collapsed in Tuesday's earthquake. An upper
section of the San Francisco-Oakland Bay Bridge also collapsed.
   Gov. George Deukmejian has called for an immediate investigation
of I-880's collapse. A commission of bridge engineers is being set
up to determine why the structure fell and what can be done to
prevent such tragedies, Best said.
   Engineer J. David Rogers said he determined in his 1975 study
that the structure wouldn't survive a major earthquake. And he said
the information was presented to state transportation officials at
that time.
   Best said it is irresponsible to suggest the state knew the
structure would collapse. He said it's possible there were
``unusual subsurface conditions that we didn't know about'' that
could have contributed to the collapse. The highway was built on
fill dirt.
   Rogers blamed the collapse on wood-fiber expansion joints on the
columns that held up the highway, The Washington Post reported
today.
   Asked why the late designer of the highway, F.W. Panhorst, used
the joints, Rogers said: ``God only knows. ... It creates a
tremendous weakness position for the columns.''
   The failed structure had undergone only the first phase of a
three-step program to reinforce California's roadways.
   Work on I-880 began in 1977 and was the first improvement since
the highway was designed in 1954 and constructed in 1957.
   But the work on I-880 and other roads with double-column
supports was deferred while officials focused on phase two, shoring
up single-column elevated roadways.
   The third phase, now under way, calls for research with the
University of California to figure out how to strengthen
multiple-column supports of multi-level elevated highways.
   Officials maintained that I-880 was not neglected or given too
low a priority in the project.
   However, John Kariotis, a South Pasadena structural engineer who
studies earthquakes, said the state could have ``colossally
reduced'' the danger by sheathing the columns in steel jackets,
according to the Post.
</TEXT>
