<FIRST>r a PM-SpyCase     10-20 0473</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Spy Case,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Spy Case Going Before Grand Jury</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal grand jury will hear the
government's case against a former military communications officer
who claims he sought to aid the United States when he allegedly
gave classified information to the Soviets.
   Magistrate W. Curtis Sewell ordered Frank Nesbitt, 44, held
without bail Thursday. FBI agents arrested Nesbitt last week at a
hotel in McLean, Va., and charged him with delivering and
attempting to deliver unauthorized information to Soviet agents.
   Nesbitt's court-appointed attorney, Gregory English, told
reporters his client, a former Marine and Air Force communications
officer, ``felt it was a chance to benefit the United States'' and
``wanted to have some excitement in his life.''
   The government's only witness, FBI Special Agent Lizzie Cassell,
testified about conversations she had with Nesbitt starting Oct. 4.
in which he told her about passing information, later determined by
the National Security Agency to be classified, to the Soviets.
   Ms. Cassell said Nesbitt came to the FBI office in Washington,
D.C., accompanied by an official from the U.S. Embassy in
Guatemala, to tell his story.
   According to the agent, Nesbitt left his wife and two children
near Memphis, Tenn., last June. Leaving behind a note Ms. Cassell
said read, ``Don't look for me, I'm gone,'' Nesbitt began an
odyssey that took him from Central and South America to the Soviet
Union and back to Guatemala.
   Ms. Cassell said Nesbitt told her he met by happenstance a
Soviet official, Feodor Temoyev, during his travels in Bolivia. The
Soviet made arrangements for a trip for Nesbitt to the Soviet Union.
   ``He stated to me he had defected,'' Ms. Cassell told the court.
   She said Nesbitt gave classified communications intelligence
information to the Soviets during his 10-day stay in Moscow and
also provided Soviet agents with diagrams and charts.
   English said his client believed the information he passed on
was unclassified and argued there was no intent to harm the U.S.
government. He said Nesbitt also had broached the idea of working
as a double agent when he voluntarily went to the FBI.
   Nesbitt served from 1963 to 1966 in the Air Force's Electronic
Security Command in West Germany and from 1969 to 1979 in the
Marine Corps, where he dealt with classified
communication-gathering. He also worked at the Los Alamos National
Laboratories from 1983 to 1984. He had top secret code word
clearance in all his jobs.
   Ms. Cassell said Nesbitt told her he was paid $2,000 for the
information he provided to the Soviets and would receive up to
$100,000 if he would return to the Los Alamos plant and obtain
other secrets. She said Nesbitt agreed.
   Nesbitt faces a minimum sentence of 30 years in prison and a
maximum of a life sentence if convicted.
</TEXT>
