<FIRST>r a PM-SFQuake-Taxes     10-20 0343</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SF Quake-Taxes,0355</SECOND>
<HEAD>Calif. Assembly Speaker Calls for Tax; Governor Wouldn't Oppose</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-SF Quake Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some legislative leaders have proposed
special taxes to pay for earthquake damage, and Gov. George
Deukmejian said he may support a new levy.
   ``If we don't have enough (money) in terms of what we have on
hand, I have not ruled out the possibility of a tax increase to
raise whatever funds necessary to bring the communities back to
normal,'' Deukmejian told reporters Thursday while touring badly
damaged Santa Cruz.
   The state has an emergency reserve fund of just over $1 billion
that can be spent without legislative approval.
   Tuesday's earthquake has caused well over $4 billion in damage,
according to the state. Some private economists say it may reach
$10 billion.
   Assembly Speaker Willie Brown, a Democrat from San Francisco,
has said he would prefer a short-term increase in the gasoline or
sales tax to pay for quake repairs.
   ``I don't really think we should be relying on the budget
reserve to rebuild the Bay Bridge or the freeway,'' he said of the
collapsed Nimitz Freeway in Oakland.
   Brown met Thursday with 17 Bay area-legislators, some of whom
had their own ideas about how to raise earthquake repair money.
   Assemblyman Dick Floyd said there should be a one-year,
25-cent-per-gallon gasoline tax surcharge to raise $3.5 billion to
help repair the damage and to strengthen bridges, overpasses and
elevated highways statewide.
   Deukmejian, a Republican, was scheduled to meet legislative
leaders _ including Brown _ on Monday.
   The governor said there is precedent for a special tax. He said
motor fuel taxes have at times been raised to pay for roads damaged
in natural disasters.
   He said a special legislative session _ which only he could call
_ would be required.
   The 17 legislators who met Thursday with Brown agreed
unanimously to a special session and said transportation and
housing needs should be the top priorities.
   The lawmakers ended their regular 1989 session in September and
are not due to return until January.
</TEXT>
