<FIRST>r w PM-US-Baltics     10-20 0648</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Baltics,640</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Mulling Response to Major Political Moves in Baltics</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<NOTE>Associated Press Writer</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. government is considering how to
respond if the Kremlin cracks down on freedom movements in the
Baltic republics or if those states gain independence from the
Soviet Union, says a senior State Department official.
   The United States has never recognized Soviet annexation of
Lithuania, Latvia and Estonia, which were occupied by the Red Army
during World War II, and that policy has come under new scrutiny
with the upsurge of independence movements there.
   ``Our basic policy of non-recognition has not changed and it is
not going to change,'' Deputy Assistant Secretary of State James F.
Dobbins testified Thursday before the congressional Commission on
Peace and Security in Europe.
   Activists in the Baltic republics, encouraged by the reforms of
Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev, have been campaigning for more
independence, but have drawn sharp warnings from Gorbachev and
other Kremlin officials.
   ``We are going to have to develop well-considered administration
responses to this,'' Dobbins said. ``Many of us who have not been
experts on the Baltic republics are becoming Baltic experts.''
   Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze assured Secretary
of State James A. Baker III at their meeting in Wyoming last month
that the Kremlin would not use force against the Baltic
independence movements.
   However, a private attorney told the congressional panel on
Thursday the approach by the U.S. and other Western governments was
too timid and disorganized to ensure a peaceful solution.
   ``Western statesmen have reacted to the resurgence of peaceful,
democratic, Baltic mass movements with nervous confusion and
anxiety,'' testified William Hough, a New York attorney.
   ``Not one Western state, to my knowledge, has ever proposed a
plan for independence for the Baltic states or proposed a peaceful
diplomatic solution for the Baltic region that would take into
account the security interests of nation's of East-Central Europe,
including the U.S.S.R,'' said Hough.
   Arvydas Juozaitis, a leader of Lithuania's Sajudis popular
front, told The Associated Press recently that his movement expects
to win a 80 percent majority in elections scheduled for next
February in Lithuania, one of 15 Soviet republics.
   One of the first acts of the Lithuanian parliament will be to
dissolve itself and vote to form a new government, independent of
the Soviet Union, Juozaitis said.
   Lithuania would then seek to establish ties with Moscow on the
basis of a 1939 treaty which affirms Lithuanian independence but
allows the Soviet Union to maintain military bases in the republic.
   ``To achieve some agreement with Moscow, we will agree that
Soviet troops can remain in Lithuania,'' Juozaitis said.
   Asked whether there was any flexibility in the Sajudis position,
Juozaitis said: ``I suppose. A lot of maneuvering can occur in the
nearest future, before the Lithuanian Soviet sits.''
   ``We are not expecting that the Soviets would use force before a
radical decision is taken. They have no argument for using force
before a decision is taken,'' he said.
   ``One of our most decisive tasks is to win time. If we win a
month, we are happy because there are big changes every month,'' he
said.
   The Bush administration favors democratic elections to ``allow
the Baltic peoples do decide these questions themselves,'' Dobbins
told the congressional panel headed by Rep. Steny Hoyer, D-Md.
   ``We, the administration and other governments, have to consider
how we can best promote that process,'' he said. ``We are prepared
to respect and enthusiastically support whatever the results of the
process of self-determination are.''
   The congressional panel underscored U.S. support for Baltic
independence by hearing testimony from the heads of the Estonian,
Latvian and Lithuanian legations, who represent their governments
in exile.
   It was the first time in 35 years the emigre missions had
testified before Congress, said the legation heads, Stasys
Lozoraitis of Lithuania, Anatol Dinbergs of Latvia and Ernst
Jaakson of Estonia.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
