<FIRST>r a PM-SFQuake-Mianus     10-20 0545</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SF Quake-Mianus,0559</SECOND>
<HEAD>Connecticut Bridge Project May Figure in Quake Rebuilding</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-SF Quake, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEAN GOLEMBESKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lessons learned in a 1983 Connecticut
bridge disaster could provide a blueprint for engineers seeking to
rebuild a collapsed section of the San Francisco-Oakland Bay
Bridge, officials say.
   The engineers who designed a temporary span on the Mianus River
bridge on Interstate 95 are suddenly in demand, as are hundreds of
structural engineers around the country who could reap a windfall
from the San Francisco earthquake.
   Clem Zawodiak, director of the Connecticut Department of
Transportation, said Thursday that the Army Corps of Engineers had
asked for the names of contractors and equipment used in the
reconstruction of the Mianus bridge.
   A three-lane section of southbound I-95 collapsed on June 28,
1983, killing three people. The accident was blamed on a failed
hanger system that supported the bridge's steel girders.
   The highway is a major transportation link between Connecticut
and New York City and is used daily by thousands of commuters.
   A two-lane, temporary span once described as ``a giant Erector
set'' was built over the gaping hole in the interstate in 22 days.
On July 22, 1983, the temporary span was opened to light traffic.
   While the temporary bridge was in place, crews worked below to
construct three new, permanent lanes. It was the first time such a
procedure was used to rebuild a bridge. The reconstructed bridge
was opened to traffic in January 1984.
   In San Francisco, a 50-foot, five-lane section of the upper deck
of the Bay Bridge collapsed onto the lower deck during Tuesday's
earthquake. The collapse has closed a vital link for those
commuting between San Francisco and Oakland.
   Zawodniak said California transportation officials could
construct a temporary span similar to the one used on the Mianus
bridge. However, because the Bay Bridge has two levels, he said, he
wasn't sure if construction could take place while the temporary
span was in place.
   The earthquake, which also caused the collapse of a 1\-mile
stretch of Interstate 880 in Oakland, has drawn hundreds of
structural engineers to Northern California.
   The engineers _ most of whom are government employees, but some
of whom are private contractors _ are crawling around buildings,
elevators, dams, highways, bridges, pipelines and other structures
that might have suffered damage.
   Bill Killeen, vice president of engineering for Acrow Corp. of
America, which built the temporary Mianus River span, said his
company has contacted California transportation officials. But he
declined to say whether his company might become involved in
reparing the Bay Bridge.
   ``We're sharing ideas with the state,'' Killeen said.
   Acrow's bridges use a series of 10-by-5-foot panels connected in
rows to form trusses. Beams are placed between them to form a
bridge deck. In addition to Mianus, the technology was used to
erect temporary bridges in Washington state in the wake of the
Mount St. Helen's volcano in 1980.
   Peter Shugert, spokesman for the Army Corps of Engineers in New
York, said the corps solicited information about Mianus as a
courtesy to California officials. Corps engineers said they didn't
know if the Mianus technology would be applied to the Bay bridge.
   ``We were looking for anything that would help them,'' Shugert
said.
</TEXT>
