<FIRST>u a PM-SFQuake-Homeless Bjt   10-20 0661</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SF Quake-Homeless, Bjt,0678</SECOND>
<HEAD>Quake Fallout: Homeless Find Barest Essentials in Emergency Shelters</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT DVORCHAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP National Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For Goldie Pennington, the earthquake was
like an intruder who robbed her of her most precious worldly
possession: the place where she and her family lived.
   ``It was like somebody took everything I had and threw me out in
the streets,'' said Mrs. Pennington, 47, lying on a Red Cross cot
and keeping a watchful eye on two grandchildren at an emergency
shelter.
   ``At least we have a roof over our heads and food to eat. You
can always start over.'' Mrs. Pennington said. ``The unexpected can
happen to anybody, rich or poor.''
   The woman, her three children and two grandchildren were unable
to stay in their city apartment because the earthquake split open
walls and caused other damage. She stayed with a friend for two
nights before checking into the shelter set up at the Moscone
Convention Center.
   In the city, 2,555 people are staying in three Red Cross
shelters. Ten thousand people were left homeless in Santa Cruz
County, according to the state Office of Emergency Preparedness.
Most are staying with relatives or in hotels instead of in shelters.
   Life for the newly homeless consists of bare essentials: donated
meals, bottled water, restrooms, a cot and a blanket or sleeping
bag.
   Among the few frills were puppet shows for the kids, donated
stuffed animals, chalkboards, jigsaw puzzles, playing cards and an
occasional television. The Red Cross dispensed toothbrushes and
other toiletries.
   The Moscone Center was supposed to have greeted delegates of the
Water Pollution Control Federation before Tuesday's quake hit.
Instead of exhibitors, about 90 families were housed in one hall.
Other cots were crammed under escalators and in the crannies of the
lobby.
   ``People still don't feel safe outside. It's better to be here
than to be alone,'' said shelter manager Bob Puett.
   The shelter people were a motley bunch, thrown together by
chance and circumstance. Those displaced by the quake bunked with
the city's considerable homeless population who didn't have places
to lose.
   As a way to beat the monotony, Chris Buell worked as a
volunteer, helping people set up their cots, showing them locations
of restrooms and offering a reassuring hand.
   ``Everything I have is gone. It's history. I'm still walking
around in a daze,'' said Buell, 28, a professional boxer who
escaped from his apartment in the Marina district with the clothes
on his back and $5 in his pocket.
   ``I'm stuck right now, so I might as well be helping people,''
Buell said.
   The Red Cross offered snacks, juice, fruit and coffee. It also
provided disposable diapers and baby food for fidgety infants such
as 11-month-old Hannah Watson, who was nursed by her mother, Terri.
   ``It seems like a nightmare,'' said Mrs. Watson, 29, whose
apartment had a big crack in the ceiling and was uninhabitable.
``The first feeling was how it seemed like we were cut off from the
rest of the world. I just feel so helpless.''
   In the middle of the room, Blanca Manzanero entertained her
three daughters with donated dolls and playthings. The woman drove
into the city to see her lawyer and was trapped when a section of
the Bay Bridge collapsed.
   She still hasn't built up the nerve to try driving 30 milies
home to Vallejo, where her husband is staying.
   ``I'm so afraid the freeway has a big hole in it. I want to wait
until it's safe,'' Mrs. Manzanero said. ``It's better to stay here.
It's the safest place for me.''
   In the fashionable Marina district, 500 families are bunking at
the Marina Middle School. John and Linda Reda tossed what they
could into the back of their blue Volvo station wagon and headed
for the shelter.
   ``I just wanted to have my family albums. They're all my
memories. You can rebuild a house,'' said Mrs. Reda, who is five
months pregnant.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
