<FIRST>r a PM-ChurchConfession     10-20 0346</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Church Confession,0356</SECOND>
<HEAD>Clergy Who Heard Confession of Robber Called to Testify</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERKELEY SPRINGS, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three ministers called to testify
against a man who confessed during a church service to robbing his
uncle's store are claiming that requirement would violate their
right to freedom of religion.
   ``We're not in the business of putting people in jail. We're in
the business of repenting them,'' Shirley Hiles, one of the
ministers at the Word of Deliverance Church, said Thursday.
   Morgan County Judge Thomas Steptoe Jr. on Monday refused to
quash a subpoena for Mrs. Hiles, 50; her husband, Jack Hiles, 50;
and Wilda Maconaughay, 54.
   They were subpoenaed to testify in the trial of Larry Yost, who
is charged with breaking and entering. Steptoe postponed the trial
until Dec. 5 to give the ministers time to appeal.
   At an evening service during Christmas week last year, Yost
stood up before 45 members of the congregation and said he had
broken into his uncle's store. Yost was arrested in January and has
been in jail since on $25,000 bail.
   Yost allegedly stole $3,700 worth of material from Yost Building
Supply Inc.
   The ministers, whose church advocates the public confession of
sins, said their jail ministry program has been hurt because
inmates are afraid that what they say will be used against them.
   ``This will stop the function of our church,'' Mrs. Hiles said.
``We might as well close the doors because people won't be able to
be born again.''
   ``I've heard many public confessions from all kinds of good
people who have repented,'' her husband said. ``A lot of them could
have been dragged into court, but they became good people again,
valuable people.''
   If convicted, Yost could be sentenced to life in prison without
parole under the state's repeat offender law because he has two
previous convictions.
   In 1986, Yost and two other inmates broke out of the Morgan
County Jail, broke into a bar across the street and stole a keg of
beer, which they carried back to their cells and had a party.
</TEXT>
