<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-89 0347EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Blacks-Study     10-20 0477</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Blacks-Study,0492</SECOND>
<HEAD>Study on Blacks By Blacks Looks Behind the Trends</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANA KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A study by black researchers into the plight of
black Americans provides more insight and policy recommendations
than a far more expensive report conducted mostly by whites, says a
sponsor of the new study.
   ``Historically, blacks have been treated as objects of study,
rather than as major participants in conducting a study,'' said
Wornie Reed, director of the William Monroe Trotter Institute for
the Study of Black Culture at the University of Massachusetts at
Boston.
   ``Many studies say black people are unemployed,'' he said. ``We
looked at why they're unemployed.''
   The study, a summary volume of which was released Thursday, was
commissioned by the Trotter Institute and cost about $100,000.
   ``Race continues to matter,'' according to the report.
``Discrimination persists, although its forms have altered.''
   The study, titled ``Assessment of the Status of
African-Americans,'' was conducted by academics around the country
in response to another, controversial study of blacks by the
National Research Council released last summer that was conducted
mostly by whites at a cost of $2 million.
   That study, called ``A Common Destiny: Blacks and American
Society,'' found that blacks made great strides in the last 50
years but were losing ground in such areas as economic and
educational status. At the time the National Research Council study
was announced in 1984, some black scholars protested their omission
from the study.
   Reed acknowledged Thursday that the basic findings of the
Trotter study did not differ greatly from the previous report. He
said he believes some of the protests by black scholars may have
contributed to the ``fairness'' of the National Research Council
study. But he said the Trotter report questioned how society
contributes to the status of blacks today.
   ``They talked about cultural poverty but we go even further to
explain why there is such a problem and make policy
recommendations,'' said Reed.
   The Trotter report calls for more federal assistance to black
students, strengthening black families and stimulating economic
growth, expanding child care and other federal aid programs, bail
reform, cultural sensitivity training for judges and others in the
criminal justice system and recruiting more blacks for the health
professions.
   The report found that racial discrimination impedes blacks'
access to health care, higher education and jobs and is present in
the criminal justice system.
   Among the specific findings:
   _ During 1985 and 1986, life expectancy for blacks dropped, the
first consecutive decline this century. The average life expectancy
for blacks dropped to 69.4 years in 1986, while whites increased to
an all-time high of 75 years.
   _ In 1984, the average black family had a net worth of $3,400,
compared with $39,000 for a white family.
   _ Minority youths are imprisoned three to four times more than
white youths and receive stiffer sentences.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
