<FIRST>r a PM-CursedConcert     10-20 0215</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cursed Concert,0220</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jinxed Piano Music is Performed _ Finally</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUBURN, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Liszt piano variation linked to misfortune
and death for more than 150 years was presented by a set of twins _
this time, without a hitch.
   The 800-member audience rose to its feet Thursday night to
applaud the performance by John and Richard Contiguglia of Franz
Liszt's ``Great Concert Piece on Mendelssohn's `Songs Without
Words.''' The 52-year-old twins are credited with discovering the
piece in 1973.
   Liszt, the Hungarian composer, wrote the variation on
Mendelssohn's music in 1835. He collapsed at the keyboard during
the premiere of the piece that year.
   The Contiguglias, who hail from this central New York town but
live in New York City, were scheduled to play the music Saturday
night, but the concert was canceled when a violent thunderstorm
plunged the East Middle School auditorium into darkness.
   Pianist Ferrucio Busone died shortly before a performance of the
piece in 1924.
   In 1986, the Contiguglia brothers planned to perform it at a
Liszt festival in Holland, but the Dutch government seized the
sheet music, claiming it held a coded spy message being passed from
East Germany to the West.
   ``It's uncanny how many times something has prevented this song
from being played,'' Richard Contiguglia said.
</TEXT>
