<FIRST>r a PM-JamieFiske     10-20 0261</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Jamie Fiske,0268</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jamie Fiske Discharged; Cause of Bleeding Still Uncertain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 7-year-old girl whose need for a new liver
as an infant helped spur the nation's organ transplant policy has
been discharged from the University of Minnesota Hospital.
   She left Thursday afternoon, though doctors remained unsure what
caused a bout of internal bleeding. She will stay in the area with
her parents at least until the middle of next week, hospital
spokeswoman Mary Stanik said.
   Doctors on Oct. 9 removed the youngster's enlarged spleen in the
belief that it had caused three bouts of internal bleeding within a
month. She was discharged on Saturday, but was readmitted the
following day when she suffered more bleeding several hours after
leaving the hospital.
   Stanik said Jamie has had no more bleeding since re-entering the
hospital.
   Jamie was born Nov. 26, 1981, with biliary atresia, a condition
in which the liver's bile ducts are blocked.
   She received a liver at the University of Minnesota in 1982 a
few days after her father, Charles Fiske, made a televised appeal
for a donor during a convention at the American Academy of
Pediatricians.
   Doctors during the spleen removal surgery were able to examine
Jamie's liver, and said it and her other organs were normal. Stanik
said doctors do not think the liver has anything to do with the
girl's current problems.
   Stanik said Jamie's spirits are good, although she still hopes
to return to her Bridgewater, Mass., home in time for Halloween.
   ``She seems to be handling things quite well,'' Stanik said.
</TEXT>
