<FIRST>r a PM-BollesGrandJury     10-20 0317</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bolles Grand Jury,0323</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Reopens Probe Into Reporter's Death, Sources Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY LOPEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state grand jury has subpoenaed witnesses in
Arizona and other states in a new investigation into the 1976
car-bomb slaying of investigative reporter Don Bolles, sources said.
   Among those subpoenaed, sources familiar with the investigation
told The Associated Press on Thursday, was Phoenix attorney Neal
Roberts, a figure in the original Bolles investigation.
   The sources demanded anonymity, saying they feared prosecution
under an Arizona law making it a crime to disclose grand jury
matters.
   Roberts, 60, did not return a call from the AP but was quoted in
today's editions of The Arizona Republic as confirming that he had
been served with the subpoena by aides to Attorney General Bob
Corbin.
   The newspaper said Ben Funk, a St. Louis hotel clerk and member
of a racing family that had clashed with Bolles, also confirmed he
had been subpoenaed.
   Corbin, who has been coming under pressure over the Bolles
murder, declined comment on the grand jury probe but confirmed that
his office had been working on the Bolles case for more than a year.
   Bolles, an investigative reporter for the Republic, was murdered
by a remote-controlled car bomb. The man convicted of planting the
bomb, racing dog owner John Harvey Adamson, is in prison, but no
mastermind has ever been convicted.
   Roberts arranged for Adamson to fly to Lake Havasu City a few
hours after the bombing. He was granted limited immunity in 1976
provided that he was not involved in planning or carrying out the
slaying and that he told all he knew about it.
   Bolles died 11 days after the June 1976 explosion. Before his
death he repeatedly said the word ``Emprise,'' an apparent
reference to a company later called Delaware North that was
partners with the Funk family in Arizona dog-racing interests.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
