<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-89 0435EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Mexico-Drugs     10-20 0415</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mexico-Drugs,0433</SECOND>
<HEAD>Medellin Drug Cartel Suspects Captured In Mexico</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD HERZFELDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Local Mexican officials may have given
protection to two Colombian drug-runners linked to the Medellin
cocaine cartel and arrested in the southern Yucatan, federal police
say.
   Federal officials on Thursday announced their capture of the
nephews of two major Colombian drug kingpins, saying they had
broken up a ring that flew cocaine into Mexico and shipped it by
boat to Florida.
   The Colombians and eight other men were captured Sunday at a
clandestine airstrip in the Yucatan peninsula, said federal police
commander Fausto Valverde, head of the narcotics interdiction
forces.
   ``We imagine they made an arrangement for protection,'' Valverde
said. He said police were investigating the matter.
   Two other men were captured in the resort city of Cancun,
Valverde said.
   Authorities said they waited to announce the arrests because
they had hoped to capture more accomplices. They said they were
searching for another Colombian suspect.
   Valverde also said that an airplane carrying drugs to Cancun
escaped when someone on the ground warned it by radio that Mexican
police were at the clandestine airstrip.
   Captured were ringleaders Luis Alfredo Aguilar Castro, a nephew
of Gonzalo Rodriguez Gacha, and Ricardo Isunza Ochoa, a nephew of
Fabio Ochoa, according to Valverde.
   Fabio Ochoa and Rodriguez Gacha, known as ``El Mexicano''
because of his interest in Mexican culture, are top members of the
Medellin cartel and are among the world's most-wanted drug
traffickers.
   Valverde said Aguilar and Isunza Ochoa were their uncles' direct
representatives in the smuggling operation.
   He said he did not know whether the two were wanted in Colombia
or the United States on drug-related charges. Asked whether the two
might be extradited to the United States, Valverde answered,
``Anything is possible.''
   Commander Miguel Rodriguez Lorrabaquio said the group brought
cocaine from Colombia by air to Mexico, then shipped it by boat to
the United States, usually to Florida.
   Colombia's Medellin and Cali cocaine cartels account for an
estimated 80 percent of cocaine shipped to the United States.
   Traffickers in that South American country have operated with
relative impunity over the years by intimidating or paying off
judges.
   But on Aug. 19 the Colombian government declared war against
cocaine barons after traffickers assassinated the country's leading
presidential candidate. That included seizing the property of
alleged traffickers and reinstating an extradition treaty with the
United States.
   In response, cocaine barons began a bombing and terror campaign
in Colombia.
</TEXT>
