<FIRST>r i PM-China-Prostitution     10-20 0291</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Prostitution,0299</SECOND>
<HEAD>Beijing Plans Strict Punishment For Prostitution</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Beijing lawmakers have called for jails to be
built to house prostitutes and severe punishment, including the
death sentence, for anyone who induces or coerces women into
prostitution.
   The official Xinhua News Agency said today the municipal
government was discussing a draft bill to give the capital its
first anti-prostitution statutes.
   It quoted Liu Changyi, deputy director of the Beijing Public
Security Bureau, as saying prostitution had re-emerged in the city
and evolved fairly quickly since the early 1980s.
   Liu gave no figures except to say there were many more people
involved in prostitution now than in 1985, when there were about
100 cases.
   He that only four cases of syphilis and other sexually
transmitted diseases were discovered in 1984, compared to about
1,000 last year.
   The draft regulations call for the city to set up a penitentiary
for those involved in prostitution and enforce strict punishment,
including the death sentence, for procurers.
   Foreigners involved in prostitution will be punished according
to the law, and those with sexually transmitted diseases expelled
from the country, according to the regulations.
   The Communist government nearly succeeded in eliminating
prostitution after taking over in 1949, but the practice has
returned in recent years with the country's increased exposure to
the outside world.
   Prostitution has made its strongest comeback in Canton and other
cities of southern China that are influenced by neighboring Hong
Kong. Two Canton men were executed in 1987 for running a
prostitution ring.
   China has national laws against prostitution, but penalties are
generally light. According to a 1986 law, women caught selling
sexual favors are detained for less than 15 days or, in more
serious cases, sent to labor reform camps.
 
</TEXT>
