<FIRST>r a PM-SFQuake-SantaCruz     10-20 0564</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SF Quake-Santa Cruz,0579</SECOND>
<HEAD>Beach Town Picks up Pieces from Quake</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COLLEEN BARRY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA CRUZ, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Residents camped out today in this
earthquake-stricken beach town as workers faced repair jobs on
hundreds of damaged buildings and on a ruptured sewer line that
leaked effluent into Monterey Bay.
   Six people were killed following Tuesday's quake and the Santa
Cruz County emergency services office estimated 10,000 of the
county's 229,000 residents were displaced.
   One of the dead was Robin Ortiz, whose body was found Thursday
in the rubble of Santa Cruz Coffee Roasting Co. Thirty people had
kept a vigil since Tuesday's quake. Five were arrested late
Wednesday when they broke through a barricade after learning rescue
efforts were suspended for the night, police said.
   County officials estimated that Santa Cruz, on the north end of
Monterey Bay 90 miles south of San Francisco, sustained $350
million damage and unincorporated county areas sustained $400
million damage.
   President Bush was scheduled to make an inspection tour today.
   Many of the newly homeless lived in the 250 homes destroyed
Tuesday and the rest were ``people afraid to go in their houses,
who don't have any water or don't have any electricity,'' said
county spokeswoman Dinah Phillips.
   Power was restored to all but 3,600 customers in the county and
water was fit to drink in the city of Santa Cruz, population
50,000, and in much of the county by Thursday night, officials said.
   Aftershocks also caused problems. A 4.3 magnitude aftershock
triggered a landslide on Highway 17 Thursday afternoon,
guaranteeing that the primary route north to San Jose would remain
closed for another three weeks, a county spokeswoman said.
   The tremor also rocked a civic center shelter in downtown Santa
Cruz where nearly 200 people have been housed and some 3,000 fed
each day since the quake. Many others have been camping out.
   In the city, major damage occurred in the Pacific Garden Mall
business district and a residential area near marshy Neary Lagoon
where about 40 homes were destroyed. Communities to the north and
south also were damaged.
   Gov. George Deukmejian on Thursday surveyed damage to the
Pacific Garden Mall and promised local officials state aid.
   An estimated 30 percent of the businesses along the Pacific
Garden Mall will have to be razed. Unreinforced masonry structures
along an entire block of downtown Watsonville also must come down.
   Elsewhere, an unknown volume of sewage continued to leak into
Monterey Bay from ruptures in a county sewer line, closing beaches
in Santa Cruz.
   Authorities also continued to evacuate residents whose homes
were threatened by landslides or destroyed by the quake near
Boulder Creek and the Blue Ridge area in mountains north of Santa
Cruz.
   Despite the widespread damage, residents began resuming routine
as businesses slowly continued to reopen, mostly on a limited basis.
   Business owners said it would be at least several days until
they could start getting reliable shipments over roads leading into
Santa Cruz, many of which were entirely or partially closed.
   Outside a shelter for the homeless, though, pictures drawn by
children showed some youngsters had hope for the future.
Ten-year-old Amanda Charnas of Santa Cruz drew the Earth, flowers
sprouting from a crack and a rainbow nearby.
   ``Because that's what I think it will look like when the cracks
are gone, I think there will be rainbows,'' Amanda said.
</TEXT>
