<FIRST>r a PM-AngelofDeath     10-20 0503</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Angel of Death,0521</SECOND>
<HEAD>Victim Says Angelo Told Him Injection Would Make Him Better</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAT MILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RIVERHEAD, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A nurse charged with poisoning at least
seven patients, four of them fatally, told one, ``This will make
you feel much better,'' before slipping him a paralyzing injection,
said the patient who survived.
   ``I couldn't move, I couldn't breathe,'' 75-year-old Gerolamo
Kucich testified Thursday. ``I was thinking, how long is it going
to last before I die?''
   Kucich was the first witness in the opening day of the murder
trial of Richard Angelo, 27.
   Angelo is charged with four counts of second-degree murder and
three counts of assault for allegedly administering lethal doses of
Pavulon, a muscle relaxant, to patients at Good Samaritan Hospital
in 1987. He worked at the hospital in the Long Island town of West
Islip for six months as a nurse.
   Prosecutor John Colins called Angelo ``a monster dressed in
nurse's whites'' and ``the living embodiment of your worst
nightmare.''
   Colins said Angelo first experimented on mice and then moved on
to ``terribly vulnerable human beings for his stated purposes of
improving his image and reputation.''
   Police say Angelo admitted in written and videotaped confessions
that he gave the injections to patients with the intention of
reviving them so he would look like a hero.
   Kucich testified that a bearded man in a white medical coat came
into his hospital room one day and asked him how he was feeling.
   The former patient said that when he responded, ``Not bad,'' the
man opened his coat, took out a needle and told him, ``This will
make you feel much better.''
   Angelo then injected the drug into his intravenous tube and left
the room, said Kucich.
   ``I became like dead,'' said Kucich.
   He managed to press the emergency alarm and his regular nurse,
Lauren Ball, came in and helped revive him.
   Kucich said he still couldn't talk or see moments later when he
heard Angelo return to the room. He gestured towards Angelo's
voice, hoping Mrs. Ball would catch on.
   According to Kucich, Mrs. Ball asked Angelo, ``What did you do?''
   Kucich said Angelo answered, ``Nothing,'' and left the room.
   Mrs. Ball was scheduled to testify today when the trial resumes.
   As Kucich spoke, Angelo sat at the defense table with his eyes
downcast. His parents, Alice and Joseph Angelo, retired
schoolteachers who recently moved to Florida, sat behind him.
   Kucich of Yugoslavia was visiting his children when he was
hospitalized for a heart attack in 1987. He returned for the trial.
   Twenty-two patients' bodies were exhumed during the
investigation. Pavulon poisoning was found in six bodies but could
be established as a cause of death in only four. The other two
cases resulted in assault charges against Angelo. The third assault
charge is for the attack on Kucich, the only known survivor.
   Angelo's attorney, Eric Naiburg, admitted that Angelo gave the
injections but he asked the jury to consider a lesser charge than
second-degree murder.
</TEXT>
