<FIRST>r a PM-SFQuake-Television     10-20 0506</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SF Quake-Television,0520</SECOND>
<HEAD>CBS's `48 Hours' Has Telling Finale</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dan Rather thought the ``48 Hours''
earthquake broadcast was going well enough. Then a disturbance
broke out off-camera, interrupting the live show.
   Designed to report the news both quickly and with a personal
spin, ``48 Hours'' was handed a perfect finale Thursday: Just a few
feet from the CBS cameras, the father of a man believed killed on
collapsed Interstate 880 was accusing the Oakland mayor of
negligent homicide.
   ``It was a telling moment,'' anchorman Rather said in an
interview after the show. ``It said a lot about fears and
frustrations and what happens to people in situations like this.
   ``When you talk about earthquake victims, you have to remember
that's one person at a time. What gets drowned out in a lot of
newscasts on a story like this is the story of one person. One
person like Mr. Rubi's son, up there in the wreckage.
   ``That's something I and a lot of other people can relate to.''
   Daniel Rubi assailed Mayor Lionel Wilson during an evening news
conference in front of Interstate 880, saying that Wilson ``was
directly responsible for my son's death.'' Rubi said his son Juan,
28, was killed because Wilson had failed to maintain the freeway.
The younger Rubi's body is not among those recovered from the
wreckage so far.
   The elder Rubi, profiled on ``48 Hours'' shortly before his
outburst, was taken from the scene in a police squad car but not
arrested, authorities said.
   For the weekly news magazine, the Rubi incident was an
unfortunate but nevertheless valuable break. Like the other
networks and media organizations swarming around the Bay area, CBS
News has labored to find fresh ways to tell a complex story.
   ``The first problem you have is getting on the air in the first
place,'' said Don DeCesare, vice president of news coverage for
CBS. He cited an array of logistical problems, from no telephones
to no on-site editing bays and a shortage of mobile broadcast
facilities.
   One danger of incorporating journalists themselves in the news
accounts and importing high-ticket anchors like Rather, NBC's Tom
Brokaw and ABC's Peter Jennings is that they can become as much a
part of the story as the story itself.
   Andrew Heyward, the executive producer of ``48 Hours,'' said the
arrival of the network stars was only a reflection of the story's
importance.
   ``There is an advantage for the anchor to be in the city _ it's
certainly better than in the studio,'' Heyward said.
   Yet when ABC's Jennings arrived at the scene, just the opposite
was true.
   Jennings pulled into the destroyed freeway scene on Wednesday
morning and, minutes later, delivered a live dispatch that
demonstrated the hazards of capturing the story both quickly and
accurately.
   Jennings said rescue workers had labored through the night to
save lives on the collapsed freeway.
   Anyone who had spent the early-morning hours there, however,
would have said very little happened after midnight.
</TEXT>
