<FIRST>r i PM-Czechoslovakia     10-20 0290</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Czechoslovakia,0298</SECOND>
<HEAD>Continuing Harassment Campaign, Cops Haul Off Activist Before Dawn</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police hauled a prominent human rights
campaigner from his Prague home before dawn today, holding him for
several hours one day after detaining 15 opposition activists in
another raid, an emigre source said.
   Jan Urban, a leading member of the Charter 77 human rights
movement and other pro-democracy groups, was taken from his home by
police at 5:30 a.m., said the source, who asked not to be
identified.
   Sources in Prague said Urban was released abouutu four hours
later after apparently being warned not to engage in further
dissident activity.
   Jiri Hajek, Czechoslovakia's foreign minister during the 1968
Prague Spring, was among those arrested Thursday and held for
several hours by police who raided a meeting the activists were
holding with international human rights campaigners. U.S. human
rights monitor Jeri Laber also was briefly detained.
   Police have made at least three other police raids on activists
over the past week.
   Czechoslovakia's Communist authorities, unlike their
counterparts in neighboring Hungary and Poland, have firmly
rejected dialogue with opposition groups who seek a more open
society.
   A wave of pro-democracy demonstrations in January has been
answered with carefully targeted harassment of leading activists
and the jailing of lesser known campaigners whose detention stirs
less protest at home and abroad.
   The current wave of harassment may be connected with the
upcoming Oct. 28 anniversary of Czechoslovakia's independence in
1918.
   Last year, about 5,000 peaceful demonstrators gathered at a
banned rally to mark the anniversary and were dispersed by police
using water cannon, tear gas, dogs and batons.
   The Communist party daily Rude Pravo has already warned that
anybody attending a similar rally this year could face prosecution.
</TEXT>
