<FIRST>r a PM-PhoneStrike     10-20 0278</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Phone Strike,0285</SECOND>
<HEAD>NYNEX, Phone Worker Unions Name Mediators</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Striking telephone workers and NYNEX Corp.
prepared to resume talks with the help of mediators aimed at ending
a 10-week-old strike.
   The first mediation meetings of the strike were to begin today,
New England Telephone announced.
   NYNEX is the parent company for New England Telephone and New
York Telephone, the companies that supply local phone service to
most consumers in Massachusetts, Rhode Island, Vermont, Maine and
New Hampshire and New York.
   The mediators were selected and approved by NYNEX; the
International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers, which represents
most strikers in New England; and the Communications Workers of
America, which represents most striking New York Telephone
employees.
   Malcolm Read Lovell Jr., a visiting professor of government and
business at George Washington University, will act as mediator for
the communication workers union and NYNEX.
   Donald White will act as mediator for the electrical workers
union and NYNEX. White is dean of the graduate School of Arts and
Sciences at Boston College.
   Workers walked off the job Aug. 6 after contract discussions
broke down over salary and health care issues. The CWA, which
represents 40,000 workers, and the IBEW, which represents 20,000
workers, struck over NYNEX's insistence that the workers pay up to
$1,500 a year in health care costs.
   The unions and NYNEX agreed last week to bring in impartial
mediators to help settle the dispute, but had been unable to agree
until Thursday on who to pick.
   Strikes beginning Aug. 6 at three other regional phone companies
around the country _ Ameritech, Pacific Telesis and Bell Atlantic _
were all settled by the end of August.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
