<HEAD>Prices Climb to $60 for Broadway Musicals</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Add another Lincoln to your Grant when in the
mood for a Broadway musical.
   Prices on Thursday went up $5 for ``Jerome Robbins' Broadway,''
which now is the highest-priced musical of the season at $60 for
best seats.
   The musical opened at the Imperial in February with a top
admission of $55.
   The new price follows the lead last month of ``Black and Blue''
and ``Me and My Girl,'' which had raised their prices to $55. Other
Broadway musicals soon matched those prices.
   ``The Merchant of Venice,'' starring film actor Dustin Hoffman,
will charge $55 _ the highest price ever for a non-musical _ for
orchestra and front mezzanine seats when it previews Dec. 4.
