<FIRST>r i PM-UN-Namibia     10-20 0273</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-UN-Namibia,0282</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jackson Says South Africa Trying To Rig Namibia Vote</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Rev. Jesse Jackson says South Africa
is trying to rig pre-independence elections in the territory
through a ``reign of terror.''
   The former presidential candidate made his remarks Thursday in
an appearance before the General Assembly's Fourth Committee, which
handles independence questions.
   Meanwhile, black African nations called for an urgent Security
Council meeting to condemn South Africa's administration in the
territory. U.N. officials said debate would probably begin early
next week.
   Jackson said South Africa was trying to rig the Nov. 7-11
elections to hurt the leading black nationalist party, the
South-West Africa People's Organization known as SWAPO.
   Jackson accused South Africa of promoting ``a reign of terror
taking part in Namibia today'' by keeping former Namibian commandos
and paramilitary police on the payroll but letting them act as
``armed vigilantes'' for anti-SWAPO parties.
   He also criticized the United Nations for not sending enough
peacekeepers to Namibia to prevent what he called ``a climate of
intimidation so as to make a free and fair election impossible.''
   The Security Council decided early this year to send only 4,650
military observers, rather than 7,500, as a cost-cutting move.
   Namibians are to vote for a constituent assembly to organize the
first independent, black majority-ruled government in the territory
of 1.3 million. The former German colony has been ruled by South
Africa since 1915.
   In December, South Africa signed accords with Angola and Cuba
agreeing to cooperate with a U.N. plan for Namibia's transition to
independence as Cuba withdraws its 50,000 troops from Angola.
</TEXT>
