<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-89 0714EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-BabySaved     10-20 0316</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Baby Saved,0323</SECOND>
<HEAD>Surgeons Deliver Baby from Dying Mother</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BETHESDA, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A surgical team at Suburban Hospital
delivered a baby boy from his dying mother about 30 minutes after
the woman suffered massive injuries in a traffic accident, hospital
officials said.
   Surgeons removed the infant by Caesarean section about 12:50
p.m. Thursday, a half-hour after the gravely injured mother, Ana
Hernandez, 27, had suffered cardiac arrest and stopped breathing, a
hospital spokesman said. Hernandez, who was in a two-car collision,
had been due to deliver the baby in about a week.
   ``You have to realize, when the mother's system shuts down, the
baby stops getting oxygen,'' said the spokesman, Michael Fortier.
``Obviously there's a lot of amazement, probably wonder, and a lot
of happiness'' that he survived.
   Dr. Ernest Hanowell, who helped deliver the child, called it
unusual that the baby survived in light of his mother's injuries.
Doctors were unable to restore Hernandez's breathing or make her
heart beat on its own, and she was pronounced dead about 45 minutes
after the birth.
   The baby boy, weighing about seven pounds, suffered ``oxygen
deprivation'' and was hospitalized in serious condition Thursday
night, officials said.
   ``It's extraordinary, but it's something we think about in
emergency medicine all the time,'' Dr. Hugh Hill, another trauma
surgeon, said of the emergency Caesarean section. ``It's something
we anticipate and we worry about it. It's one of those heroic
interventions we fear, yet hope will be successful.''
   Hill said surgeons did not have to choose between saving the
mother or the baby. Hernandez technically was not dead when she was
wheeled into the emergency room, Hanowell said, but she had
suffered massive internal injuries, ``and if no one was breathing
for her and pumping on her chest, she certainly would have been
dead.''
   Hernandez had no other children. Her husband was with her at the
hospital, officials said.
</TEXT>
