<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-89 0832EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r p PM-NYCMayoral     10-20 0500</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-NYC Mayoral,0514</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dinkins Unable to Explain Discrepancy in Valuing Stock Holdings</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   NEW YORK _ Democratic mayoral candidate David Dinkins says he's
not sure why he valued a cable TV company's stock at $1 million but
sold it to his son for a fraction of the sum, according to a
published report today.
   Dinkins told The New York Times in an interview Thursday that
when he learned that his stock in Inner City Broadcasting was worth
$1 million or more, he could not believe it.
   He said he learned of the estimate by company officials from his
secretary.
   ``The day the secretary says this is true, I thought it was
almost like a big joke,'' Dinkins recalled. ``I said, `Like, I'm a
millionaire.'''
   He said that to avoid a conflict of interest when he became
Manhattan borough president, he sold the shares to his son David
Jr. in 1986 for $58,000 _ a price he said he randomly picked
without consulting tax lawyers or accountants.
   The Democratic front-runner provided no explanation for the
different values placed on the stock, saying, ``It didn't seem to
matter much'' at the time.
   Asked what could have caused the discrepancy, he said, ``I
really don't know.''
   The true worth of Inner City's stock _ difficult to assess
because the company is privately held rather than publicly traded _
is important because Dinkins might owe gift taxes on its sale, say
tax experts and campaign aides for Dinkins' opponent, Rudolph
Giuliani.
   New York Newsday on Thursday quoted the general counsel of Inner
City as saying the stock in 1984 was conservatively worth $4,292
per share, or $2.5 million for Dinkins' 588 shares.
   But Dinkins said the company's general counsel, John Edmonds,
might have inflated the price of Inner City stock to obtain a loan,
Newsday said today.
   Edmonds told Newsday on Thursday he had not inflated the value
of the stock but could offer no explanation for the different
prices. ``I made that statement on my judgment based on what the
value was in my judgment. He's right and I'm right,'' Edmonds said.
   The Daily News reported Thursday that Dinkins' former secretary,
Raquel Vidal, said her boss had set the stock's value at ``$1.3
million or something like that'' when he submitted a sworn,
confidential report to Gov. Mario Cuomo.
   The report was submitted when Dinkins was a candidate for
director of the State Urban Development Corporation.
   ``Based on the publicly available information, it appears to me
that David Dinkins owes between $285,120 and $848,291 to the
federal government and as much as $195,626 more to the state,''
said Giuliani's campaign manager, Peter Powers, according to
today's New York Post and Daily News. Powers said he was a tax
lawyer.
   Dinkins said he was reviewing his tax forms and any liability he
might have.
   He accused Giuliani of ``gutter politics'' after the latter's
week of unrelenting criticism on Dinkins' handling of the stock
sale. He threatened to respond with negative attacks of his own.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
