<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-89 0854EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Poland-Economy     10-20 0500</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poland-Economy,0513</SECOND>
<HEAD>Production Drops in Key Government Sectors, Grows in Private Sector</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DRUSILLA MENAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Production fell in seven key sectors,
including food and steel, during the third quarter of 1989 while
prices and wages grew in an inflationary spiral, according to
another gloomy government report published today.
   The steel, chemical, paper, engineering, transport, food and
fodder industries produced less in the first nine months of the
year than during the same period of 1988, according to the main
statistical office known by its Polish initials GUS.
   At the same time, there was a 30 percent increase in production
from Poland's private sector, newly liberated from many government
regulations. But because the private sector accounts for only about
6 percent of the economy, the report said the growth there could
not balance the production decreases in government industries.
   There were better results from the government's power, mineral,
timber, electro-engineering, electronical, textile, clothing and
printing industries, the report said.
   Several factors have been blamed for the production drop:
outmoded factories; lack of production materials; factories not
paying suppliers for lack of payment from customers; and the flight
of workers to the private sector, black-market activities or to
work abroad, where they can earn more.
   Also, former Deputy Prime Minister Ireneusz Sekula told a
government committee this week that the former government erred in
its decision to freeze prices, which caused enterprises and private
farmers to cut back production.
   The government report is the key quarterly analysis of the
Polish economy, but it follows numerous other commentaries from the
new Solidarity-led government and from Poles themselves on the dire
state of finances.
   The government faces a budget deficit of about $2.3 billion, and
it could reach $4.4 billion by the end of the year without radical
cost-cutting steps.
   An oversupply of money has cleared store shelves of goods and
further driven up prices. The price of butter, for example, is up
more than 1,000 percent since August.
   Government controls had kept food prices artificially low. The
controls were lifted Aug. 1 as part of the transformation designed
to create a market-oriented economy.
   The economic report said food prices are now 300 percent to 400
percent higher than at the start of the year, while prices of other
goods were 200 percent to 300 percent higher.
   A monthly report for August put overall price increases at 50
percent for that month, which would translate into an annual rate
of 600 percent.
   Employment continued to decline in the five main branches of the
government-run economy, with the jobless rate rising from 2.6
percent in January to 5.4 percent in September.
   Workers have been reported to be abandoning their jobs in the
state industries for higher salaries in the private sector.
   Pay rates rose substantially in the five main branches of the
economy, from a monthly $42 in the first quarter to $99 in the
third quarter. By mid-October, the average overall salary was $114
a month.
</TEXT>
