<FIRST>r i PM-CommonwealthSummit     10-20 0426</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Commonwealth Summit,0438</SECOND>
<HEAD>Commonweath Leaders Disagree Over Proposed Environmental Fund</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KENNETH L. WHITING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Commonwealth leaders disagreed
today over whether they should invest $18 billion in a joint fund
to protect the environment.
   British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher opposed establishing a
Commonwealth fund, arguing that additional resources should be
channeled through the U.N. World Environmental program.
   Officials of the 49-nation Commonwealth, the association of
Britain and its former colonies, said several other leaders also
supported holding off on establishing the fund.
   After discussing the issue, the leaders left for a weekend
retreat at Langkawi Island, 210 miles from Kuala Lumpur. There,
they will consider both the final draft of an environmental
declaration and try to agree on a joint statement on South Africa,
the main issue dividing them.
   Armed police lined the road from the Langkawi Island airport to
the beach resort where the summit delegates will stay. Young
Malaysian women dressed in batik sarongs and white vests greeted
each head of government.
   Hotel workers in white uniforms lined up and, to the
accompaniment of guitars, broke into a version of ``Have You Ever
Seen The Rain?''
   Australian Prime Minister Bob Hawke said Thursday the leaders
will try to ``reach a concensus'' over the weekend on strategy
toward South Africa. His plan stipulates that the Commonwealth call
on international banks to tighten financial sanctions against South
Africa.
   Mrs. Thatcher, the sole opponent of sanctions, has argued that
South African President F.W. de Klerk's moves toward reform deserve
encouragement. During the morning debate on the environment, India
pushed its proposal for a ``planet protection fund,'' which it
first put forward at a summit of the Non-Aligned Nations in
Belgrade, Yugoslavia, last month.
   The aim of the fund would be to ``bring within the easy reach of
all countries, developed and developing, the technologies to combat
pollution and environmental degradation,'' India's statement said.
   New Zealand Prime Minister Geoffrey Palmer said leaders divided
into three groups: those who want a fund set up now; those who
oppose the fund; and those who support leaving open the possibility
of a fund in the future.
   ``The developing countries tend to say, `You must pay,' and the
developed countries say, `We are not going to pay,''' Palmer told a
news conference.
   Earlier, the summit host, Malayasian Prime Minister Mahathir
Mohamad, complained that developing countries were to blame for
pollution.
   But Commonwealth spokeswoman Patsy Robertson told reporters, ``I
think they agreed, developed and developing, that we are all
polluters, each in our own way.''
</TEXT>
