<FIRST>r a PM-PlannedParenthood     10-20 0323</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Planned Parenthood,0334</SECOND>
<HEAD>Planned Parenthood Announces Formation of Political Arm</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Planned Parenthood Federation of America has
announced the creation of a political arm that will lobby
legislators against abortion restrictions.
   Citing the recent Supreme Court ruling giving states more
authority to regulate abortion issues, organization president Faye
Wattleton announced the formation of the Planned Parenthood Action
Fund at a news conference Thursday opening the group's 66th annual
meeting.
   ``The Webster decision put women's access to abortion in grave
danger,'' Wattleton said. ``Webster left us with no other choice
but to become even more politically aggressive than we had been
before to ensure that the right to choose abortion remains secure.''
   The Action Fund's first-year budget of $1 million, which must be
raised separately from Planned Parenthood's regular funds, will
allow the national organization to expand its current lobbying and
political campaign activities nationwide, Wattleton said.
   Final tax status approval from the Internal Revenue Service is
expected in three to four months, she said.
   The change will not affect the existing organization, which will
retain its tax-exempt status that limits its spending to $250,000
on grass-roots campaigns in individual states and $1 million
nationally.
   Contributions to the new fund will not be tax deductible, but
donations to the parent organization still will be.
   The fund's initial effort will be a newspaper advertising and
direct-mail campaign targeting the voting records of at least a
dozen congressmen Planned Parenthood feels are a threat to abortion
rights, Wattleton said.
   More than 1,200 delegates are attending the annual convention,
which runs through Sunday.
   On the agenda is a debate among the organization's leadership
regarding whether it will direct efforts toward a constitutional
amendment protecting abortion rights. Wattleton predicted a
decision by Sunday.
   Also scheduled to make an appearance at the convention is Dr.
Etienne-Emile Baulieu, developer of the controversial abortion pill
RU 486, who will receive a scientific research award from the
organization.
</TEXT>
