<FIRST>r a PM-BrownAttacks     10-20 0301</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Brown Attacks,0309</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brown Cancels Black Social Events in Wake of Attacks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Brown University, acting in the wake of
attacks by blacks on white and Asian students, has canceled two
social events for tonight that would have been attended mainly by
black students.
   The school canceled Funk Night and a dance sponsored by Omega
Psi Phi, a black fraternity, said Robert Reichley, vice president
for university relations.
   He would not explain why officials canceled those events and not
others during the annual Parents' Weekend at the Ivy League school.
   ``Our intention is not to make every move public,'' he said
Thursday.
   Reichley said the university wants to make sure campus social
events are retricted to students so they are easier to supervise.
   There have been 19 reports of assaults or robberies on 22
students since classes began in September. At least 14 incidents
were assaults on white and Asian male students, who described their
attackers as black teen-agers who did not appear to be students,
Reichley said.
   Campus and Providence police have increased security efforts and
Brown President Vartan Gregorian, in a statement this week, said he
might ask for unspecified federal help. He said some of the attacks
appeared to be racially motivated.
   Troy Priest, a senior who is president of the Brown chapter of
the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People,
said he wanted to study the cancellation of the social events
before commenting.
   ``The way it has been applied may not be fair,'' Priest said.
``But I want to talk to the university officials first.''
   Reichley said the attacks had heightened tension on the campus
where racial and anti-homosexual graffiti was written on the walls
of a dormitory last spring. A march against violence is planned on
the campus Sunday night.
</TEXT>
