<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-89 0955EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-WindShear     10-20 0287</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wind Shear,0294</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jets Fly Through Wind Shear Despite Warnings</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Retransmitting to CORRECT summary line.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal report says four United Airlines jets
flew through a dangerous wind shear at Stapleton International
Airport last year when pilots either did not hear or misunderstood
a control tower warning.
   The report released Thursday by the General Accounting Office
said one jet canceled its approach, but four others went through
and eventually landed safely.
   ``Four commercial airline pilots from one airline flew into
microburst activity, despite prior warning by the controllers and
explicit airline policy to avoid microburst alert areas,'' the
report said. ``The crews either did not hear clearly or did not
know the meaning of the term `microburst alert.'''
   A microburst is produced when a downdraft of heavy air hits the
earth and causes winds to spread horizontally along the ground. A
plane going through one experiences a head wind, then a downdraft,
and finally a tailwind, which can cause a crash.
   The Stapleton microburst pushed winds in opposite directions at
92 miles an hour, officials said.
   ``They were lucky,'' said James Evans, a researcher with the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology, who has helped conduct tests
on the radar detecting the wind shifts.
   None of the four pilots who landed during the incident could
remember getting the alert, said Bob Ireland, who was staff
engineer with United's flight training center in Denver at the time.
   ``They flat didn't remember it. ... It was no wonder they didn't
hear it. That's a very, very busy time for pilots,'' he said.
   The GAO recommended in its report that controllers be required
to reroute air traffic when microbursts are detected, even if
pilots think it's safe.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891020-0090 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-89 1002EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Lebanon-Israel     10-20 0174</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon-Israel,0178</SECOND>
<HEAD>Norwegian Peacekeepers Clash with Israeli-backed Militia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TYRE, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Norwegian peacekeeping troops clashed today
with Israeli-backed militiamen who kidnapped a civilian in south
Lebanon, U.N. sources said.
   One source, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the
30-minute clash involved automatic rifles and rocket-propelled
grenades and occurred after the militiamen grabbed Lebanese citizen
Mohammed Adib Abdul-Hadi in the town of Shibaa.
   A six-man Norwegian patrol ``tried to prevent a force from the
South Lebanon Army militia from holding Abdul-Hadi against his
will. The SLA men opened fire at the Norwegian patrol and the
Norwegians returned fire,'' the source said.
   He said no casualties were reported in the clash, which ended
when the Lebanese force withdrew deep into the Israeli-controlled
zone in south Lebanon, taking the detained man with them.
   There were no injuries in the firefight.
   The 702-strong Norwegian battalion serves with the United
Nations Interim Force in Lebanon, which patrols a narrow buffer in
the southern provinces separating the zone Israel has controlled
since 1982 from the rest of Lebanon.
