<FIRST>u i PM-Pope-Poland     10-20 0446</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pope-Poland,0459</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pope Hails Changes in Poland in Meeting with Prime Minister</HEAD>
<HEAD>By VICTOR L. SIMPSON</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II embraced Prime Minister
Tadeusz Mazowiecki of Poland today and urged his countryman to
continue down the path of reform.
   Mazowiecki took office on Aug. 24 to become the first
non-Communist leader of a Soviet bloc nation. He thanked the pope
for supporting Poland's opposition movement ``during the difficult
years'' of government oppression.
   Mazowiecki, a Roman Catholic intellectual and old acquaintance
of the pope, made Rome his first foreign visit since his
appointment as prime minister.
   The pope called the 20-minute meeting ``historic.''
   In an emotional reunion, the two-men embraced outside the pope's
private library, the site of the closed-door talks. John Paul told
an aide there was no need for introductions.
   Later, Mazowiecki said the meeting was the ``crowning, the fruit
of the dialogue, of which today we see the results.''
   John Paul turned toward a Polish television crew and responded
in Polish, `We hope there's no turning back.''
   ``This is not possible,'' said Foreign Minister Krzystof
Kubiszewski.
   John Paul's return to Poland in June 1979, eight months after
his election to the papacy, helped spark demands for democracy that
led to the formation of Solidarity, the first non-Communist labor
movement in the Soviet bloc.
   During the dark years following the martial law crackdown of
1981, John Paul helped keep the Solidarity spirit alive, including
making a return to his homeland in 1983.
   The church, which has historically played a pivotal role in the
overwhelmingly Catholic country, took part in the long negotiations
that led to elections this year and approval of a 24-member Cabinet
that includes 12 Solidarity members and four Communists.
   Vatican spokesman Joaquin Navarro quoted some words from the
pope t emphasize that John Paul had acted not only as a Pole but as
head of the worldwide Roman Catholic Church.
   ``If I did something, I did it as part of my universal mission
and it should be viewed as such,'' the Vatican quoted the pope as
telling Mazowiecki. ``I consider this audience an historic and
positive fact. However, it is not historic for me only under a
patriotic profile...''
   As evidence of the changes sweeping the Soviet-bloc, John Paul
on Friday ordained as bishops the Vatican's first ambassador to
Poland since the Communists broke diplomatic relations after World
War II and the first Roman Catholic bishop in Soviet Byelorussia in
60 years.
   Aides said Mazowiecki, long a Solidarity adviser, and the pope
have met about 20 times during John Paul's 11-year pontificate,
most recently when Solidarity leader Lech Walesa came to Rome in
April.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
