<SECOND>PM-Baby Rescued,0221</SECOND>
<HEAD>Baby Pulled from Sinking Car</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DURHAM, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rescuers plucked a baby from a sinking car
ditched in a creek by a man who had assaulted the infant's mother,
police said.
   ``The water was coming up to the baby's chest and it was still
rising,'' said police officer T.L. Scott. ``If he had not been in
the child seat, I am more than convinced he would have drowned.''
   Officers were heading for the scene of an accident involving a
stolen car early Thursday when they found the automobile in a
rain-swollen creek and the baby inside.
   In the predawn darkness, Scott reached into the back seat, which
was two-thirds full of water, and pulled out the 9-month-old boy.
   The infant's mother, Felichia Peace, reported she was assaulted
as she talked on a pay phone. The man threatened her with a gun and
tried to drag her behind a convenience store, but she managed to
grab a bottle from atop an ice machine and hit him in the head,
police said.
   She broke free and ran to a nearby house and called police. When
she went back outside, she discovered her car was gone _ with her
son, Tirone D. Peace, in the back seat.
   No arrests have been made, police said.
