<FIRST>r w PM-Quake-FEMA     10-20 0184</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Quake-FEMA,170</SECOND>
<HEAD>FEMA Preparing to Oepn Assistance Centers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Emergency Management Agency said
today it is preparing to open as many as 17 assistance centers to
process applications from victims of northern California's
earthquake disaster.
   The centers, which probably will be open by Sunday, will be
located in the seven counties that President Bush declared disaster
areas after Tuesday's earthquake.
   Robert Blair, a FEMA spokesman, said people who suffered
property losses in the earthquake will be able to apply for
low-cost loans and receive other advice from federal officials at
the centers.
   Meantime, Blair said the toll-free telephone lines opened
Thursday to assist victims are being clogged by calls from people
who have not been affected by the earthquake.
   ``Some people are calling looking for loved ones,'' he said.
FEMA, he said, is unable to handle that kind of call, which he said
could be handled by the Red Cross.
   He said the 110 FEMA telephone lines are staffed round-the-clock
to handle questions, such as where homeless people should go.
   The telephone number for those FEMA lines is 1-800-462-9029.
</TEXT>
