<FIRST>u i PM-Colombia 1stLd-Writethru   10-20 0576</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Colombia, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0456,0592</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Workers Return to Work With Protection Demands Unmet</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Leads with 14 grafs to UPDATE with strike over, report of Medellin
attempt to begin talks. Pickup 10th pvs, `But the...;' Deletes last 3 grafs
to trim.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STAN YARBRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Colombia's judges and other court
workers returned to work today after failing in a three-day strike
to force the government to protect them from drug traffickers.
   ``We are certain that more of us will be murdered in coming
months, but we can't shut down the court system for very long,''
said Consuelo Herrera, a federal judge and member of the court
workers' union, the Association of Judicial Employees.
   The 5,000 judges and 12,000 other judicial workers walked off
the job Tuesday after a federal judge was slain by drug dealers in
retaliation for the extradition of drug suspects to the United
States.
   Since 1981, about 50 judges and 170 other judicial employees
have been killed in Colombia. The Association of Judicial Employees
says 1,600 of the 5,000 judges have been threatened with death in
the last 12 months.
   Ms. Herrera said union workers are prepared to strike again the
next time a judge or court worker is murdered by drug traffickers.
   ``The next strike will be longer and the next one longer
still,'' she said. ``We will continue to call strikes as long as we
are being killed and the government continues to do nothing.''
   Ms. Herrera said Justice Minister Roberto Salazar Manrique told
union members in a meeting Tuesday that the government lacks the
resources to increase protection for judges.
   She said none of the $19 million in aid promised by the Bush
administration to protect Colombian judges has arrived in the
country.
   Meanwhile, the Bogota daily El Tiempo published an account of
yet another attempt by the Medellin cocaine cartel to begin talks
with officials on ending the government crackdown on the drug trade.
   An unidentified Medellin lawyer representing the cartel spoke
two weeks ago with the country's leading leftist, Bernardo
Jaramillo, a candidate in March presidential elections, El Tiempo
quoted Jaramillo as saying.
   Jaramillo was quoted as telling the lawyer that he favors
dialogue with the traffickers but not while the traffickers are
setting off bombs and killing people.
   The Medellin cartel has made several contacts with government
officials and other politicians in attempts to negotiate a truce in
the 2-month-old war on drugs.
   President Virgilio Barco has said there will be no talks and no
truce.
   Barco resumed extraditions to the United States on Aug. 18
following the slayings of a leading presidential candidate, a
federal judge, and a police colonel by drug barons.
   But the traffickers have struck back with a terror campaign that
has included more than 160 bombings and the assassinations of eight
news industry workers.
   The government on Thursday pressed ahead in its anti-drug
offensive by arresting two drug suspects, one the alleged personal
pilot of the presumed head of the Medellin cocaine cartel, Pablo
Escobar.
   The pilot, Jorge de la Cuesta Marquez, is wanted on federal
charges in Florida, national police Col. Oscar Pelaez Carmona said
in a news release.
   De la Cuesta, arrested in a raid on a north Bogota apartment, is
wanted on a U.S. indictment for conspiracy to distribute cocaine
and will be held for extradition, Pelaez Carmona said.
   With de la Cuesta's arrest, five Colombians await extradition to
the United States.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
