<HEAD>Former UPI Editor Named Editor of Journal Newspapers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ben Cason, former managing editor and
editor in chief of United Press International, has been named
editor in chief and vice president for editorial of The Journal
Newspapers.
   Publisher Geoffrey Edwards announced the appointment today.
   Cason was an assistant managing editor at The Washington Post
for 10 years before leaving in January 1987 to join UPI as managing
editor for news. He was named editor in chief two months later. He
left the wire service in November of that year and has been a
consultant.
   At the Post, Cason served as news editor, assistant managing
editor and assistant managing editor for new projects. He was
involved for several years in the development of new sections.
   Prior to joining the Post, Cason was news editor of the St.
Petersburg Times in Florida.
   He is to join the Journal papers, which are the Montgomery
Journal, Prince George's Journal, Alexandria Journal, Fairfax
Journal and Arlington Journal, on Thursday.
   The five suburban Washington papers are published each weekday
morning.
