<HEAD>Twenty-Two People Die in Bus Crash</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SYDNEY, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A tour bus filled with vacationers
crashed into a truck today north of Sydney and killed at least 22
people, including seven members of one family, police said. It was
Australia's worst bus accident.
   Both drivers were among those killed in the head-on collision on
the Pacific Highway near Cowper.
   The tour bus was carrying about 42 passengers, said Keith
Weinert, managing director of Sunliner Coaches, which owned the
bus. It was 320 milesnorth of Sydney, en route to Brisbane, when
the accident occured at about 4 a.m.
   Witness Michele Bowling, whose family farm is near the crash
site, described the scene: `The vehicle was on its side with smoke
pouring from it and I could hear screams from people trapped in the
bus.''
   She said her paddock had been turned into a makeshift morgue.
   Colin Ormsesher, an advertising executive on a New South Wales
central coast newspaper, survived the crash, but the dead included
his wife, their two teen-age children, his brother, sister-in-law
and their two children.
   Ormsesher's brother, Les, had arrived with his family from
England on Monday for a holiday in New South Wales and Queensland.
   The families were on their way to the Whitsunday Islands in
northern Queensland for a boating holiday.
   The cause of the accident was not known.
