<FIRST>r a PM-BombingArrests     10-20 0278</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bombing Arrests,0287</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nine UMW Members Arrested in Mine Bombings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILBURN, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nine United Mine Workers members were
arrested and charged in a series of bombings at a mine where a
strike has been under way for five years.
   The miners arrested Thursday were accused in two bombings, an
attempted bombing and a fire that did $400,000 damage at Milburn
Colliery, where 45 union members went on strike in October 1984.
   Authorities planned to seek indictments next week before a
federal grand jury in Charleston, said U.S. Attorney Michael Carey.
   One miner, Larry Massey, was charged with destroying property
involved in interstate commerce, Carey said. He faces 10 years in
prison and $250,000 in fines if convicted. Eight others were
charged with conspiracy to use explosives and faces up to five
years in prison and $250,000 in fines.
   All nine were arraigned before a federal magistrate in Bluefield
and freed on $10,000 bond.
   The UMW's chief spokesman, Joe Corcoran, said the union was
unaware of any evidence implicating the nine.
   ``In any strike situation, there are many allegations and
accusations that turn out not to be true,'' he said.
   In June, not long after the mine's owners hired a new company to
operate the mine, a bomb was set off at a bridge entrance, and in
July a fire resulted in about $400,000 damage, Carey said.
   Then last month, a bomb caused about $35,000 damage to a mine
ventilation system, and authorities disarmed a 57-pound time bomb
before it exploded, Carey said.
   No one was injured in the incidents.
   Carey said the investigation is continuing, but would not
comment on whether further arrests are expected.
</TEXT>
