<FIRST>u i PM-Britain-Bombings 1stLd-Writethru a0461 10-20 0425</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-Bombings, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0461,0434</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fourth Man Wrongly Convicted In IRA Bombing Freed on Bail</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with fourth man free on bail pending
appeal on separate offense. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WEST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Irishman cleared by an appeals court of a
14-year-old terrorist bombing was freed on bail today pending his
appeal of a separate murder conviction.
   Paul Hill's release by a Belfast court meant all the so-called
Guildford Four are now free after a long fight for exoneration.
   The four were serving life sentences for two Irish Republican
Army bombings that killed five people in 1974 in Guildford,
southwest of London. A London judge overturned the convictions
Thursday, ruling that police officers probably lied to get the four
convictions.
   The government immediately ordered an inquiry into alleged
police misconduct.
   While three of the four were freed Thursday, 35-year-old Hill
was also serving a life sentence for the murder of a British
soldier, and he was flown to Belfast to begin an appeal.
   He was freed today on $6,500 bail and emerged from the court to
cheers from friends and relatives, including his 14-year-old
daughter, Cara.
   ``I am very happy,'' he replied to a reporter's question. ``How
do you think I feel after 14 years of hell?''
   Home Secretary Douglas Hurd, the Cabinet member responsible for
police, said in a BBC-TV interview Thursday night that the
Guildford case was ``a blow for the whole system'' of criminal
justice in Britain.
   David Williams, deputy chief constable of the Surrey county
police force, whose officers handled the original investigation of
the Guildford Four, said Thursday that three officers had been
suspended from duty pending the inquiry by retired appeals judge
Sir John May.
   Williams identified them as a sergeant and two constables. He
said a fourth officer involved, a detective inspector, had died and
a fifth, a detective chief inspector, had retired.
   The ruling ended years of work by relatives, former government
officials, church leaders and journalists to overturn the verdict.
The sentence had been upheld in 1977 even though IRA members made
detailed confessions in the case.
   The appeals court threw out the convictions of Gerard Conlon,
35, Patrick Armstrong, 39, and Hill, all of Belfast, and Carole
Richardson, 32, of London, in the bombing of two pubs at Guildford
in Surrey on Oct. 5, 1974.
   The convictions of Armstrong and Hill for a pub bombing in the
London suburb of Woolwich on Nov. 6, 1974, also were reversed. Two
people died in that attack.
</TEXT>
