<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-89 1148EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u e BC-Theater 1stLd-Writethru a0886 10-20 0682</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Theater, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0886,0691</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Dangerous Games,' Two Dance Musicals, Open on Broadway</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Adds four grafs with what other critics said. No PMs planned.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Critic</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In ``Dangerous Games,'' the collective title of
two dance theater pieces created by Graciela Daniele, the theme is
domination, primarily sexual and political, done to a tango beat.
   In ``Tango,'' two sinister, working-class brothers violate and
then fight over a young prostitute; in ``Orfeo,'' a reworking of
the Orpheus legend, the hero seeks to rescue his love from the
Argentine secret police who operate out of a place not unlike Hades.
   All of this, which arrived at Broadway's Nederlander Theater on
Thursday, is not as interesting as it might sound, even though the
evening contains some haunting tango music by Astor Piazzolla.
   The dancing is a tad pretentious and a bit silly, particularly
when it's trying to be sexy. Daniele's choreography is filled with
steamy clinches, erotic posturing and a heavy dose of whips and
leather. It's light years from the romantic duets that were the
main attraction of a different kind of tango entertainment, ``Tango
Argentino,'' a mild Broadway success several seasons ago.
   ``Tango'' is the earthy, simple and more successful of Daniele's
two dances. The two brothers (Gregory Mitchell and John Mineo) are
violent, narcissistic men, stereotypes of the macho Latin
tradition. They fight, strut and then take whatever they want,
particularly the new woman in the bordello (Tina Paul).
   Paul is not only a fine dancer but she's an actress, too, making
the woman's brutalization all the more convincing. In the end, she
is the most poignant victim, transformed into someone as hard and
as uncaring as the men who used her.
   In ``Orfeo,'' Daniele reaches for political significance and
falls short. The piece is dedicated to the ``desaparecidos,'' the
Spanish word for all those who were arrested and then disappeared
during the brutal Argentine military dictatorship.
   Daniele's Orfeo (Gregory Mitchell, again) is a gaucho who sees
his love (Rene Caballos) spirited away by Pluton (Ken Ard), who
wears military fatigues and a beret. Ard is an athletic dancer who
projects an unnerving menace. But he's also saddled with some of
William Finn's worst lyrics, particularly when he sings about ``the
joys of torture.'' The lyrics seem to be an intrusion on the
evening and could have been cut with little harm to both pieces.
   The choreography can't support the weight of Daniele's political
message. At times, it has a folksy, Agnes de Mille quality,
peasants cavorting around the stage. At other times, it reaches for
the mock solemnity of Gerald Arpino, recalling the Joffrey Ballet
clinker, ``Sacred Grove on Mount Tamalpais.'' But it's never as
moving as its subject matter.
   Tony Straiges has designed a tawdry and forbidding bordello for
``Tango,'' and an all-purpose red wall meant to signify hell in
``Orfeo.'' Patricia Zipprodt's costumes are surprisingly
understated, all-black outfits for the men and billowy dresses for
the women.
   Daniele, who has choreographed Broadway musicals including ``The
Pirates of Penzance,'' ``The Rink'' and ``The Mystery of Edwin
Drood,'' needs more of a story line on which to hang her dances.
Her choreography isn't compelling enough to compensate for the thin
tales she and co-author Jim Lewis have concocted for ``Dangerous
Games.''
   What other critics said:
   Frank Rich, The New York Times: If theater people want to make a
spectacle of themselves on a Broadway stage, that is their
inalienable right, but whatever happened to the poor audience's
right to enjoy a few laughs in the face of such disaster?
   Howard Kissel, Daily News: While the choreography in both is
virtuosic and danced with great vehemence and ardor, Daniele's
imagination seldom goes beyond the adolescent in her depiction of
the earthiness and sensuality of the brothel or the repressiveness
of the generals.
   Clive Barnes, New York Post: The sad thing is that the dancers
do their level best to raise this grisly corpse of an evening into
some semblance of life _ as if they were literally flogging a dead
horse.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
