<FIRST>r a PM-CDC--HuntingInjuries 1stLd-Writethru a0454 10-20 0616</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-CDC--Hunting Injuries, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0454,0627</SECOND>
<HEAD>Federal Study: Many Hunting Injuries Come From Falling Out of Trees</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 4 grafs after 12th graf, `That number...' with accounts
of unusual tree accidents. Picks up 13th graf, `Some of...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Many hunters get hurt simply by falling out of
trees, not by being shot by other hunters, federal health
researchers said.
   The Centers for Disease Control, which studies injuries as well
as disease, reported Thursday the results of a Georgia study
showing that 36 percent of hunting injuries involved tree stands _
the perches where deer hunters wait for prey.
   The CDC and Georgia officials studied 594 deer hunting-related
injuries in the state over the 1979-89 hunting seasons: 214
involved tree stands, which may be hastily built platforms or
store-bought tree chairs.
   Seventeen people died, fractures were common and several
teen-age hunters suffered neck fractures and were paralyzed.
   ``This is just the tip of the iceberg,'' said Dr. Steven Gordon,
an epidemiologist with the Georgia Department of Human Resources.
``The nature of the system is such that the only reports we get are
the ones that are fairly serious.''
   He added: ``We're sure this is occurring in other states. But no
one had systematically looked into it.''
   When most people hear of hunting accidents, they picture one
person shooting another, said Joel Brown, Georgia's state
hunter-safety coordinator. But in recent years, he said, more than
50 percent have involved tree stands. ``It's a serious problem,''
he said.
   Most of the tree stand injuries involved falls; 111 hunters were
hurt when they tumbled out of their stands, 49 fell while trying to
climb down and 40 fell while trying to climb up. Gordon said the
average stand was 16 feet above the ground.
   Twenty-seven injuries _ and eight of the 17 tree stand
fatalities _ occurred when weapons went off accidentally, either
while firearms were being carried up and down the tree or on impact
from a fall.
   Sixty-one of the 214 tree stand mishaps involved mechanical
failure, as the stand or its steps collapsed under the hunter's
weight.
   Eleven hunters reported they had fallen asleep just before
falling out. Eight hunters either admitted they were drunk or were
suspected of it by game officials.
   That number, Gordon said, might be low. ``We could not assess
the influence of alcohol or other substance abuse. ... Most of
these hunters did not have blood-alcohol levels taken,'' he said.
   While some hunters simply lost their balance, some suffered
bizarre accidents.
   A law enforcement officer chopped down small trees surrounding
his stand to improve his view of the deer. He fell from his stand
onto the jagged tree stumps and was severely injured, Brown said.
   Another hunter, Brown said, climbed a tree in a pond, not
knowing the tree had been killed by beavers. The tree broke in two
and the hunter was killed when he tumbled out and the tree fell on
top of him.
   Gordon said a woman was hurt when she shot a deer from her tree
perch and the wounded animal charged. The impact from the deer
crashing into the tree dislodged her and she broke a leg in the
fall.
   Some of the injured hunters were asked whether they had taken a
hunting safety course; two-thirds hadn't. And none of the 214
injured hunters was wearing a safety harnesses or seat belt.
   Many mishaps could have been prevented, the CDC said, if hunters
had used safety harnesses, unloaded their guns while climbing up
and down, used pull-up cords to hoist their weapons into their
stands and checked the condition of their stands before climbing in.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
