<FIRST>u i PM-Hungary 1stLd-Writethru   10-20 0442</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hungary, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0568,0454</SECOND>
<HEAD>Parliament Disbands Communist Paramilitary Organization</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with approval of political trial
legislation; picks up 10th pvs: Parliament has ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEX BANDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Parliament, meeting to move Hungary
closer to democracy, voted today to disband a militia that was
created to protect the Communist Party after the 1956 revolt.
   The legislature also approved proposals to rehabilitate victims
of political trials during Hungary's years of Communist oppression.
   The decision to disband the militia came just three days before
the 33rd anniversary of the 1956 revolt, which was crushed by
Soviet tanks.
   The bill had been opposed by the Socialist Party, which assumed
power after the Communist Party was formally dismantled Oct. 7.
   The Socialist Party, which professes democratic ideals but
remains in sole possession of power at least until parliamentary
elections next year, had suggested disarming the force but keeping
it as a civil defense organization.
   ``The existence of the Workers Militia ... is no longer
justified,'' declared Justice Ministry State Secretary Gyula Borics
in introducing legislation to dissolve the 60,000-strong force.
   Of votes cast on the issue, 274 were in favor of termination,
with six against and 30 abstentions.
   Parliament already rehabilitated revolutionary leader Imre Nagy
and his leading associates earlier in the year.
   Parliament had already rehabilitated revolutionary leader Imre
Nagy and his leading associates earlier in the year, but the bill
passed today was broader, extending to all those convicted of
revolutionary activity during the a956 uprising.
   The bill, which also pledged unspecified compensation to
victims, was approved by 278 legislators, with four against 26
abstentions.
   A similar but separate bill also formally rehabilitated those
victimized between 1948 and 1962 _ the period now officially
considered Hungary's Stalinist period.
   Parliament has been meeting in a historic session aimed at
removing the vestiges of 41 years of Communist rule. On Thursday,
Parliament passed legislation permitting opposition parties to
compete in the first free national elections since 1948.
   Lawmakers still must settle a dispute over when to select a new
president.
   A proposal agreed on by the Socialist Party and most major
opposition parties suggested that voters cast ballots on Nov. 26,
with subsequent heads of state appointed by Parliament.
   But some opposition groups fear the ruling party would have too
strong an advantage if the president were chosen next month.
   They have collected nearly 200,000 signatures calling for a
referendum on whether the president should be chosen now or only
after national elections redistribute political power. Parliament
is to try and sort out the issue at its next session, beginning
Oct. 31.
</TEXT>
