<FIRST>r a PM-JetEngines-Sting     10-20 0258</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Jet Engines-Sting,0264</SECOND>
<HEAD>FBI Arrests Three More Suspects in Jet Engine Sting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three Hill Air Force Base security
policemen have been arrested in a federal ``sting'' operation that
uncovered thefts and illegal sales of military property, the FBI
said.
   Gregory Lewis Hawley, 27, Robin James Olson, 21, and Robert Todd
Young, 23, were arrested without incident Wednesday by agents of
the FBI, the Defense Criminal Investigative Service and the Air
Force Office of Special Investigations. They were charged with
theft of government property.
   The arrests were part of Operation Punchout, a three-year
undercover investigation that prosecutors say eventually could
result in charges against more than 100 people.
   The three were among nine people charged in sealed indictments
that were handed up Oct. 13 by a federal grand jury in Ogden. An
additional 12 persons were charged earlier in a separate sealed
indictment handed up in Salt Lake City.
   In the undercover operation, FBI agents posed as operators of a
mock military surplus store in the town of Roy, 35 miles north of
Salt Lake City. They netted an assortment of government munitions
and equipment, including three F-16 jet engines.
   Two men from Hill, Airman 1st Class Brian David Roth and Senior
Airman Danny Joe Stroud, pleaded guilty Wednesday to stealing the
engines and selling them to the undercover agents. They were two of
the 12 named in the earlier indictment.
   The guilty pleas were part of a deal that will result in
additional charges being dropped when they are sentenced Dec. 12.
</TEXT>
