<FIRST>r i AM-Vietnam-US     10-20 0219</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Vietnam-US,0225</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Military Experts Visit Vietnam on MIAs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. military experts left Friday for
Vietnam for the eighth joint field investigation to resolve the
fates of American soldiers missing from the Vietnam War, a U.S.
Embassy official said.
   For about 15 days, the two U.S. teams will investigate areas in
Song Be province and Ho Chi Minh City in southern Vietnam and Ha
Bac province near Hanoi, the embassy official said.
   They included specialists of the Joint Casualty Resolution
Center and forensic experts from the Army Central Identification
Laboratory, said the official, who spoke on condition he not be
identified. They will cooperate with workers from Vietnam's Office
for Seeking Missing Personnel.
   Both U.S. agencies are based in Hawaii and entrusted with
resolving the fates of America's wartime missing.
   About 2,340 Americans are listed as missing in action from the
Vietnam War, which also involved fighting in Cambodia and Laos.
U.S. combat involvement ended in 1973 and the communists toppled
U.S.-backed South Vietnam in April 1975.
   The United States and Vietnam began the joint field
investigations in October 1988. These involve inspecting plane
crash sites and interviewing villagers who may have seen the
crashes.
   On Sept. 11, Vietnam returned what it said were believed to be
three sets of remains of missing Americans.
</TEXT>
