<SECOND>AM-Britain-Gunman,0253</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gunman With Terminal Illness Kills Two, Then Himself</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANCHESTER, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man whose doctors gave him only two
weeks to live went on a shooting rampage, killing two men and then
himself, police said Friday.
   Peter Crack, armed with a .22-caliber pistol, killed his first
victim at a gun club at Stockport near Manchester on Thursday night
and his second victim on a Stockport street an hour later, police
said.
   Crack then holed up in an empty house near Manchester Airport,
said Assistant Chief Constable Jim Paterson of the Greater
Manchester police force.
   Officers surrounded the house and tried to talk him into
surrendering, but three hours later they heard a shot and found him
dead inside, he said.
   Crack, 30, had been undergoing treatment for cancer at
Manchester's Christie Hospital and was told recently he had two
weeks to live, Paterson said. He was married with a 2-year-old
daughter.
   The first slaying occurred Thursday night at the Stockport
Shooting Center, a gun club where Crack had gone for target
practice, Paterson said.
   In a commotion that started because Crack left himself in the
firing line, he shot and killed Duncan Allman, 31, who was
supervising the practice, Paterson said.
   Crack then fled and an hour later arrived at the home of an
acquaintance, Howard Savage, 27. Crack and Savage left the house
and crossed the street into an alley leading to garages where
Savage was shot several times, Paterson said.
