<FIRST>r i AM-Wallenberg     10-20 0481</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wallenberg,0494</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wallenberg Relative to Visit Prison Where Diplomat Reported Once
Held</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MOSB4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAREY GOLDBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Relatives who insist Raoul Wallenberg is still
alive said Friday the search for the Swedish diplomat who vanished
decades ago after saving thousands of Jews will continue in a
prison next week.
   ``There is evidence that Raoul had been at various periods
between 1950 and 1980 in the prison of Vladimir'' about 75 miles
from Moscow, said Guy von Dardel, Wallenberg's half-brother.
   Soviet authorities say Wallenberg, who is credited with saving
tens of thousands of Hungarian Jews from the Nazis during World War
II, died in another prison in 1947, two years after he was arrested
in Budapest on spying charges.
   The Soviet line on Wallenberg's death has not changed, von
Dardel told a news conference, but officials are cooperating with
the relatives' search and suggested a trip to the Vladimir prison
Monday to let them check its archives and cells themselves.
   Von Dardel and Wallenberg's half-sister, Nina Lagergren, arrived
in Moscow on Oct. 14 for their officially approved trip. In an
initial meeting, Soviet authorities presented them with
Wallenberg's personal effects, including his blue diplomatic
passport, which they said had just been found among sacks of such
items at KGB headquarters.
   They were also shown a copy of a death certificate that backs up
the Soviet claim that Wallenberg died of heart failure in 1947.
   But von Dardel and Lagergren maintain their belief that
Wallenberg, who would be 77, is still alive.
   Von Dardel said the Vladimir prison used to have a special
section for foreigners and about 20 former prisoners have told
Western investigators ``there was a Swede whose name varied'' but
resembled Wallenberg.
   He said he would travel to the prison and investigate its
records, which go back to 1953, and the cells themselves, but that
he did not expect to find Wallenberg there because the foreigners'
section is gone.
   Lagergren said it was moving just to visit Moscow and the KGB's
Lubyanka prison, where Wallenberg was held.
   ``You can imagine what it feels like to pass through the
Lubyanka prison and think that Raoul has been there beginning in
1945,'' she said. ``And that he was there for two years, not far
away from the Swedish embassy, without being able to contact
anybody outside prison. And we didn't know.''
   Soviet authorities investigated the relatives' list of people
who believed they had seen Wallenberg with ``remarkable quickness''
and resolved many points, but not all, von Dardel said.
   A Soviet official who met with the Wallenberg relatives said
Friday they would continue to be welcome to search for his traces,
but they could not expect to find him alive.
   ``The Soviet side has confirmed that the fact of Wallenberg's
death is irrevocable and nothing more can be done here,'' Foreign
Ministry official Nikolai Uspensky said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
