<HEAD>Frank Says Published Allegations Have `No Basis'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Barney Frank, D-Mass., said Friday there
is ``no basis whatsoever'' to a published report that he engaged in
sexual misconduct in the House gym and predicted that any ethics
committee investigation would support his denial.
   The Washington Times reported Friday that the ethics committee
has evidence of sexual misconduct by Frank and several other
members in the gym, located in the sub-basement of the Rayburn
House Office Building.
   ``The allegations in the Washington Times today that I engaged
in improper activities in the House gym are completely untrue,''
Frank said in a statement issued by his office.
   ``There is simply no basis whatsoever for any suggestions to the
contrary and I am confident that the ethics committee will concur.''
   Gym supervisor Dennis Fogle, asked if he was aware of any
misconduct in the gym, said, ``not to my knowledge.'' He said the
gym is for members only and there are no provisions he is aware of
for members to bring guests there with them.
   A source in the speaker's office, speaking on the condition of
anonymity, said no allegations of misconduct in the gym have been
brought to the attention of the speaker of the House, Thomas S.
Foley, D-Wash.
   One ethics committee source, who also spoke on the condition of
anonymity, said the full panel has not held discussions on the
subject during its investigation of Frank.
   The newspaper, which said it could not ascertain the names of
any of the other congressmen, said it learned of the evidence from
several members close to the ethics investigation. These sources
were not named.
   The Times quoted a male prostitute, Stephen Gobie, as saying he
and Frank had performed sex acts ``on a couple of occasions'' after
hours in the House gym. The newspaper said it had confirmed that
Frank had brought ``a number of young men'' to the gym, which
generally is off-limits to the public and to staff.
   The paper said the ethics panel had determined that several
congressmen had taken male and female guests into the gym ``for
illicit sexual activity.''
   The ethics committee has been investigating Frank's conduct
since Gobie revealed his 1985-1987 relationship with the
congressman to the Times.
