<FIRST>r i AM-Korea     10-20 0446</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea,0460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Inter-Korea Sports Talks Make Breakthrough: A Flag Design</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL SHIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANMUNJOM, Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sports officials from North Korea and
South Korea on Friday announced their first breakthrough in
months-old talks on the Asian Games: they agreed on a flag to be
used by athletes from both nations.
   Progress also was reported on plans to form a single team for
the games next year in Beijing, but obstacles remain, such as what
to call the team.
   ``There was a considerable progress on the flag and others,
including the selection of athletes for the joint team,'' North
Korea's chief delegate Kim Hyung Jin said after the four-hour
meeting at the Panmunjom truce site.
   ``We will do our best to form the first single team in our
history and we in turn expect the South to do so,'' he said.
   His South Korean counterpart, Chang Chung-sik, also reported
progress.
   ``The northern side was rather active and straightforward and
there was some progress. But I would not say the prospect is 100
percent bright,'' Chang said after the meeting, which was open to
the press.
   The talks were businesslike, with both sides avoiding political
exchanges. Recent talks have bogged down in acrimonious political
exchanges.
   Sports officials of the two Koreas met twice early this year
before North Korea unilaterally suspended dialogue in April to
protest the arrest of South Korean dissident clergyman Moon
Ik-hwan. Moon was arrested for visiting North Korea without
permission from the South Korean government.
   North Korea has been demanding Moon's release, but North Korean
officials did not raise the issue Friday.
   Delegates of the two Koreas quickly agreed on a flag to be used
by the first inter-Korea joint team at the Asian Games. The flag
will have a map of the Korean peninsula in blue on a white
background.
   It is the first time both Koreas have agreed on a joint flag for
an international sports event since they first started talks on
forming a single team for the 1964 Olympics in Tokyo. All efforts
to form a joint team for any event so far have failed.
   Both Koreas also agreed in principle to select athletes for the
single team through joint training and open competition.
   They could not agree on the name of the team. Both sides agreed
to use Korea as the English name of the team but could not decide
what name to use in Korean.
   North Korea proposed Nov. 2 as a date of the next meeting but
South Korea suggested Nov. 22. They settled on Nov. 16.
   The Korean peninsula was divided into communist North Korea and
capitalist South Korea in 1945.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
