<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-89 1315EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Reagans     10-20 0626</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Reagans,0649</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reagans Arrive For Visit, Reportedly Will Receive $2 Million</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto TOK1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELAINE KURTENBACH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ronald and Nancy Reagan arrived here Friday on a
visit for which the former president reportedly will receive $2
million, and the Japanese government said it will award him one of
its highest honors.
   The Reagans arrived on a chartered TWA Boeing 747 along with 229
U.S. military dependents they invited to hitch a ride to the Far
East.
   Reagan will receive the Grand Cordon of the Supreme Order of the
Chrysanthemum for his ``contribution to the maintenance and
promotion of friendship between the United States and Japan,'' said
Foreign Ministry spokesman Taizo Watanabe.
   ``Mr. Reagan has always been clear in refusing protectionism and
tried his best to maintain the free trade system,'' Watanabe said.
   The only other U.S. president to receive the honor was Dwight
Eisenhower.
   The Reagans are in Japan at the invitation of the Japanese
government and the Fujisankei Communications Group. Fujisankei has
refused to confirm reports Reagan will receive about $2 million for
the visit, which it said will cost a total of about $7 million.
   Fujisankei, Japan's largest media group, owns the newspaper
Sankei Shimbun, the Fuji Telecasting Corp. and Nippon Hoso, Japan's
biggest commercial radio network, among dozens of other companies.
   Like Fujisankei's chairman, Nobutaka Shikanai, many of the
company's media outlets espouse conservativism and nationalism. At
the time of Emperor Hirohito's death and the controversy it spawned
over his role in World War II, the Fuji TV network generally
carried fewer critical views of Japan's imperial system.
   The Reagans descended hand-in-hand from their plane and were met
by U.S. Ambassador Michael Armacost and Vice Foreign Minister Naoki
Tanaka.
   In short remarks on the tarmac, Reagan said he was ``delighted''
to be back in Japan. The former president made a state visit to
Japan in 1983 and attended the annual summit of industrialized
nations in Tokyo in 1986.
   ``I deeply valued the working relationships I had with Japanese
leaders during my time in the White House,'' he said. ``Nancy and I
have a special fondness for the Japanese people.''
   The Reagans will attend several charity events and meet Prime
Minister Toshiki Kaifu, Emperor Akihito and other government
figures during the two-day official part of the visit.
   The Reagans' chartered jet was half-filled with relatives of
military personnel.
   The wives, children and parents on the plane were greeted by
uniformed family members with tears, hugs and kisses.
   ``It's great. I wasn't expecting to see them until next
February,'' said Pat Andreas of Yokosuka Naval Base, south of
Tokyo, as he tousled the heads of his sons Michael, 7, and Alex, 3,
after they and their mother, Lyn, arrived from Oxnard, Calif.
   ``The Reagans were so friendly and down to earth,'' said Cleo
Bookwalder of Albuquerque, N.M., who traveled with her husband Don
to see their son, Fred, who is stationed in northern Japan, for the
first time in two years.
   The Bookwalders and others said the Reagans spent time on the
jet shaking hands and talking with them.
   ``I want to write to someone in charge to thank them for making
this possible,'' said Sue Abel of Fort Madison, Iowa, as she
greeted her husband's parents, Violet and Bill Abel.
   The Reagans were whisked by helicopter from Tokyo to
Fujisankei's Hakone Open-Air Museum in the forested hills near
Mount Fuji where, after a brief welcoming ceremony, they were to
spend Friday evening and Saturday resting.
   It is Reagan's first major excursion since he had surgery Sept.
8 to drain fluid from his brain after suffering a head injury in a
horseback riding accident this summer.
   The Reagans are scheduled to return to the United States on Oct.
28.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
