<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Crash     10-20 0207</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Crash,0212</SECOND>
<HEAD>Plane Carrying Equipment for Quake-Ravaged Armenia Crashes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A cargo plane carrying construction equipment for
earthquake-ravaged Armenia crashed early Friday, killing all 17
people aboard, a newspaper reported.
   The crash near the airport in Leninakan, Armenia, was the second
air disaster in the Caucasus region this week and recalled a
similar disaster in the same area just after December's quake.
   The evening newspaper Izvestia said an Ilyushin-76 on its way to
the Leninakan airport slammed into a mountain 11 miles away. On
board were seven crew members, seven passengers and three
pilot-trainees, it said.
   A government commission was formed to investigate the accident.
   Leninakan is in the heart of the area devastated by the Dec. 7,
1988, earthquake, which killed 25,000 people. Four days after the
quake, an Il-76 carrying Soviet soldiers to help rescue quake
victims plunged to the ground near Leninakan's airport, killing all
78 people on board.
   On Wednesday, one of four engines on an Il-76 caught fire after
takeoff in Azerbaijan and the plane crashed in the Caspian Sea,
killing all 57 people aboard. Among those killed were paratroopers
assigned to keep order in the Caucasus, which has been wracked by
ethnic violence for more than a year.
</TEXT>
