<DOCNO> AP891020-0135 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-89 1335EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-SFQuake-HighwayRescuers 2ndLd-Writethru a0529 10-20
0736</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SF Quake-Highway Rescuers, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0529,0755</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rescue Workers Continue Search for Survivors on Highway, But Hope
Fades</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with 21 bodies recovered, 52 other
vehicles located; picks up 5th graf, `But 167 ...'.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto OAS1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID FOSTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Firefighter Lee Kraft was visibly shaken
after he crawled into an 18-inch-high opening on the collapsed
Nimitz Freeway to pull out the bodies of a 6-year-old girl and her
mother.
   ``It kills you. It just kills you. We all have families, you
know. ... The adults are no problem. But the kids ...,'' he said
Thursday before trailing off, dabbing tears.
   The carnage on the highway, also known as Interstate 880, upset
even the most veteran of rescue workers. Here, on a 1\-mile-long
section of interstate just south of the Bay Bridge, Tuesday's
earthquake was its deadliest.
   Using shovels, backhoes, cranes and their hands, workers had
recovered 21 bodies and located 52 vehicles between the pancaked
decks of the highway by early today. Twenty-three of them were
empty, single bodies were removed from nine of them and 20 others
were yet to be investigated. In addition, 45 cars and trucks were
pulled off the shattered upper deck or from the streets below,
authorities said.
   But 167 people remained on the official missing list today for
Alameda County, which includes Oakland and several other
communities. Dozens of vehicles still were sandwiched between tons
of concrete.
   Early estimates put the number of dead at 250 people, but
officials said Thursday night that they expected the total would be
lower _ possibly much lower.
   Some rescuers, working around the clock, stubbornly clung to
hopes that someone might be found alive in the highway debris.
Others, including Kraft, had no hopes.
   ``We haven't found a live one yet, and I don't think we will,''
he said.
   The even layers of the two-tiered elevated highway lay buckled
and twisted like a writhing serpent, their concrete supports
sheared off.
   On the railing of the flattened upper deck, spray paint pointed
the way to crushed cars and shattered bodies: 1DOA signified a
body, 2MT a pair of empty cars, a circle and arrow with the number
43 stood for a car 43 feet away.
   ``You could see blood splattered everywhere on the concrete,''
said volunteer Jason Losorio, taking a break after a 13-hour shift
that included moving concrete chunks by hand.
   The scene drew hundreds of onlookers on Thursday, including many
who feared a relative or friend might be buried.
   During a live broadcast of CBS-TV's ``48 Hours,'' an angry man
who believes his son may be in the wreckage confronted Mayor Lionel
Wilson.
   ``Mayor, did you know that you are directly responsible for this
here mess, this disaster?'' asked Daniel Rubi of San Francisco.
Rubi said he had been turned away on Wednesday when he asked to
climb the freeway structure and search for his son, Juan.
   The mayor replied, ``I'm sorry, I can't answer that question.''
   Police took Rubi away but did not place him under arrest.
   Authorities say it could be at least three days before workers
reach all the trapped vehicles, thereby getting an accurate count.
After that, the highway will be demolished.
   Rumors of survivors periodically swept through the crowds of
rescue workers, reporters and bystanders _ only to be knocked down
by officials each time.
   Wednesday night brought reports that a rescuer had touched a
live human hand in the wreckage. It was a false alarm.
   Losorio said he sneaked in, without permission, between the
levels Wednesday night and spotted the forms of four or five people
in their mangled vehicles.
   They may have been unconscious, he said. But he left because of
the danger, and he agreed with rescue leaders' caution about
sending workers into dangerous sections.
   ``All that might happen is someone else would get hurt,'' he
said.
   A burly carpenter who declined to give his name said he had seen
incredible bravery by his fellow carpenters and ironworkers.
   ``I saw people crawling in there in places where they weren't
sure a branch was holding them up, running torches in places they
weren't sure there was gas because they had to. ...
   ``Four carpenters worked 'til 2 this morning and went to their
regular jobs at 7 and they'll be back tonight,'' he said. ``We're
here just because we believe in it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
