<FIRST>u a PM-ArtilleryAccident     10-20 0231</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Artillery Accident,0234</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soldiers Charged in Artillery Accident That Killed Three</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Nickoles cq</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT SILL, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Army charged two soldiers with
negligent homicide for using too much powder in an artillery round
that strayed and killed three soldiers last month, officials said
today.
   Sgt. Edward C. Tyler, 26, of Washington, D.C., and Spec.
Nickoles W. Holly, 24, of Canton, Ohio, were told Wednesday that
they were being charged in military court with negligent homicide
and dereliction of duty through negligence, said Sheila Samples, a
spokeswoman at Fort Sill.
   The stray round struck near 80 soldiers on a rifle range outside
the target area and injured 24 as well as killing three.
   Tyler, a howitzer battery section chief, and Holly, a No. 2
cannoneer, are accused of using too much powder, which caused the
105mm howitzer round to land outside the designated impact area,
the Army said.
   Ms. Samples said the two were not in confinement and were still
performing their duties with C Battery, 2nd Battalion, 2nd Field
Artillery at Fort Sill. She said, however, that they were not
firing cannons.
   Ms. Samples said that if the Fort Sill commander, Maj. Gen.
Raphael J. Hallada, convenes a general court-martial and the men
are convicted of both charges, the maximum sentence would be a bad
conduct discharge and 15 months confinement with loss of pay and
allowances.
</TEXT>
