<FIRST>u a PM-PentagonProbe 1stLd-Writethru a0609 10-20 0367</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pentagon Probe, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0609,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Sperry Official Admits Role in Bribery Scheme</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS pvs 3rd graf, Lavelle, a, to CORRECT maximum fines to $30,000
sted $500,000</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former Sperry Corp. marketing executive
pleaded guilty today to charges he participated in a scheme to
bribe a Navy official as part of an effort to get a lucrative
electronics contract.
   Frank J. Lavelle, 68, pleaded guilty to conspiracy and bribery
in connection with payment of $400,000 to Garland L. Tomlin, Jr., a
former Navy procurement official.
   Lavelle, a former marketing director for Sperry's Clearwater,
Fla., facility, faces a possible 20-year prison sentence and fines
of $30,000 for his involvement in the bribery scheme that included
another Sperry official and a defense consultant for the company.
   Tomlin, 59, has already pleaded guilty to charges he took
$400,000 from Sperry and $75,000 from Honeywell Inc. to provide
confidential bid information on a multimillion-dollar contract for
maintaining electronic components of Navy weapons.
   Lavelle admitted that he introduced Tomlin to Charles F.
Gardner, a former Sperry executive on Long Island, N.Y., who has
also pleaded guilty to charges arising from his role in the
Pentagon procurement scandal.
   Lavelle told Gardner that Tomlin wanted a ``nest egg'' for his
retirement. Gardner obtained permission from another official of
Sperry to approve the payments.
   The money was funneled to an offshore account that Tomlin kept
in the Bahamas by James G. Neal, a consultant who worked for
Sperry, which became part of the Unisys Corp. following a merger
with Burroughs Corp.
   U.S. District Judge Claude Hilton scheduled Lavelle's sentencing
for Jan. 12, 1990.
   Former Unisys marketing executive Dennis Mitchell, 42, meanwhile
received a 90-day sentence in a halfway house for his guilty plea
to participate in a scheme to pay $4,000 in illegal campaign
contributions to several members of Congress.
   Mitchell was also placed on two years' probation and ordered to
perform 100 hours of community service.
   The contributions were funneled through Unisys consultants at
the direction of Gardner to various House members involved in
defense appropriations. They included Congressmen Les Aspin, the
Wisconsin Democrat who chairs the House Armed Services Committee.
</TEXT>
