<DOCNO> AP891020-0143 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-89 1444EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-SFQuake-RealEstate     10-20 0472</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SF Quake-Real Estate,0483</SECOND>
<HEAD>Experts Expect Quake to Cause No Long-Term Effects on Real Estate</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-SF Quake, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By E. SCOTT RECKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Will lofty prices for California real estate
tumble along with the roadways, bridges and homes devastated by
this week's quake? Don't bet the house on it, especially in the
eternally optimistic Golden State.
   ``I've been here for over 60 years, and I've been through them
all including the 1933 earthquake (that hit Long Beach), and that
was a bummer,'' said Thelma Orloff of the Fred Sands brokerage in
Los Angeles, who listed Joan Collins' house at $6 million and
Lucille Ball's at $6.9 million.
   ``But an earthquake takes, what, 15 seconds? And then it's over
for 30 years. And if you're fortunate your foundation is safe and
your house is safe,'' she said. ``And if you're taking earthquake
insurance and the house is destroyed, then you rebuild.''
   Prices, meanwhile, ``just keep going up and up,'' Ms. Orloff
said.
   Experts in San Francisco said some multimillion-dollar deals for
office buildings have been put on hold while damage inspections are
made and prices of homes may drop briefly because of the Northern
California quake.
   But those effects will be temporary, they suggested,
particularly because severe damage is limited to a few older areas,
roadways and bridges. Even in San Francisco's Marina district,
devastation was limited to eight square blocks of old homes built
on landfill _ perhaps one-tenth of the district itself.
   ``You hate to say it's not devastated that much, but there's
only small pockets that have been substantially damaged in the
city,'' San Francisco Realtors Association President Victor Makras
said Friday.
   ``No one's phone is ringing to buy today. Everyone is working
with their present buyers to educate and comfort them,'' Makras
said. ``But I think that once the city services are back and up and
rolling, we will be back to a similar situation to what we had.''
   Prices will intimidate people more than earthquakes in the long
run, said California Association of Realtors spokesman Joel Singer.
   In August, just 10 percent of the households in the Bay Area
could afford the area's median-priced home of $272,016, as
calculated by a realty board ``affordability index,'' which among
other things assumes a 20 percent down payment, average loan rate
and a 30-year loan.
   Harold A. Ellis, the chairman and chief executive of San
Francisco-based Grubb &amp; Ellis, a major national broker for
commercial and residential real estate, said deals would be delayed
while buyers and lenders assess potential damages.
   But Ellis said San Francisco's commercial real estate market had
been picking up since spring, buoyed by a general upturn in the
area's economy, and he and Makras predict that trend will continue.
   ``I think memories will be very short,'' Ellis said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891020-0144 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-89 1431EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Pravda Bjt   10-20 0787</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pravda, Bjt,0805</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pravda Gets New Editor: Gorbachev Aide</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The millions of Soviets who see the world through
the gray pages of the Communist Party daily Pravda were told Friday
their newspaper had a new chief: a reformist philosopher and top
aide to Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   The appointment of Ivan T. Frolov as Pravda's editor seems to
consolidate the Soviet president's grip on the flagship party
daily, which has noticeably lagged behind other official newspapers
in printing the sort of eye-opening criticism encouraged by the
Kremlin's campaign for ``glasnost,'' or more openness.
   As Pravda's circulation has sagged to 9.3 million, that of more
feisty publications such as Ogonyok and Arguments and Facts has
soared. Thus, the influence on public opinion of the party's most
authoritative newspaper was visibly on the wane.
   A joke shows the current popular view of the newspaper, which
was founded by Vladimir I. Lenin in 1912 as an instrument to
overthrow the Russian czar, and whose name means ``truth.''
   ``There's no truth in Izvestia,'' goes the joke, referring to
the Soviet government's evening paper whose name means ``news.''
And, the joke continues, ``there's no news in Pravda.''
   Frolov, 60, erstwhile editor of the party theoretical monthly
journal Kommunist, replaces Viktor G. Afanasyev, a white-haired
holdover from the era of Leonid I. Brezhnev, Sovie leader from 1964
to 1982. Afanasyev, 66, had served as Pravda's editor-in-chief for
13 years.
   Western sources identify the Russian-born graduate of Moscow
University's Philosophy Department as Gorbachev's personal adviser
on ideological matters. Frolov is also reputed to be the country's
top biomedical ethicist and in the 1960s criticized Stalin's
henchman, biologist Trofim Lysenko, for waging an ideological
witchhunt against colleagues that led to the exile, torture and
death of many talented scientists.
   In the 1970s, Frolov reportedly fell from favor because of his
reformist views. He was rehabilitated after Gorbachev became Soviet
leader in 1985.
   Frolov's latest appointment was made by the ruling party
Politburo and announced by Pravda in a page one report on the
Politburo's Thursday meeting. The report was also read on state-run
TV Thursday night.
   A Pravda worker said Friday that Frolov had not yet started
work. Gorbachev was expected to go to the paper's headquarters _ on
Pravda Street in northwest Moscow _ to present Frolov personally to
the staff, the worker said.
   Afanasyev, the No. 1 journalist in the Soviet pecking order by
virtue of his position as Pravda's chief editor and chairman of the
official Union of Journalists, had spoken out for glasnost, once
complaining there were still ``restricted zones'' where coverage
wasn't permitted.
   But he still favored keeping government processes under strong
Communist Party control, rejected the notion that there should be
competing political parties, and warned against allowing criticism
of Communist policy to go too far.
   His clout as Pravda editor was considerable: he once revealed he
was allowed to attend Politburo meetings. But under his tutelage,
Pravda printed the same terse Tass bulletins on the Politburo's
doings that appear in every other Soviet paper, and little more.
   Frolov has been working as an assistant to Gorbachev, the
party's general secretary, Tass said in a brief biographical note.
In that post, Soviet sources say, he helped author a major change
in the philosophical underpinnings of Kremlin foreign policy.
   For decades, the Soviets were ideologically committed to aiding
the worldwide class struggle, but in 1987, presumably due to
Gorbachev's impetus, they proclaimed instead their adherence to
``universal human values,'' meaning they would cooperate with
regimes once regarded as enemies.
   Frolov, a doctor of philosophical sciences, headed the journal
Questions of Philosophy in 1986-77 and has been chairman of the
nation's Philosophical Society since 1987, the same year he became
an aide to Gorbachev.
   He served as chief editor of Kommunist in 1986-87, watershed
years in the elaboration of party doctrine when the Gorbachev-era
policies of ``glasnost'' and ``perestroika,'' or reconstruction,
were being hammered out and put to practical use.
   According to Tass, Frolov also wrote a book along with another
top party official fated to become a Gorbachev adviser, Vadim
Zagladin, titled ``Global Problems of Our Times: Scientific and
Global Aspects.''
   Frolov is a member of the party's policy-making Central
Committee and its Ideological Commission, and a member of the
prestigious Soviet Academy of Sciences department of law and
philosophy. He also has a seat in the new Soviet parliament, the
Congress of People's Deputies.
   Western references report Frolov was a philosophy student at
Moscow State University in 1953, the same period the future Raisa
Gorbachev was enrolled there to study the same subject. Gorbachev,
the son of a southern Russian peasant, was in the university's law
school at the time.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
