<FIRST>u a PM-High-RiseFire 1stLd-Writethru a0537 10-20 0272</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-High-Rise Fire, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0537,0274</SECOND>
<HEAD>Firefighters Extinguish High-Rise Fire from Above</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with fire shutting offices of state Supreme
Court, appeals court, attorney general. Deletes outdated material. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fire in a 21-story high-rise today shut the
local offices of the state's courts and the state attorney general
just days after a major earthquake closed those same offices in San
Francisco.
   The fire was limited to an unoccupied machinery room on top of
the building, but other offices were closed while firefighters
inspected the building, said city Fire Department spokesman Greg
Acevedo.
   More than 250 firefighters battled the blaze, which broke out
about 12:35 a.m. and was doused about 40 minutes later, Acevedo
said.
   Three helicopters transported crews to the roof of the building
where firefighters gained control of the blaze from above, he said.
   ``The firefighters on the roof obviously played a big role in
putting the fire out because the building was tall,'' Acevedo said.
   Firefighters were hampered slightly by work in the building to
remove asbestos insulation, Acevedo said. He said no one was inside
the structure when the fire started and there were no injuries
reported.
   Firefighters were not sure what caused the fire, Acevedo said,
adding that no damage estimate was available.
   The Wilshire district, which includes several high-rise office
buildings, is located a little more than one mile west of downtown.
   On Tuesday, a 6.9-magnitude quake seriously damaged the historic
state office building in San Francisco, making unsafe the offices
of Attorney General John Van de Kamp, the state Supreme Court and
Court of Appeals.
</TEXT>
