<DOCNO> AP891020-0146 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-89 1508EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-China-Quake     10-20 0665</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Quake,0685</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thousands Homeless in Quake</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 50,000 peasants whose homes were destroyed
by earthquakes prepared Friday to spend a second night outdoors on
the windy north China plain.
   No new deaths were reported Friday, leaving the toll at 29 dead
with more than 150 injured. Many peasants said they survived
because the first quake Wednesday night woke them up and sent them
outdoors. A stronger quake early Thursday brought their homes down.
   Two more strong aftershocks were felt Friday morning.
   ``This was the worst quake we've ever had,'' Liu Rongzhen, a
peasant in Xicaitian Village in Shanxi province, told a Western
reporter. About half the 230 houses in the village, made of mud or
sticks and branches, suffered varying degrees of damage.
   All the homes were destroyed in nearby Bucun, a village of
1,280. Two villagers were killed _ a man and the elderly mother he
was trying to carry to safety.
   The survivors rigged tents of quilts and straw and built small
fires Thursday night, and prepared to do the same Friday night.
   Temperatures in Beijing, 135 miles to the east, have been
dipping below 40 degrees at night with a chill wind. Weather in the
quake-affected area is similar.
   The Ministry of Civil Affairs, in charge of emergency rescue,
refused Friday to answer questions and referred callers to the
International Department of the Ministry of Foreign Economic
Relations and Trade.
   There, an official who gave his name only as Xu said 11,000
homes had been destroyed in Shanxi and Hebei provinces, and 50,000
people were homeless. He had no other information.
   Shanxi villagers seemed dazed and unsure about how to begin
rebuilding. ``We just hope that the earthquakes stop,'' Liu said.
   He said he lost his home and most of his possessions, worth a
total of about $800. He and others said it would not be possible to
rebuild their homes before winter sets in, but they had no idea
what they would do for shelter.
   Some victims dug with shovels and poles beneath the mounds of
mud and stone that were their homes, but found little that could be
salvaged. One woman found an unbroken light bulb.
   Someone else found a black and white television, a prized
possession in poor areas such as Shanxi, and set it carefully on a
pile of straw.
   National TV broadcast its first report on the quake and said the
government had set up a special fund of $53,850 for quake aid.
   The television showed boxes of medicine being unloaded from a
pickup truck. An official distributed thick pancakes, a local
staple, from a pile heaped high on the ground.
   The report said more than 1,000 soldiers and medical workers
were sent into the area. Footage shot by Shanxi provincial TV but
not shown on the national news showed doctors in makeshift clinics
treating people with broken bones and badly bloodied heads.
   The national news focused on local officials arriving to inspect
damage, and only briefly showed an adobe home in ruins and doctors
treating a victim. The official media has given little attention to
the quake, perhaps because of continued popular belief that natural
disasters spell out heaven's displeasure with the ruler.
   ``Although losses were heavy, the morale of the masses is
stable,'' the television news said. There has been no announcement
of plans to provide temporary shelter for the homeless or rebuild
the destroyed homes.
   The State Seismology Bureau has said it is unlikely that more
strong aftershocks will hit in the near future.
   The bureau said the Thursday morning quake, which measured 6.1
on the Richter scale, was the strongest to hit northern China since
a 1976 earthquake that leveled most of the northeast city of
Tangshan and killed 240,000 people.
   The Richter scale gauges the energy released by an earthquake,
as measured by the ground motion recorded on a seismograph.
Tuesday's earthquake in Northern California was measured at 6.9 on
the scale.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
