<FIRST>r i AM-Commonwealth-Retreat     10-20 0415</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commonwealth-Retreat,0427</SECOND>
<HEAD>Commonwealth Leaders Retreat to Legendary Isles</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Commonwealth</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER O'LOUGHLIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LANGKAWI, Malaysia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Margaret Thatcher and her husband,
Denis, sipped fruit punch from parrot-shaped pottery mugs while
Benazir Bhutto zipped around on an electric cart with her husband,
Asif Zardari, and their baby son.
   It was the beginning of a weekend break from international
diplomacy for the prime ministers of Britain and Pakistan, who are
attending a summit with other movers and shakers of the 49-nation
Commonwealth.
   National leaders were bedecked with garlands of seashells on
arrival at the plush new resort on Langkawi Island in the Straits
of Malacca, 210 miles northwest of Kuala Lumpur, site of the
week-long summit.
   The lush green island, whose name means ``sea eagle and white
rock,'' is the largest of 99 in the Langkawi group near Malaysia's
border with Thailand, where the Indian Ocean meets the straits.
   After the fruit punch, Margaret and Denis Thatcher _ she in a
green dress and white shoes, he in a light gray suit _ were taken
to their chalet in a three-wheeled pedal-powered push chair called
a becak.
   Ms. Bhutto and her family rode in a battery-powered electric
cart normally used for baggage at the Pelangi Beach Resort, which
opened six months ago.
   She got in first and Zardari handed in Bilawal Asif, their son.
Mother and child posed for photographs before they drove off.
   Each government leader was assigned one of the two-bedroom
chalets, which are grouped in the 25-acre complex to resemble a
kampung, or Malay village. The hotel was closed to all but the
dignitaries from the organization of Britain and its former
colonies.
   Buses escorted by police collected them at the airport after the
55-minute flight from Kuala Lumpur to this island of 33,000 people.
The road to the hotel eight miles away, winds past coconut
plantations and rice paddies, was guarded by soldiers posted at
500-yard intervals.
   Friday night's buffet dinner included seven choices of fish,
tropical fruit, prawn fritters, seafood paella and steamed yams.
   A lobby notice board said the movie ``Batman'' and assorted
cartoons were the evening's entertainment.
   Others could contemplate the legend of the lovely Princess
Mahsuri, whose tomb is a tourist attraction.
   Once upon a time, the princess was involved in court intrigue
and sentenced to death after unjust accusations that she was
unfaithful to her husband. Visitors are told she placed a curse on
the island that denied it prosperity for seven generations.
</TEXT>
