<FIRST>r i AM-Marcos     10-20 0286</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Marcos,0294</SECOND>
<HEAD>Imelda Marcos Says She'll Compromise if She Can Go Home</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ferdinand Marcos' widow, Imelda, is
willing to compromise with the government if President Corazon
Aquino allows her to return home from exile in Hawaii, a senator
said Friday.
   Sen. Joseph Estrada, who arrived Thursday from Hawaii where he
attended Marcos' funeral, said Mrs. Marcos told him she is willing
to negotiate with the government in exchange for her return to the
Philippines.
   Marcos died Sept. 28 in exile in Hawaii three years after his
ouster in the civilian-military revolt that ended his 20-year rule
and swept Mrs. Aquino to power. Mrs. Aquino has refused to allow
his body or any immediate member of the Marcos family into the
Philippines, citing national security concerns.
   ``She told me that she is willing to compromise (with) whatever
President Aquino wants,'' said Estrada, a member of the Liberal
Party, which supports Mrs. Aquino. ``But compromise with dignity.''
   When asked if compromise meant surrendering the wealth the
Marcoses allegedly stole during Marcos' rule, Estrada replied:
``That's possible.'' He did not elaborate.
   Mrs. Marcos ``should be brought home to face all those charges
and not be convicted without trial,'' Estrada said.
   The Aquino government has filed 35 civil suits against the
Marcoses, accusing them of stealing up to $10 billion in public
funds. Mrs. Aquino has said she will not speak to Mrs. Marcos until
the money is returned.
   Estrada, who served as a mayor of a Manila suburb during the
Marcos administration, said Mrs. Marcos wanted to be present during
embezzlement trials against the Marcos family.
   Mrs. Marcos also faces racketeering charges in New York and is
free on bail. She denies the charges.
</TEXT>
