<DOCNO> AP891020-0153 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-89 1545EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Pope-Poland     10-20 0493</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pope-Poland,0511</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pope Welcomes Polish Prime Minister</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto ROM1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTOR L. SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II on Friday welcomed
Poland's first non-Communist prime minister in 40 years and told
him there must be no turning back from political change.
   Tadeusz Mazowiecki, a longtime Solidarity activist who came to
power Aug. 24, thanked the Polish-born pope for his support
``during the difficult years'' _ referring to the suppression of
Solidarity after the martial law crackdown in 1981.
   Mazowiecki, a Catholic intellectual and an old friend of the
pope, made Rome his first foreign visit since his appointment as
the East bloc's first non-Communist premier.
   The pope called the private 20-minute meeting ``historic.''
   In an emotional reunion, the men embraced outside the pope's
private library. John Paul told an aide there was no need for
introductions.
   Later, Mazowiecki said the meeting was the ``crowning, the fruit
of the dialogue, of which today we see the results.''
   John Paul turned toward a Polish TV crew and responded in
Polish, `We hope there's no turning back.''
   ``This is not possible,'' seconded Foreign Minister Krzysztof
Skubiszewski.
   John Paul's return to Poland in June 1979, eight months after
his election to the papacy, helped spark demands for democracy that
led to the formation of Solidarity, the first non-Communist labor
movement in the Soviet bloc.
   Mazowiecki told a news conference that ``Polish-Soviet relations
are at their most crucial moment.''
   He said there are many problems, but one of the biggest is
economic collaboration.
   ``We want to develop our economy through the East and the
West,'' he said, noting that he would discuss these problems when
Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze comes to Warsaw next
week. During that visit a date for a Mazowiecki visit to Moscow
will be set.
   He also repeated his plea for immediate help from the West,
saying his country needs loans, investments and emergency food aid
within the next two months to help it through the harsh Polish
winter.
   The church, which has historically played a pivotal role in this
overwhelmingly Roman Catholic country, took part in the long
negotiations that led to elections this year and approval of a
24-member Cabinet that includes 12 Solidarity members and four
Communists.
   As evidence of the change sweeping the Soviet bloc, John Paul on
Friday ordained as bishops the Vatican's first ambassador to Poland
since the Communists broke diplomatic relations after World War II
and the first Roman Catholic bishop in Soviet Byelorussia in 60
years.
   ``Isn't this a sign of the changes taking place, which are
happening for the good of all believers,'' John Paul said in his
homily in the service in St. Peter's Basilica.
   Aides said Mazowiecki and the pope have met some 20 times during
John Paul's 11-year pontificate, most recently when Solidarity
leader Lech Walesa came to Rome in April.
   The Polish pope and prime minister also met privately at lunch
after the audience.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
