<FIRST>r i AM-Thailand-Refugees     10-20 0423</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Thailand-Refugees,0437</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hopes Dim for Repatriation of Cambodian Refugees</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRUNNSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The failure of recent peace efforts has
dimmed prospects for repatriation of the more than 300,000
Cambodians in refugee camps on the Thai side of the border, aid
workers said Friday.
   ``Repatriation is undoubtedly farther away from us than it
appeared even three months ago,'' said Urs Boegli, head of the
Thailand office of the International Committee of the Red Cross.
   Many aid officials had felt increased diplomatic efforts put a
settlement within reach, but an international conference in Paris
in June did not resolve the civil war, which began with the
Vietnamese invasion of December 1978.
   About 300,000 of the Cambodians who fled the brutal Khmer Rouge
regime or the invasion that ended it remain in the U.N.-assisted
camps.
   Fighting nearby has intensified since Vietnamese soldiers left
Cambodia late in September, and Boegli said the camps are exposed
to increased danger.
   ``Do we have to fear a full-fledged attack on the camps?'' he
said. ``Of course this possibilty has to remain part of our
security planning.''
   He said the presence of guerrillas in the camps increased the
danger.
   The United Nations recently reduced food aid to the largest
camp, Site 2, on grounds the rebels were diverting supplies to
their own use. Khmer Rouge guerrillas control the camp, which
houses 140,000 refugees.
   Although repatriation may be delayed, aid agencies still must
prepare for it, said S.A.M.S. Kibria, U.N. special representative
for Cambodian refugees.
   ``The time has come to look beyond our established role of
providing basic emergency relief and consider greater emphasis on
social program to support and rebuild'' Cambodian society, he said.
   ``There are children as old as 10 or 12 ... who have never known
life outside a refugee camp,'' Kibria said, and the longer they
remain, ``the more serious becomes the risk that ... we will return
to Cambodia whole communities of socially handicapped persons
unable to earn a living or readjust to conditions in their own
country.''
   Kibria said more money was needed to finance reintegration
programs.
   He also expressed concern about reports that guerrillas may move
refugees back into Cambodia without involving international
organizations.
   ``Any movement of the population into Cambodia which lacks the
assurances of safety and freedom of choice cannot be supported,''
he said.
   Toshiyuki Niwa, director of the U.N. Border Relief Operation,
said the breakdown of peace talks could increase frustration among
the refugees in camps already plagued by murder, rape and other
crimes.
</TEXT>
