<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--Emory-SovietProfessors     10-20 0194</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Emory-Soviet Professors,0197</SECOND>
<HEAD>Carter's Appeal Helps Establish Soviet Professorship at Emory</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former President Carter's appeal to Soviet
President Mikhail Gorbachev helped Emory University establish a
continuing teaching post for scholars from the Soviet Union.
   An agreement signed in September will establish a visiting
professorship in Soviet law, with a several Soviet legal scholars
occupying a chairman post, Emory President James T. Laney announced
Thursday.
   Emory Professor Harold J. Berman, who negotiated the agreement,
said Soviet professors have occasionally visited and taught at
American universities in the past, but this is the first time a
Soviet academic institution has agreed to staff a position in a
U.S. university on a continuing basis.
   ``It could not have been brought to fruition without the help of
... Carter, who wrote a letter to Soviet President Gorbachev urging
him personally to endorse the proposal,'' Berman said.
   Laney said he signed the agreement with B.N. Topornin, director
of the Institute of State and Law of the USSR Academy of Sciences.
The first professor to visit will be Igor Ivanovich Lukashuk, a
scholar in public international law, who will teach at Emory during
the spring semester.
