<HEAD>Latest Flight Raises to 117 the Number of Cubans Returned to Homeland</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TALLADEGA, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States this week returned
seven Cubans to their homeland, raising to 117 the number deported
who took part in the 1980 Freedom Flotilla.
   Dana Newell, speaking for the Talladega Correctional
Institution, said Wednesday's flight was the 18th since the program
began last Dec. 2.
   She said 108 Cubans remain at the facility, with about 15 others
en route to Talladega for processing for the repatriation program.
   About 125,000 people came to this country in the 1980 boatlift
from Mariel, Cuba.
   In 1984, Cuban President Fidel Castro agreed to take back 2,746
Cubans convicted of serious crimes in this country. The government
sent scores of Cubans to the Talladega facility on the heels of
massive riots in prisons at Atlanta and Oakdale, La.

