<FIRST>u w AM-Impeachment-Color     10-20 0652</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Impeachment-Color,640</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hastings Appears Confident and Announces Political Plans</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Hastings Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The voice of Alcee L. Hastings boomed out of
the drizzle in the chill air outside the Senate entrance to the
Capitol.
   Hastings had just been convicted on the first of many articles
of impeachment, an act that formally removed him from office as a
federal district judge for the southern district of Florida.
   The former judge had a surprise in store.
   In the Senate chamber, Sen. Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va., the
Senate's president pro tempore, gravely asked the question yet
another time:
   ``Senators, how say you? Is the respondent, Alcee L. Hastings,
guilty or not guilty?''
   And the voices came: ``Guilty,'' ``guilty,'' ``not guilty,''
``guilty,'' over and over.
   Hastings had left the voices behind after the second vote to
convict him, striding from the chamber to receive bearhugs from
supporters. In a morning consumed by votes by senators soberly
rising from their gleaming mahogany desks, he would be convicted on
eight counts, acquitted on three.
   Outside on the steps, Alcee Hastings, who had been the first
black federal judge in Florida history, looked out over the
thrusting cameras and microphones, his commanding voice penetrating
through the crowd.
   His conviction was unjust, he said. The fact that a jury had in
1983 acquitted him on similar charges marked his impeachment before
the Senate with the brand of double jeopardy and dealt a ``severe
blow to the cornerstone of justice _ the jury system.'',
   Hastings then took a wholly unexpected tack.
   Defiant, smiling, appearing supremely self-confident, Hastings
said that as far as he is concerned his career was far from over.
   ``Now that the Senate has forced a career change on me, I must
go forward,'' he said.
   He will go forward, he said, to become a Democratic candidate
for governor of Florida, to become a far from ordinary candidate.
   Hastings said he had called his mother immediately after the
first of the votes, first to tell her the result, then to say,
``we're off and running.''
   ``I think I have an excellent chance,'' he said. ``...I don't
have anything to lose by offering an interest in the issues facing
the voters of Florida. I think I can take the campaign to a level
that everybody will be proud of.
   ``Quite frankly, I think that not only can I be elected, I think
I will be ... I'm going to enjoy being governor.''
   A reporter asked: ``Why do you think you can be elected after
what just happened?''
   Hastings responded: ``Because I think that Floridians are tired
of ordinariness. And if there's anything else I bring to it, it's
this experience, it's not ordinary.
   ``Oh, I will hear signals,'' Hastings said. ``I will hear, `Oh,
it's shameful that he should do these kinds of things.'
   ``Let me tell you, my mama had a man; she did not have anybody
that was afraid of the system. I think change needs to take place
and I'm going to be involved in that change until I die.''
   He said there are no legal barriers to his candidacy.
   ``Banishment is a fiction,'' he insisted, and, pointing upwards
in the direction of the Senate chamber, added: ``And what we just
saw was extremely fictional ... There are those of you who will say
I should be banished in infamy, I know nothing that I have done
that requires that.''
   But Hastings also made clear that there may be something
quixotic in his candidacy.
   ``I will go forward with my life and I'll let the voters of
Florida tell me that I'm a terrible person _ and I will go forward
with my life,'' he said.
   Was he at all downcast by the fact of his conviction?
   ``I feel just fine,'' Hastings said, crisply emphasizing each
word. ``Perhaps better than I did quite some time ago.''
</TEXT>
