<FIRST>r w AM-Congress-Indictments     10-20 0621</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Congress-Indictments,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Garcia 15th Member of Congress Indicted in Last Decade</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Wedtech-Garcia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Robert Garcia, D-N.Y., on Friday became
the 15th person in the last decade to be indicted on criminal
charges while a member of Congress.
   Garcia was convicted along with his wife, Jane Lee, in U.S.
District Court in New York of extorting payoffs from the Wedtech
Corp. in exchange for exercising political influence for the
military contractor. They were acquitted of bribery and receiving
illegal gratuities.
   Earlier this year:
   _Former Rep. Pat Swindall, R-Ga., was found guilty in June of
lying to a federal grand jury about a money-laundering scheme.
   Convicted on nine perjury charges involving his attempt to
negotaite an $850,000 home loan form an undercover agent posing as
a money launderer, Swindall, 38, was sentenced in August to a year
in prison and fined $30,000.
   _Rep. Donald E. Lukens, 58, R-Ohio, was convicted in May 26 of
contributing to the delinquency and unruliness of a minor, a
misdemeanor. A Franklin County, Ohio, jury found him guilty of
having sex with the girl last November.
   Lukens was sentenced to 30 days in jail and fined $1,000. He is
still a member of Congress and has said he plans to seek
re-election.
   Garcia is not the first congressman to be convicted in the
scandal surrounding Wedtech, a minority-owned New York City machine
shop that had won no-bid U.S. Army contracts.
   Then-Rep. Mario Biaggi, D-N.Y., was convicted in August 1988 of
racketeering, mail fraud and accepting bribes from Wedtech in
exchange for his influence.
   Biaggi, 71, resigned a day after his conviction and was later
sentenced to eight years in prison and a $242,000 fine.
   Biaggi also was convicted in November 1987 of accepting an
illegal gratuity _ a paid vacation _ for helping an ailing New York
shipyard. He was sentenced to 2{ years in prison and fined $500,000
in that case.
   Other members of Congress indicted since 1979:
   _Rep. Harold E. Ford, D-Tenn., charged in April 1987 with bank,
mail and tax fraud. No trial date has been set. He is still in
Congress.
   _Rep. Bobbi Fiedler, R-Calif., indicted Jan. 23, 1986, along
with an aide on charges she tried to buy off an opponent for the
GOP Senate nomination in California. The charges subsequently were
dismissed by a Superior Court judge in Los Angeles; Fiedler lost
the primary.
   _Then-Rep. George Hansen, R-Idaho, indicted in April 1983 and
convicted one year later on charges of violating the Ethics in
Government Act by failing to report $333,978 in loans and other
transactions on his financial disclosure forms. Hansen was freed in
October 1987 after serving nearly one year of a five-to-15-month
sentence.
   _Sen. Harrison A. Williams Jr., D-N.J., convicted in May 1981 on
charges stemming from the FBI's Abscam investigation, including
conspiracy, bribery, conflict of interest, receiving an unlawful
gratuity and interstate travel in aid of a racketeering enterprise.
   Williams resigned from the Senate in March 1982. He was paroled
from a halfway house in January 1986 after serving nearly two years
of a three-year sentence. Six House members also were indicted as a
result of the undercover Abscam investigation, and all served
prison terms. They were:
   Rep. Raymond Lederer, D-Pa.; Rep. Michael Myers, D-Pa.; Rep.
John Jenrette, D-S.C.; Rep. John Murphy, D-N.Y.; Rep. Frank
Thompson, D-N.J.; and Rep. Richard Kelly, R-Fla.
   None of the seven indicted in Abscam are still serving in
Congress.
   _Then-Rep. Claude Leach, D-La., was indicted in July 1979 on
charges of buying votes in the 1978 election and violating federal
campaign finance laws. He was acquitted of some vote-buying counts
and the others were dropped, and a federal appeals court dismissed
the charges of campaign finance law violations.
</TEXT>
