<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-89 1532EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-PentagonProbe     10-20 0536</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pentagon Probe,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Sperry Official Admits Role in Bribery Scheme</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former Sperry Corp. marketing executive
admitted in court Friday that he initiated a bribery scheme in
which a Navy official was paid $400,000 to help the company compete
for a lucrative electronics contract.
   Frank J. Lavelle, 68, who was marketing director at the
company's Clearwater, Fla., facility, faces a possible 20-year
prison sentence for participating in the scheme that included other
officials of Sperry, which became part of Unisys Corp. following a
1986 merger with Burroughs Corp.
   Lavelle entered his guilty plea in U.S. District Court on a day
that Dennis Mitchell, a former Unisys marketing executive, was
sentenced to a 90-day term in a halfway house for arranging $4,000
worth of illegal corporate campaign donations to several
congressmen.
   The guilty plea was the latest in a series of more than 20
convictions of defense consultants, corporate executives and
Pentagon employees stemming from the Justice Department's
investigation of defense procurement fraud, nicknamed ``Operation
Ill Wind.''
   Lavelle admitted that he introduced Garland L. Tomlin Jr., a
former Navy procurement official, to Sperry vice-president Charles
F. Gardner, saying that Tomlin wanted a ``nest egg'' for his
eventual retirement from the government.
   Tomlin, 59, already has pleaded guilty to receiving $400,000
from Sperry in 1983 and 1984 and $75,000 from Honeywell Inc., in
exchange for bid information on a multimillion-dollar maintenance
contract on the electronic components of Navy weapons.
   Sperry was eliminated from competition for the contract even
though Tomlin wrote reports favoring the company's proposal and
promoted the bid with other Navy officials.
   Gardner, 59, who was vice president in charge of Sperry's
surveillance and fire control systems unit in Great Neck, N.Y., was
sentenced Sept. 15 to 32 months in federal prison for his role in a
separate bribery scheme.
   According to court papers, Gardner obtained permission from an
unidentified Sperry official before approving the payments to
Tomlin, which were funneled by defense consultant James G. Neal to
an offshore bank account Tomlin kept in the Bahamas.
   Neal, 65, who has been described by prosecutors as ``the banker
for Mr. Gardner and Mr. Gardner's operation'' has received a
27-month prison term for his role in the bribery scheme.
   U.S. District Judge Claude Hilton scheduled Lavelle's sentencing
for Jan. 12, 1990.
   The judge, meanwhile, ordered Mitchell to perform 100 hours of
community service after serving a 90-day term in a halfway house.
   Mitchell admitted arranging, at Gardner's behest, the payment of
$4,000 in illegal corporate campaign contributions to various House
members who had influence over defense issues. They included Rep.
Les Aspin, the Wisconsin Democrat who chairs the House
Appropriations Committee.
   There was no evidence that the lawmakers knew they were
receiving illegal contributions, which were made in the names of
defense consultants hired by Unisys.
   Mitchell, who could have received a 10-year prison term, told
Hilton: ``I am sorry for my deeds and I am ready to face up to it
here.''
   While acknowledging Mitchell's cooperation with the Justice
Department's continuing investigation, prosecutor Lee J. Radek said
his crime was a ``very serious offense ... that goes to the heart
of the electoral process.''
</TEXT>
