<FIRST>u w AM-US-Mideast     10-20 0522</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Mideast,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shamir Urges US to Encourage Palestinians</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration appeared Friday to be
at a critical point in its drive to open Mideast peace talks as
Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir appealed for U.S. help in
drawing Palestinian Arabs into negotiations.
   A senior U.S. official said Secretary of State James A. Baker
III might soon decide to turn his attention to other foreign policy
issues. But diplomatic sources questioned the notion that Baker was
reaching a dead-end.
   ``You have a dialogue at the very highest level. It is very
substantial. They are discussing substantial ideas that might lead
to a breakthrough,'' said the sources, who spoke only on condition
of anonymity.
   Shamir, in a letter to Baker delivered on Wednesday, urged the
administration to help overcome ``intimidation'' keeping
Palestinians on the West Bank and Gaza from participating in the
prime minister's proposal for elections, the sources said.
   Shamir also asked Baker to try to enlist moderate Arab
governments, such as Morocco and Jordan, to join with Egypt in
trying to implement the elections proposal, the sources said.
   Baker followed up the letter in a telephone coversation with
Shamir Thursday evening and with Israeli Foreign Minister Moshe
Arens on Friday morning. But the details were not disclosed as
Baker took off for a long weekend at his ranch in Wyoming.
   Before he left, a senior U.S. official said Baker was ``not
going to pursue this from here to eternity.'' Also, the official
told reporters after demanding anonymity, Baker was giving the
problem ``100 percent but there could be a limit to how long you
continue.''
   Among the main roadblocks are rejection of the election proposal
by the Palestine Liberation Organization's Central Council and
Shamir's insistence that PLO members not participate in talks with
Israel.
   The State Department, after accusing SHamir of hindering the
process with unhelpful and disappointing remarks, offered
assurances Thursday it was not trying to pressure Israel into
talking to the PLO, which in its covenant is committed to
dismantling the Jewish state.
   Shamir, meanwhile, thanked Baker in the letter for his efforts
to implement the election proposal, which is designed to produce
limited self-rule for Palestinians on the West Bank and Gaza and
negotiations five years later on an overall settlement.
   The letter was not made public, but the diplomatic sources
dislosed Shamir elaborated in it on his refusal to negotiate with
the PLO and on his election proposal and urged Baker to saek
support for Egypt from modertate Arab countries.
   Also, the sources said, Shamir asked the Bush administration to
discuss the election plan with Palestinian leaders on the West Bank
and in Gaza who are more likely than the PLO to respond favorably.
   After all, Shamir reasoned, the Palestinians in the territories
are the ones who would vote, negotiate and ultimately live under
the arrangement worked out with Israel.
   The prime minister stressed the point local Palestinians need
bolstering so they will not be afraid to stand up to
``intimidation,'' the sources said, adding: ``This is very
high-profile, intimate diplomacy. They may come to an agreement.''
</TEXT>
