<FIRST>u a PM-SFQuake-Bush 10thLd-Writethru a0703-a070fficialsofislandcalledWinakung
10-20 0975</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SF Quake-Bush, 10th Ld-Writethru, a0703-a0706-a0662,980</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Gets First-Hand Look at Collapsed Freeway</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Combines pvs.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA CRUZ, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush toured the
earthquake-ravaged San Francisco Bay area today, saying ``I'm
deeply moved'' as he got a first-hand look at a collapsed freeway
that trapped rush-hour motorists. The president said he would ``do
what's needed to be done'' to speed federal aid.
   Administration officials worked on a program of assistance as
the president made his brief trip. Transportation Secretary Samuel
Skinner offered no pricetag but said the federal government would
take on ``a very, very major role in helping California.''
   After stops in Oakland and San Francisco, Bush flew to this
coastal community only a few miles from the epicenter of Tuesday
night's killer earthquake.
   ``We've got to get these disaster centers open and take the
claims,'' he said as he walked down the main street looking at
shattered buildings.
   Bush cited the work of public and private relief agencies and
said, ``God bless those volunteers.''
   ``In terms of what it will cost, I don't know,'' he said. ``But
the federal government will work with these other entities, the
government entities, the private entities, to see the suffering is
alleviated, the restoration begins.''
   He added, ``I'm willing to do what's needed to be done.''
   ``Jesus,'' muttered the president as he walked next to the
two-deck freeway in Oakland, the ground covered with rubble,
including massive chunks of concrete and giant fallen pillars.
Twisted steel girders protruded from the collapsed structure.
   Smashed cars were visible at some points between the upper and
lower decks.
   ``I am deeply moved by this, saddened in some ways, yet very
stimulated by this team effort,'' the president said.
   He complimented rescue teams and said, ``I'm very proud'' of the
military participation.
   He also said he admired ``the way this community is pulling
together ... we'll see what we can do to be part of the answer.''
   Bush, tieless and wearing a flight jacket with the presidential
seal on the right breast, toured the area on foot and chatted with
rescue workers.
   The president took a two-block motorcade to the site of the
Interstate 880 collapse. He was greeted by several California
congressmen, including Democrats Ronald Dellums, Tom Lantos,
Fortney Stark and George Miller.
   San Francisco Mayor Art Agnos, who had attended a briefing by
local officials with Bush on his arrival at Moffett Field, also
accompanied him to the rescue site, staying on the periphery as
Bush chatted with the authorities.
   Agnos had complained earlier that he was snubbed by Vice
President Dan Quayle when Quayle toured the area Wednesday.
   From Oakland, Bush went to the Presidio, a U.S. Army base in San
Francisco, where he met with city officials. The base, on the shore
of San Francisco Bay, is adjacent to the heavily damaged Marina
district.
   Bush announced he was appointing Skinner to coordinate federal
relief efforts.
   The president confessed he had had some second thoughts about
visiting the quake area, not wanting to get in the way. But, he
said he concluded, ``if you don't go _ why it's neglect.''
   Bush also taped a television public service announcement here
seeking to reassure the quake-weary Bay area that help was on the
way.
   Agnos, one of three mayors accompanying the president on his
tour, told Bush: ``We need fast action. We need checks written on
the spot.''
   ``We've got to work with each other,'' Bush told the local
officials.
   Skinner would not say how much money was in the package but
claimed ``it will be substantial.''
   ``These first 90 days virtually all of ... emergency expenses
would be covered, I assume, by the federal government,'' Skinner
said.
   He said cleanup and repair were ``primarily a California
effort'' but the federal government would help in any way it could.
   From Oakland he flew across the bay to San Francisco to tour the
heavily damaged Marina area.
   Bush was greeted at Moffett Field by Sen. Pete Wilson, R-Calif.,
Gov. George Deukmejian and Rep. Norman Mineta, a Democrat who
represents the southern San Francisco Bay area.
   Democrats have pledged at least $2.5 billion in federal funds to
assist quake victims. But Skinner said, ``I don't think the $2.5
billion will have a degree of preciseness attached to it.''
   He said, ``I don't think anybody can tell you at this moment
exactly how much is going to be needed.''
   Bush's trip, on the heels of the tour by Quayle and Skinner, is
part of swift administration action in the wake of complaints that
the federal government responded too slowly after Hurricane Hugo
struck the Caribbean and southeastern United States. Bush went to
South Carolina following the hurricane to assess damage there.
   ``I will be going out there tomorrow to take a look and to
provide encouragement to people,'' Bush said Thursday as
congressional leaders vowed to increase disaster aid for victims of
the quake that has wreaked more than $2 billion in damage.
   House Speaker Tom Foley on Thursday estimated at least $2.5
billion in federal funds would be needed to pay for the quake
assistance. He said the House would vote to provide it in a stopgap
money bill that comes up Tuesday.
   He vowed to come up with the funds but said he did not know
where the money would come from.
   Agnos, a Democrat, had complained that Quayle did not visit him
during his tour of the region on Wednesday. Agnos accused Quayle of
a ``publicity stunt.''
   Fitzwater said Agnos was invited to Quayle's two meetings with
local officials and was offered helicopter transportation to attend
them, but rejected the offers.
   The White House said an initial $273 million will be available
for the area from a pool of $1.1 billion that Congress appropriated
after the devastation caused by Hurricane Hugo.
</TEXT>
