<FIRST>u i AM-EastGermany 1stLd-Writethru a0655 10-20 0890</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-East Germany, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0655,0914</SECOND>
<HEAD>10,000 Pro-Democracy Protesters Rally in Provincial City</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to UPDATE with Berlin appealing to East
Germans to come home, news reports. Pick up 4th pvs, `A West...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GIRARD C. STEICHEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 10,000 pro-democracy supporters staged a
rally in an East German city, opposition leaders said Friday, in
the latest sign that activists will keep up the pressure on the
country's new leader.
   Members of the outlawed pro-democracy group New Forum said the
rally was held in three churches in the city of Zittau Thursday
night and thousands also gathered on the city's market square.
   Loudspeakers were set up so the crowd outside could hear a
debate on reform going on in one of the churches, said Andreas
Schoenfelder, a New Forum member in Zittau.
   Communist East Germany made its first open appeal to the tens of
thousands of citizens who have fled West in recent months to return
home.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Wolfang Meyer said East Berlin's
diplomatic missions would help East Germans return as quickly as
possible.
   ``We want to help anyone, unless there are reasons to prevent
it, to come back home,'' Meyer said.
   More than 55,000 East Germans have fled to West Germany since
July.
   State-run media Friday continued to report critically on
economic and political problems.
   The Communist Party daily Neues Deutschland devoted four pages
to the debate on how to solve the nation's problems ``by improving
socialism.''
   ``Our (Communist) Party is proving that it has the courage to
face the truth,'' the newspaper said in a commentary. ``The party
has renounced window-dressing and its presumptuousness.''
   A West German official, meanwhile, rejected conditions set by
East Germany's new leader, Egon Krenz, for the possible loosening
of travel for East Germans to the West.
   Krenz said Thursday a new law would be drafted to expand travel
rights, but he made it clear that substantial economic and
political hurdles stood in the way of letting everyone travel West.
   Many East Germans say lack of travel freedoms is one of the
worst hardships of the tightly controlled society. It has been one
of the main causes of the exodus of tens of thousands of East
Germans this year to the West.
   Krenz said the government is drafting a new law that could
ultimately ease travel abroad, including to the West, and allow all
East Germans to possess a passport. But he said the biggest
obstacle to freer travel to the West is Bonn's Germany's refusal to
recognize East German citizenship.
   East German leaders say economic problems also pose considerable
obstacles, because East Germans need West German currency for the
visits.
   East Germans cannot now go to a bank and exchange East German
marks for West German ones.
   Dorothee Wilms, who heads West Germany's Ministry for
Inter-German Relations, said Friday that Bonn will not change its
position on the East German citizenship issue, and said East Berlin
already receives millions in hard currency from West Germany.
   Wilms, in an interview with West Germany's ZDF television, said
East Germany gets the hard currency through compulsory currency
exchange from West German tourists and that Bonn pays more than
$270 million a year in connection with transit route agreements
alone.
   ``If East German officials really want to allow their citizens
free travel to the West, then they should use some of this money,''
Wilms said.
   Earlier Friday, Wolfgang Lueder, a member of West German
Chancellor Helmut Kohl's ruling coalition, said Bonn should not
allow East Berlin's apparent readiness to expand travel to the West
``to fail because of money.''
   Lueder was quoted in Cologne's Express newspaper as saying Bonn
should allow East Germans to change money at a one-to-one ratio.
East German currency is not convertible to Western currency.
   ``East German tourists would be really helped if they could
change between 300 and 500 East German marks for the same sum in
West German marks ($162 to $270),'' Lueder was quoted as saying.
   The West German mass-circulation Bild newspaper reported Krenz
and other top Communist leaders met to discuss the refugee problem
that has seriously strained the nation's economy.
   Bild said the discussion centered on whether to simply let all
those who are disenchanted with the system to leave the country in
order to ``maintain total Communist Party control.''
   The newspaper quoted on official as saying: ``That could be 10
million.'' It said another official responded: ``So what, Sweden is
a prosperous land and only has 6 million.''
   East Germany has a population of about 16.6 million.
   In Austria, officials said Friday about 900 East Germans had
crossed from Hungary to Austria en route to West Germany in the
last 24 hours.
   Border guards said the crossings brought to 40,600 the number of
East Germans who have crossed into Austria since Hungary opened its
border for the East Germans Sept. 11.
   Also Friday, East Germany's state-run ADN news agency reported
the Soviet monthy magazine Sputnik will be allowed back into the
country after being banned for nearly a year.
   The magazine was banned after it published several articles
critical of Soviet leader Josef Stalin and questioning the actions
of German Communists before the outbreak of World War II.
   Krenz took over Wednesday from Erich Honecker, who ruled East
Germany for 18 years.
</TEXT>
