<FIRST>u w AM-US-Nicaragua     10-20 0270</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Nicaragua,250</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Accuses Nicaragua of Subversive Activity</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department accused Nicaragua on
Friday of systematically violating Central American peace
agreements by continuing clandestine efforts to send military
equipment to leftist rebels in El Salvador.
   Department spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler made the accusation
after Honduran security forces found large amounts of weapons which
she claimed originated in Nicaragua and were earmarked for the
Salvadoran insurgents, known by the Spanish initials FMLN.
   The seizure occurred at a border crossing between Nicaragua and
Honduras and, according to Ms. Tutwiler, included AK-47s, rifle
grenades, explosives, thousands of rounds of ammunition and FMLN
instruction manuals.
   Honduran officials are currently evaluating the facts involved
in their seizure, she said.
   ``There is no doubt, however, that Nicaragua regularly,
systematically and continually aids, arms and trains the FMLN
guerrillas. Nicaragua thereby remains the principal violator of the
Central American peace agreement,'' the spokeswoman said.
   Tutwiler said the command and control of the FMLN continues to
operate from Nicaragua in violation of two agreements signed by
five Central American presidents, including Nicaraguan President
Daniel Ortega.
   She added that Nicaragua, in ``direct contradiction'' of its
claims, has continued to send large quantities of weapons to the
FMLN in the 20 months that have passed since American aid to the
Nicaraguan Contras was suspended.
   Honduran military officials have said that the weapons found
Wednesday morning were hidden behind false walls in a truck that
was carrying furniture from Nicaragua to an undetermined location
in El Salvador.
   The seizure was said to have been the largest ever involving a
Nicaraguan shipment but no dollar figures were available.
</TEXT>
