<DOCNO> AP891020-0171 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-89 1606EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Hastings-Charges     10-20 0482</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hastings-Charges,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Charges Against Hastings</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hastings, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are the specific charges against former
U.S. District Judge Alcee L. Hastings, who was removed from office
in a Senate impeachment trial Friday, and the vote by the Senate on
each of them:
   1. Conspiracy with former Washington attorney William Borders to
obtain a $150,000 bribe from defendants in his court in return for
reducing their entences. Guilty, 69-26.
   2. False statement to the jury that acquitted him by saying that
he and Borders never agreed to solicit a bribe. Guilty, 69-26.
   3. False statement to the jury by saying that he and Borders
never agreed to reduce the sentences of defendants in his court.
Guilty, 69-26.
   4. False statement to the jury by saying he never agreed in an
arrangement with Borders to return property that had been
confiscated from defendants in his court. Guilty, 67-28.
   5. False statement to the jury by saying his appearance at the
Fontainebleau hotel dining room in Miami Beach, Fla., on Sept. 16,
1981, was not part of the conspiracy. Guilty, 67-28.
   6. False statement to the jury by saying he did not expect
Borders to appear at a Washington hotel room on Sept. 12, 1981.
Acquitted, 48 for conviction, 47 for acquittal. A two-thirds
majority was needed for conviction.
   7. False statement to the jury about his motive for instructing
law clerk Jeffrey Miller to prepare an order returning confiscated
property to defendants. Guilty, 69-26.
   8. False statement to the jury about the meaning of a telephone
conversation with Borders on Oct. 5, 1981. Guilty, 68-27.
   9. False statement to the jury about the authenticity of three
documents, concerning a friend named Hemphill Pride. Guilty, 70-25.
   10. False statement to the jury in saying that he placed a
telephone call to Pride on May 5, 1981. Waived action.
   11. False statement to the jury in saying that he placed a
telephone call to Pride on Aug. 2, 1981. Waived action.
   12. False statement to the jury in saying that he placed a
telephone call to Pride on Sept. 1, 1981. Waived action.
   13. False statement to the jury about Pride's telephone number.
Waived action.
   14. False statement to the jury by saying he telephoned his
mother and a friend from the L'Enfant Plaza Hotel in Washington on
Oct. 9, 1981. Waived action.
   15. False statement to the jury about his motive for taking an
airline flight from Baltimore-Washington International Airport
rather than National Airport in Washington on Oct. 9, 1981. Waived
action.
   16. Improperly disclosed information obtained from a
court-authorized wiretap under his supervision by telling Dade
County Mayor Stephen Clark on Sept. 6, 1985: ``Watch out for Waxy
Gordon _ he's hot.'' Acquitted, 95-0.
   17. Undermined public confidence in the integrity and
impartiality of the judiciary. Acquitted, 60 for conviction, 35 for
acquittal. A two-thirds majority was needed for conviction.
