<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-89 2034EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Bombing     10-20 0562</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Bombing,0581</SECOND>
<HEAD>Last Defendant Freed in British Bombing Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WEST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Irishman who was exonerated in an IRA bombing
after spending 14 years in jail was freed on bail Friday pending
his appeal of a separate murder conviction.
   Paul Hill was the last of the ``Guildford Four'' defendants to
be released.
   The four were serving life sentences for two IRA bombings that
killed five people in 1974 in Guildford, southwest of London. A
London judge overturned the convictions Thursday, ruling that
police probably lied to get them.
   The government immediately ordered an inquiry into police
actions.
   Hill, 35, was also serving a life sentence for the murder of a
British soldier. He was freed on $6,500 bail and emerged from the
court to cheers from friends and relatives, including his
14-year-old daughter, Cara.
   ``I am very happy,'' he told a reporter. ``How do you think I
feel after 14 years of hell?'' He was flown to Belfast to begin his
appeal of the murder conviction.
   In the ruling Thursday, Lord Lane, the Lord Chief Justice, said
police officers involved in the investigations that led to the
bombing convictions ``must have lied.''
   The convictions were upheld in 1977 even though Irish Republican
Army members made detailed confessions in the case.
   David Williams, deputy chief constable of the Surrey county
police force, whose officers handled the original investigation of
the Guildford Four, said three officers had been suspended pending
an inquiry.
   He identified them as a sergeant and two constables. He said a
fourth officer involved, a detective inspector, had died and a
fifth, a detective chief inspector, had retired.
   In addition to Hill, the appeals court threw out the convictions
of Gerard Conlon, 35, and Patrick Armstrong, 39, of Belfast, and
Carole Richardson, 32, of London, in the bombing of two pubs at
Guildford on Oct. 5, 1974.
   It also overturned convictions of Armstrong and Hill in a pub
bombing in the London suburb of Woolwich on Nov. 6, 1974. Two
people died in that attack.
   Irish Prime Minister Charles Haughey said Thursday he was
satisfied ``the system has the capacity to correct its own
mistakes'' in the Guildford case, but he said he also believes six
Irishmen convicted in IRA bombings in Birmingham, England were
wrongly convicted.
   Home Secretary Douglas Hurd, the Cabinet member responsible for
police, rejected calls to reopen the case of the so-called
Birmingham Six, who were convicted of bombing Nov. 21, 1974. The
attacks killed 21 people.
   Hurd told the BBC the case of the Birmingham Six had been
examined in the same way as the case of the Guildford Four, and
with no new evidence emerging, the convictions were sound.
   In court Thursday, prosecutor Roy Amlot disclosed evidence that
five officers in the Guildford case altered documents, withheld
evidence and ``seriously misled the court.''
   At their 1975 trial, the Guildford Four retracted their
so-called confessions, which they said police had beaten out of
them.
   Hurd said the inquiry into police misconduct also will examine
the conviction of the so-called Maguire Seven on explosives
charges. The defendants include the late father of Conlon, one of
the Guildford Four.
   A cartoon Friday in The Independent showed Hurd staggering from
a bomb-wrecked building labeled: ``Criminal Justice System.''
   The liberal London newspaper The Guardian called the incident
``A story filled with shame.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
