<FIRST>u w AM-US-Panama     10-20 0540</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Panama,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Officials: New Sanctions Would Penalize Americans Who Do Business
with Noriega</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Americans who do business with Panama's Gen.
Manuel Antonio Noriega or any of the more than 30 firms in which he
has an interest could face jail terms and $500,000 fines under new
sanctions being imposed by the Bush administration, U.S. officials
said Friday.
   Many of the firms are used as intermediaries for trade between
the United States and Cuba, which has been illegal since 1960, the
officials said.
   The move is designed as a deterrent to Cuban efforts to
circumvent the trade embargo, while damaging Noriega's business
interests, according to the officials, who asked not to be
identified.
   State Department spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler had no comment on
the measure, which was first reported in Friday's editions of the
Los Angeles Times. A formal announcement is expected next week.
   The administration has been groping for ways to force Noriega
from power but has been reluctant to utilize extreme measures, such
as a trade embargo, out of concern that hundreds of American firms
in Panama would go bankrupt. In addition, the harm inflicted on the
Panamanian economy would take years to overcome.
   The new sanction is narrowly targeted at Noriega and his
business partners and is not expected to do major damage to the
economy as a whole.
   It is not clear how extensive the business dealings are that
Americans have with the firms linked to Noriega. Cuba has found
these firms useful, importing through them high technology
U.S.-made items which otherwise would be beyond Cuba's reach
because of the trade embargo.
   The firms also have served as conduits for illegal Cuban exports
to the United States, the officials said.
   The administration had begun examining ways to bring new
pressure to bear on Noriega well before the abortive coup attempt
on Oct. 3.
   One move being considered is barring Panamanian-flag vessels
from U.S. ports. Another is the withholding by U.S. agencies of
certain taxes they pay to the Panamanian government on behalf of
their Panamanian employees.
   Spanish Prime Minister Felipe Gonzalez ended a two-day visit to
Washington on Friday with praise for the restraint President Bush
showed in not committing Panama-based U.S. forces to the assistance
of the rebel officers who tried to overthrow Noriega earlier this
month.
   ``Interventionism is never desirable,'' Gonzalez said through a
translator. ``I'm very pleased to know that it has not happened.''
   Gonzalez has offered some ideas for resolving Panama's crisis
but he acknowledged that a solution cannot be achieved by third
countries.
   ``It should be a Panamanian solution; otherwise there will be no
solution,'' he said.
   Gonzalez has called for new elections in Panama and for the
newly elected leadership to have the authority to name a new
Defense Force commander to replace Noriega.
   Noriega would be allowed to remain in Panama and thus would
remain out of the reach of U.S. law enforcement authorities.
Noriega is under indictment in Florida on drug trafficking charges.
   Gonzalez believes that a solution to Panama's crisis would be
eased if less attention is devoted to Noriega's personal fate and
more toward achieving the democratic rule blocked by Noriega's
theft of an election earlier this year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891020-0174 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-89 1616EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-SFQuake-Newspapers     10-20 0565</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SF Quake-Newspapers,560</SECOND>
<HEAD>Newspapers Publish the Old-Fashioned Way</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANTHONY MARQUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Typewriters clattered in newsrooms again
this week as newspapers around Northern California scrambled to
publish after the earthquake darkened computer screens and silenced
presses.
   When the quake struck, newspapers from Monterey to San Francisco
were forced to improvise to publish special editions, at times
resorting to writing by longhand in the flickering light of candles.
   ``The sound of the old manual typewriter was heard in the
newsroom for the first time in a million years,'' said Reg Henry,
editor of The Herald of Monterey.
   The Herald, without power, was able to publish an earthquake
special edition that hit Monterey streets Wednesday night by
arranging to print at a weekly paper's plant in King City, 50 miles
to the south.
   A team was sent to King City to produce the 12-page special
edition. Reporters wrote by hand and typewriter with candles
burning at their sides.
   ``I was very proud of what we did,'' said Henry. ``It was a
very, very trying experience.''
   Mike Wallace, editor of the Watsonville Register-Pajaronian,
said Friday that in the first hours following the quake he couldn't
reach his reporters because phone lines were out in the area, which
was close to the epicenter.
   At daybreak, reporters spread across their territory then
returned to the powerless office to write on battery-powered laptop
computers in sunlight from the front window.
   Wallace made arrangements to print at the Register's sister
paper, the Telegram-Tribune, 160 miles south in San Luis Obispo.
The laptop stories were sent over phone lines to laptops at the
Telegram-Tribune, then transferred to that paper's main computer
and edited.
   A private plane flew the newspapers to Watsonville, where they
reached the streets just after 6 p.m. Wednesday.
   The ``long, arduous process'' was worth it, Wallace said,
because readers were hungry for news. More than 15,000 copies of
the eight-page edition, without ads, were quickly snapped up.
   The Register-Pajaronian was nearly back to normal and produced a
24-page edition Friday, he said.
   ``We had a hairy day on Wednesday, but rule No. 1 in this
business is you always publish,'' said Wallace.
   In San Francisco, the Chronicle used generators to put out
Wednesday morning's eight-page edition, produced on Apple Macintosh
computers. The afternoon Examiner also used generators, flashlights
and Macintoshes to get out the news.
   Both published full editions Friday with most of their regular
sections.
   Tossing aside traditional rivalry, the San Jose Mercury News
helped the Santa Cruz Sentinel publish a 12-page special edition by
8 p.m. Wednesday.
   The Sentinel, a morning paper, sent editors and darkroom and
composing workers 25 miles to San Jose for the editions published
Wednesday through Friday evenings.
   The Sentinel hoped to resume morning editions by Sunday.
   Editor Bruce McPherson praised the Mercury News for its
cooperation.
   ``We're impressed. They were really great. They were really
helpful,'' said McPherson. ``They were a class operation.''
   Some newspapers were lucky, such as The (Oakland) Tribune.
   Leroy Aarons, senior vice president for news, said the Tribune
survived the quake with its electricity intact. The computers were
quickly revived.
   The morning Tribune was able to put out a complete edition on
schedule, said Aarons. The paper printed 206,000 papers, some
60,000 more than normal.
   The Mercury News also came out on time, printing 100,000 extra
copies the morning after the quake.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
