<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-89 1618EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-ImpeachmentRules     10-20 0307</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Impeachment Rules,280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rules Say Hastings Can Run for Governor but Not Congress</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hastings Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alcee L. Hastings, removed on Friday from his
federal judgeship, can run for governor of Florida if he chooses.
But he can't run for the United States Senate or the House of
Representatives.
   The Constitution says so.
   Hastings announced immediately after his conviction by the
Senate on eight articles of impeachment that he would run for
governor of his state.
   The Constitution specifies that conviction by the Senate
includes ``disqualification to hold and enjoy any office of honor,
trust or profit under the United States.'' That refers to federal,
not state office.
   The impeachment clause of the Constitution gives the House of
Representatives ``the sole power of impeachment'' _ to bring
charges against a president, vice president and ``all civil
officers of the United States.'' The power to try the individuals
on these charges is given to the Senate.
   It is the only means by which federal judges, who hold their
office for life, can be removed from the bench.
   The word impeach means to accuse. The House votes to impeach,
when it adopts articles of impeachment. The Senate then conducts a
trial on these issues and if the accused is convicted, he is said
to have been impeached.
   Hastings was convicted of perjury and conspiracy to obtain a
$150,000 payoff.
   He is the sixth official removed from office after trial. Only
one president, Andrew Johnson, has ever been tried by the Senate,
and he escaped conviction by one vote.
   In Richard Nixon's case, the House Judiciary Committee voted
three articles of impeachment against Nixon, but the president
resigned before the matter could be brought before the full House.
Nixon stepped down after he was told by Senate leaders that his
conviction in any trial was certain.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
