<DOCNO> AP891020-0176 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-89 2039EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-BusCrashTrial     10-20 0383</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bus Crash Trial,0392</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge OKs Bus-Safety Defense, Nixes Photos of Bodies in Bus-Crash
Trial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CARROLLTON, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawyers can use evidence about bus safety
to fight the 27 murder charges their client faces from last year's
bus-crash disaster, a judge ruled Friday.
   But the prosecution can use results of blood alcohol tests to
prove Larry Mahoney was drunk when he rammed his pickup into the
bus carrying a church youth group, Carroll Circuit Judge Charles
Satterwhite said.
   Satterwhite also ruled that photographs of the victims can be
used by the prosecution to illustrate a large bus seating chart,
but that the jury cannot be shown pictures of the victims' burned
bodies.
   Mahoney, 36, is charged in the deaths of three adults and 24
children and teen-agers who were killed in the May 14, 1988, crash,
one of the nation's worst bus disasters. His trial is to begin Nov.
8
   Police said Mahoney was driving in the wrong direction on
Interstate 71 southwest of Carrollton when his truck collided with
the bus, which burst into flames. One adult and 39 youths escaped,
some with severe injuries.
   Mahoney's attorneys had made clear their intention to base his
defense on the condition of the bus _ a school bus bought as
surplus by Radcliff First Assembly of God church.
   Special Prosecutor Paul Richwalsky opposed that, but the judge
sided with the defense team. He also rejected the defense's attempt
to bar the use of multiple blood-alcohol tests conducted on Mahoney
within hours of the crash.
   Mahoney's lawyers had argued that blood samples were illegally
obtained and that test results were unreliable.
   Observers of the case have said Mahoney's sole hope at trial may
be in trying to show that safety defects, not his wayward driving,
were ultimately responsible for the deaths.
   The National Transportation Safety Board concluded that the
probable cause of the accident was Mahoney's ``alcohol-impaired
condition.'' But it added that contributing to the accident's
severity was the puncturing of the bus' fuel tank and the resulting
fire, as well as its flammable seat cushions and bench seats that
partly blocked the rear emergency door.
   The Kentucky medical examiner found that all 27 deaths were due
to smoke inhalation and that no one on board was seriously injured
by the crash impact.
</TEXT>
