<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     10-20 0435</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROGUE RIVER, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former President Jimmy Carter is
following in the fishing footsteps of President George Bush.
   Carter and former first lady Rosalynn began a four-day fishing
trip Thursday on the Rogue River.
   ``It's good for the area to have someone like that come here to
go on the river,'' outfitter Mel Norrick said.
   Bush fished the river last year for a day, with Norrick as a
guide. Outfitter Dean Helfrich has outfitting chores for the
Carters.
   ``The weather has been good, but we need a little rain,''
Norrick said. ``I hate to see someone like Mr. Carter rained on,
though.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BEATTYVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Who needs the National Weather Service
with Rosemary Kilduff around to keep an eye on woolly worms.
   The Beattyville woman Friday predicted in an annual survey that
winter in central Appalachia will have an early kick and a late
bite, because the fuzzy caterpillars were mostly black on the ends
and brown in the middle.
   This is the eighth year Mrs. Kilduff has conducted her woolly
worm survey, also taking into account other Appalachian folk signs
to make her winter predictions.
   About 250 people called Mrs. Kilduff during the four-week survey
to report 1,423 woolly worms were black on the ends and brown in
the middle; 52 were solid black; 82 were light colored; and 11 were
white, she said.
   In addition, there were 25 local foggy mornings in August, three
hornets' nests seen very low to the ground and three persimmon
seeds with spoon-like structures in the middle.
   ``So we would predict from the woolly worms that our winters
would be cold on each end and mild in the middle and that it will
snow but that the snow won't lay on because the hornets' nests are
close to the ground,'' Mrs. Kilduff said.
   The height of the hornets' nests indicate the height of snow _
the higher the nests the deeper the snow, Mrs. Kilduff said. The
shape of the persimmon seeds generally indicate snow, and the color
of the woolly worms predicts the severity of winter, she said.
August fog tells her how many snowy days winter will have.
   Mrs. Kilduff said her forecasts are ``remarkably accurate.''
Last year, she predicted a milder than usual winter that proved to
be true, said National Weather Service forecaster Gil Russell.
   Radio stations in New York City, Minneapolis and Chicago called
Mrs. Kilduff this week to discuss her predictions. National
Geographic magazine sent a photographer and writer to cover this
weekend's Woolly Worm festival that will include a woolly worm race.
</TEXT>
