<FIRST>r w AM-ConservationPayments     10-20 0124</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Conservation Payments,110</SECOND>
<HEAD>Farmers to Receive Payments for Erodible Cropland</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 300,000 farmers will be getting nearly
$1.5 billion in federal payments for highly erodible cropland in
the long-term Conservation Reserve Program, the Agriculture
Department said Friday.
   Keith Bjerke, executive vice president of the department's
Commodity Credit Corp., said the annual cash rental payments are
for contracts farmers signed in 1986, 1987, 1988 and 1989.
   Under the program, producers agree to retire eligible cropland
from production for 10 years. In return, USDA helps farmers pay for
establishing grass and trees on the land to protect it from
erosion, and pays annual rental payments. Those average around $50
per acre annually.
   Bjerke said the payments will be made ``soon as possible.''
