<SECOND>AM-Missing Press Secretary,230</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush's Press Aide Misses Flight to California</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There was an empty seat in President Bush's
motorcade when it pulled out of the White House gates long before
dawn Friday. The president's press secretary, Marlin Fitzwater, was
missing.
   No one seemingly noticed Fitzwater's absence as Bush rode
through an early-morning rain to Andrews Air Force Base to catch
Air Force One to fly to Northern California to inspect earthquake
damage.
   Yet, puzzled flight attendants on Bush's plane noted that
Fitzwater, who virtually always accompanies the president, was
listed on the manifest for the flight and they inquired about his
whereabouts.
   When he didn't show up, his seat was given to a magazine
reporter who was stranded at Andrews after missing an earlier
flight to California on a plane chartered by the press corps
accompanying the president.
   White House press aides who had flown ahead on the earlier press
charter were baffled when their boss didn't get off Air Force One
with the president at Moffett Naval Air Station near San Jose,
Calif.
   The mystery was solved back in Washington.
   Fitzwater had missed the motorcade's departure at 5:31 a.m. He
said he had been working in his office and no one alerted him that
the motorcade was about to pull out.
   When he went out in the rain to join the motorcade, Fitzwater
was told it had left a minute or so earlier. He spent the rest of
the day working at the White House.
