<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-89 1649EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Hastings 2ndLd-Writethru a0726 10-20 0847</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hastings, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0726,780</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Convicted, Ordered off Federal Bench</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 9th graf, bgng: The impeachment xxx to CORRECT that Hastings
was acquitted in 1983.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate on Friday convicted U.S. District Judge
Alcee L. Hastings of perjury and conspiracy to obtain a $150,000
payoff, making him the sixth federal official in the naton's
history removed from office by impeachment.
   ``I have no choice but to accept their judgment,'' said
Hastings, pausing in a drizzle on the Senate steps as he left the
chamber. He maintained his innocence, called the trial unfair,
pledged to run for governor of Florida and said he would resume the
practice of law.
   Hastings, 53, Florida's first black federal district judge, was
acquitted of the bribery-conspiracy charges in a criminal trial six
years ago.
   The Senate sealed his fate when it voted 69-26 to convict him on
the first of 17 articles of impeachment, charging him with
conspiracy to obtain a bribe.
   In two hours of back-to-back roll calls, the Senate found him
guilty on eight of the articles, acquitted him on three and waived
action on six.
   Senate President Pro Tempore Robert Byrd, D-W.Va., announced the
results and declared that ``it is therefore ordered that the said
Alcee L. Hastings be and is hereby removed'' from the office for
which he was paid $89,500.
   His ouster followed by three years a similar action against
Judge Harry E. Claiborne of Nevada, the fifth official ever removed
in an impeachment case. The Senate is nearing final action on
impeachment charges against Judge Walter Nixon of Mississippi.
   Hastings left the Senate a free man, facing no prison sentence
and with no criminal acquitted on his record.
   The impeachment trial was not designed to reverse the verdict of
the jury that acquitted him in 1983 but to remove him from the
bench.
   For that reason, his accusers scoffed at Hastings' frequent
complaint that he was a victim of ``double jeopardy'' because he
had already been acquitted n court of the same charges.
   ``Do you then not take the matter up and then let a judge serve
who you know is guilty of bribery?'' Rep. John Bryant, D-Texas,
told a news conference following the Senate's action. The articles
of impeachment had been prepared by the House.
   ``This isn't a case of double jeopardy,'' said Sen. Bob Graham,
D-Fla. He said that was so because ``we are sitting in a separate
forum with separate standards of proof.''
   But he voted to acquit Hastings on all articles of impeachment.
   ``The evidence presented was not clear and convincing,'' Graham
said.
   Hastings watched at a table on the Senate floor throughout the
first roll call while defense attorney Terence J. Anderson kept a
tally. Anderson showed the results to Hastings before they were
announced and they shook hands.
   A moment later, defense attorney Patricia Williams, a longtime
Hastings friend, left the chamber. She was soon followed by
Hastings and Anderson.
   ``I'm upbeat and can go forward with my life ...,'' he told
reporters. ``There are those of you who would say I should be
banished in infamy. I know nothing in my life that requires that.''
   Hastings was accused of plotting with William Borders, once a
prominent Washington attorney, to obtain a bribe from two brothers,
Frank and Tom Romano, who each were facing three-year fraud
sentences imposed by Hastings.
   Borders was arrested Oct. 9, 1981, while driving from a suburban
Virginia motel with an FBI undercover agent posing as Frank Romano
and a garment bag containing $125,000 in cash.
   Hastings, in Washington for a testimonial dinner in honor of
Borders that night, was told that the FBI wanted to question him
but instead quickly returned to Miami by an indirect route without
checking out of his hotel.
   Borders later served a prison sentence in the matter and was to
be released Friday from jail, where he had been held for contempt
of court for refusing to testify in the Senate impeachment trial.
   Hastings was acquitted Friday of one count of perjury, which he
had been chraged with in telling the jury he had not expected
Borders to appear in a Washington hotel room Sept. 12, 1981. His
accusers said the hotel room meeting was part of the conspircay.
   In an anticlimax, the Senate acquitted him, 95-0, of a charge
that in an unrelated case he improperly disclosed information
obtained from a court-authorized wiretap under his supervision. The
Senate also acquitted him of an omnibus or ``catchall'' charge that
he had acted improperly or given ``the appearance of impropriety.''
   Hastings said that what ``the Senate has said is a standard of
almost proven, innuendo and inference is good enough to remove a
judge or executive officer by way of impeachment. That is chilling
and fraught with potential to do a lot of harm.''
   He said he was ``hopeful that some book offers will come along.''
   ``There are so many wonderful and tragic stories that are born
of this saga. They need to be told and tell them I shall.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
