<FIRST>u a AM-DeFuscoPlea     10-20 0631</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-DeFusco Plea,610</SECOND>
<HEAD>Couple Pleads Guilty to Time-Share Resorts Scheme</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A couple who lured consumers to visit
time-share resorts with false promises of expensive prizes pleaded
guilty Friday to charges of defrauding creditors of more than $1
million.
   David A. DeFusco, 34, and his 28-year-old wife, Annette,
admitted to a bankruptcy fraud conspiracy in guilty pleas that U.S.
Attorney Henry Hudson said ``ends the story of a very charmed life
led by those two individuals.''
   Hudson said the couple used phantom corporations and aliases to
hide money frozen in bankruptcy proceedings from creditors who
claim unpaid debts of $2.5 million from the DeFusco's and their
companies.
   The couple had ``every kind of luxury item you could imagine,''
including eight mink coats, a Rolls Royce and two Mercedes-Benz
automobiles, Hudson said.
   After the trustee ordered liquidation of their assets last
spring, the DeFuscos sold two cars and moved $250,000 worth of
personal possessions to Rancho Santa Fe, Calif., and opened another
business under assumed names, Hudson said.
   FBI agents who raided their California home on July 5 found
jewelry, furs, a Persian rug worth $15,000, and art work valued at
more than $10,000, Hudson said.
   The search also uncovered a well-worn copy of a book entitled
``How to Create a New Identity'' that Hudson said was ``the Bible''
of the DeFusco's business operations. ``They became masters of
deceit.''
   DeFusco, who pleaded guilty Oct. 6 in Beaumont, Texas, to fraud
charges stemming from the operation of the couple's direct-mail
advertising company, admitted diverting $1 million worth of
corporate and personal assets that had been frozen by a U.S.
bankruptcy trustee.
   Mrs. DeFusco, who was sobbing as she appeared before U.S.
District Judge Claude Hilton, admitted diverting $290,000 worth of
assets as part of the scheme with her husband.
   Each could be sentenced to 25 years in prison and fined up to
$750,000 for guilty pleas to conspiracy to conceal assets from a
bankruptcy trustee and money laundering. DeFusco also faces a
possible 10-year term for his fraud convictions in Texas.
   Hudson told reporters the DeFusco's had lived in a $1 million
house in Great Falls, Va., with a gardner, maid and a nanny. They
often dined twice a week a an expensive French restaurant where the
bill was $250.
   Their creditors claim $2.5 million in unpaid bills, including
$60,000 for American Express credit-card charges to buy jewelry,
Hudson said.
   The couple mailed millions of pieces of advertising that
promised prizes ranging from televisions to imported cars to people
if they drove hundreds of miles to visit time-share condominium
resorts, prosecutors have said.
   In earlier guilty plea, DeFusco admitted conspiring with Freedom
Financial Corp. to lure residents from Midwest and Southwest states
to visit time-share resorts in Texas and Missouri.
   The Federal Trade Commission has filed suit to seek an
injunction barring the DeFuscos from continuing the mailings.
   Defense attorney Kent A. Schaffer disagreed with Hudson's
description of his cleints. ``This isn't a situation where two
people set to out see how much theycould steal,'' he said.
   ``They are people who have been successful in business for a
time,'' he said. ``In 1986, they started to have problems of money
owed to the postal authorities.''
   ``They got on a treadmill'' trying to pay off the $240,000 owed
to the Postal Service for mailing costs, Schaffer said.
   He accused Hudson and Robert J. Wortham, the U.S. attorney in
Beaumont, Texas, of competing ``to see who is going to get the
first press conference'' about the case.
   As part of the plea agreement, federal prosecutors in Seattle
agreed not to press fraud charges stemming from the DeFusco's
operation of another marketing company.
   The couple also agreed to help investigators trace assets that
are still missing.
</TEXT>
