<FIRST>u i AM-Israel     10-20 0274</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel,0281</SECOND>
<HEAD>Palestinian Assailants Kill Two Suspected Collaborators</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Masked men with knives killed two Palestinians
on Friday who were accused of collaborating with Israel, and
wheeled one body through the streets of Nablus as a warning to
others, Arabs reported.
   In Nablus, the occupied West Bank's largest town, masked
Palestinians stabbed 24-year-old Taher Abu Saleh to death, then
pushed the body through the central market on a cart and dumped it
on the street just before dawn, Arab journalists said.
   Other masked Palestinians entered the home of Harb Odeh Essa,
43, at the Bureij refugee camp in the occupied Gaza Strip and slit
his throat, according to Arab reporters.
   Israeli soldiers seriously wounded two Arab teen-agers in the
Gaza Strip. The army said one was shot when he tried to grab a
soldier's rifle.
   Saleh's death in Nablus was blamed on the Red Eagles, one of two
Palestinian gangs said to be active there against alleged
collaborators.
   At least 132 Palestinians have been killed by others, most as
alleged collaborators, since the uprising in the occupied
territories began 22 months ago. Israeli soldiers or civilians have
killed 596 Palestinians and 40 Israelis have died.
   Israel radio said Friday that Shimon Peres, vice premier and
finance minister, had postponed plans to visit the Soviet Union
because Kremlin officials would not guarantee a meeting with Soviet
leaders.
   Peres wanted to meet with President Mikhail S. Gorbachev or
Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze, the radio reported,
quoting his spokesman, Meron Reuven.
   It said Peres, who leads the Labor Party, sent chief political
aide Nimrod Novick to Moscow last week to arrange the visit.
</TEXT>
