<DOCNO> AP891020-0190 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-89 1720EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Quake-Highways 1stLd-Writethru a0747 10-20 0318</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Quake-Highways, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0747,280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bill Introduced to Lift Emergency Aid Cap</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-SF Quake, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS `highway' to `building,' penultimate graf</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Legislation enabling California to receive
extra emergency highway funds for repairing the collapsed Bay
Bridge and other federal highways was introduced Friday with one
senator saying he wanted to know why a section of Interstate 880
gave way in Tuesday's earthquake.
   Sen. Steve Symms, R-Idaho, introduced the bill, which would
waive the $100 million cap on emergency highway funds for a single
disaster and allow the money to be used on the Bay Bridge, which
would normally be ineligible for such emergency relief because it
is a toll facility.
   The emergency highway-aid fund currently has $219 million,
consisting of this year's $100 million authorization and a $119
million carryover from previous years.
   Highway money also exists in a $10 billion highway trust fund
financed by user fees and fuel and tire taxes, but that money is
not available for emergency highway aid.
   Symms is the ranking member and former chairman of the
Environment and Public Works subcommittee on water resources,
transportation and infrastructure. The subcommittee is chaired by
Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y.
   Moynihan said he would like to hold hearings ``to ask the
necessary question, `Why was it that a 60-story skyscraper survived
this event event in California without any damage of any kind, and
two-story highways collapsed?''
   ``The interstate system is now in effect completed. ... but we
also observe that there are portions that fall down more readily
than they ought, that do not withstand the shocks that we can
obviously provide for,'' he said. ``If we do it in a 60-story
building, we can do it a two-story concrete highway. We want to
know about that.''
   Engineers and California officials have said the two-level
highway, which had been strengthened, should have been able to
withstand the quake.
</TEXT>
