<FIRST>u i AM-Salvador-War     10-20 0378</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salvador-War,0389</SECOND>
<HEAD>Military Command Rejects Rebel Purge Demand as `Ridiculous'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The entire military command met
with journalists Friday and declared that a demand by leftist
rebels for a purge of the armed forces was ``ridiculous and
impossible.''
   Rebel leaders contend the commanders are corrupt and implicated
in human rights abuses.
   The unusual gathering of the defense minister, air force
commander, chief of the joint chiefs of staff and commanders of all
brigades and battalions _ two generals and 35 colonels in all _
reaffirmed a rejection of the idea Thursday by President Alfredo
Cristiani.
   ``We feel it appropriate to provide a strong, clear, united
response to the proposal made by the FMLN in Costa Rica,'' said
Gen. Humberto Larios, the defense minister.
   He described the rebel demand that he and 16 other top
commanders be remoed as ``absurd, ridiculous and impossible.''
   Representatives of the rightist government and the Farabundo
Marti National Liberation Front, the guerrilla alliance, ended
three days of peace talks Wednesday in Costa Rica. No substantive
accord was reached, but they agreed to another meeting next month.
   An estimated 70,000 people have been killed, most of them
civilians, since the civil war began 10 years ago.
   In a nationally broadcast address Thursday, Cristiani also
called the purge demand ``ridiculous.'' He accused the rebels of
using the talks ``tactically'' in an effort to isolate the
government and divide the armed forces.
   ``The FMLN has not demonstrated the political will to want to
achieve peace,'' said Cristiani. ``It refuses to talk about a
cessation of hostilities. Its entire attitude is one of
provocation.''
   He said it was ``totally absurd'' for the guerrillas to demand
that any cease-fire agreement recognize their control of territory
and stipulate that Supreme Court judges be replaced.
   ``We recognize the FMLN is a reality, that it exists, but it is
a small reality and cannot oblige the government to change the
republic's constitutional system,'' Cristiani said.
   Guerrilla forces control a swath of northern and eastern El
Salvador and are present to some degree in all 14 provinces.
   The rebels say the government's insistence on an immediate
cessation of hostilities without agreement on eventual reforms is a
disguised call for surrender.
</TEXT>
