<FIRST>u w AM-Hastings-Prosecutor     10-20 0443</FIRST>
<SECOND>^AM-Hastings-Prosecutor,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congressman Celebrates Senate Vote on Impeachment Trial</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hastings Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. John Bryant celebrated the Senate's vote
Friday to oust U.S. District Judge Alcee L. Hastings from the bench
by sipping champagne and eating pizza.
   ``The rewarding feeling I have is that a complicated and
controversial case ended with justice being done,'' said Bryant,
appointed by the House as the chief prosecutor in Hastings' Senate
trial. ``I feel 100 percent certain that he was guilty and clearly
should not be serving as a federal judge.''
   Bryant said he expects the former federal judge to campaign
against him as he seeks the Democratic nomination for Texas
attorney general.
   Hastings, the first black U.S. District Court judge in Florida,
said he would do so during a recent meeting in Houston with a
coalition of black Democratic leaders, where he also complained he
was being unfairly prosecuted by Bryant, the Dallas congressman
said in an interview.
   But Benjamin L. Hooks, executive director of the National
Association for the Advancement of Colored People, said black
voters should not hold Bryant's role in the case against him.
   Hooks said that since all but three members of the congressional
Black Caucus voted to impeach Hastings, ``it's difficult to say
that because a white man took part, he should be singled out ...''
   Hooks said one of those congressmen supporting Hastings'
impeachment was Rep. John Conyers, a Detroit Democrat who ``no one
can say is soft on positions affecting black people.''
   Bryant, meanwhile, said he feels vindicated by the Senate's vote
to convict Hastings of perjury and conspiracy to obtain a $150,000
payoff, making the Miami judge the sixth federal official removed
as a result of impeachment.
   ``I was not certain what the verdict would be at any stage,
because of the fact that it was a case that involved a previous
acquital of the judge on one of the central charges,'' Bryant said.
``Of course it also involved a conviction of his co-conspirator for
conspiring with the judge to extort a bribe.
   ``So you had contradictory jury verdicts, making the matter
legally complicated. And then you had a very complex set of facts
... requiring the Senate to make a decision based on strong but
circumstantial evidence,'' said Bryant, a member of the Judiciary
Committee.
   Hastings, 53, was acquitted of the bribery-conspiracy charges in
a criminal trial six years ago.
   Bryant said he feels good about having fulfilled his
responsibility.
   ``I was asked to take this role (by Judiciary Chairman Jack
Brooks of Texas) and I knew it would be extremely controversial and
time consuming,'' he said.
</TEXT>
