<FIRST>r i AM-Hungary-Opposition     10-20 0206</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hungary-Opposition,0212</SECOND>
<HEAD>Largest Opposition Group Opens Congress</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hungary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hungary's largest opposition group
opened a national meeting Friday to decide on a campaign strategy
for next year's freely contested elections.
   The Democratic Forum began as a loose grouping of intellectuals,
artists and scientists in 1987 and since has grown to about 20,000
members.
   The three-day congress, the group's second national meeting,
opened as Hungary's parliament ended a landmark session in which it
adopted a package of laws designed to open the way for the first
multiparty elections in more than 40 years.
   In recent special elections for four parliament seats, Communist
Party candidates were defeated by candidates put up by the
Democratic Forum.
   In an opening address, Forum leader Gyoergy Szabad told the 850
delegates that ``people are beginning to feel confidence in
Hungarian democracy.''
   ``Let us change the course of history ... (and) make democracy a
permanent companion,'' he said.
   Szabad said the Forum ``went to the grass roots'' after decades
of Marxist-Leninist dictatorship and ``discovered new areas of
political and democratic culture in Hungary.''
   Delegations from the Polish Solidarity group and the West German
Christian Democratic Union are attending the congress as invited
guests, Forum spokesman Sandor Lezsak said.
</TEXT>
