<FIRST>r w AM-SaudiTanks     10-20 0222</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Saudi Tanks,210</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Promises To Answer 29 House Members On Saudi Tank Sale</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department said Friday it will
respond to questions raised by Majority Leader Richard Gephardt of
Missouri and 28 other House members on the planned $3 billion sale
of 315 modern tanks and other military equipment to Saudi Arabia.
   In a letter to Secretary of State James A. Baker III on
Thursday, they asked if the purchase was in the U.S. strategic
interest, what armor would be included and where the tanks would be
deployed.
   Rep. Melvin Levine, D-Calif., questioned in an accompanying
letter whether the administration had conducted sufficient
consultation with Congress.
   ``In light of the fact that the Saudis have received over $30
billion worth of military goods and services in the past eight
years from the U.S.,'' Levine wrote, ``I am troubled that they
still have yet to meet many basic U.S. policy objectives in the
Middle East.''
   In a statement Friday, the department's press office called the
questions raised in the letter by the 29 members ``thoughtful and
reasonable.'' The statement added: ``We look forward to answering
them thoroughyl as we continue our consultations with the Hill
about this sale.''
   The purchase will go through unless it is rejected by majority
vote of both the Senate and the House.
</TEXT>
