<FIRST>u a AM-SFQuake-Losses     10-20 0332</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SF Quake-Losses,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Damage Estimates Reach $5.5 Billion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA MYERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The estimated cost of California's
deadly earthquake rose to $5.5 billion Friday as state officials
received new reports of damage to businesses, public buildings,
homes and state highways and bridges.
   The pricetag of the disaster continues to grow and doesn't
include losses on many county roads left cracked from Tuesday's
quake that measured 6.9 on the Richter scale.
   ``The damage estimate is going up constantly as we get new
reports,'' Alameda County Sheriff's Sgt. Jim Knudsen said. ``We
won't know the total damage for quite a while.''
   So far, Alameda County is estimating at least $1.3 billion in
losses in Oakland alone, while figures for the other parts of the
county which escaped with far less damage weren't immediately
calculated.
   The figure includes $30 million in damages to 1,400 homes and
$986 million in destruction of 213 private and commercial
businesses, according to Knudsen.
   The city-county of San Francisco, with its still-crippled Marina
district, estimated total damages at $2 billion.
   Affluent Marin County, just across the Golden Gate Bridge from
San Francisco, escaped relatively unscathed with an estimated $2
million in damages.
   ``We were extremely lucky,'' said Marin County Public Works
Director Mehdi Sadjadi. ``We feel that we have been under a lucky
star because we were spared.''
   Santa Cruz County, which continues to assess damage from,
reported as much as $750 million in damages as of Friday morning.
That includes $125 million in damaged public facilities, $400
million in destruction to private buildings and ``hundreds of
millions of dollars'' in damages to the city of Santa Cruz.
   Total damages reported by seven counties most affected amount to
about $4.5 billion. State transportation officials estimate losses
to state highways and buildings at between $500 million and $1
billion.
   The state Office of Emergency Services, which gets reports from
local agencies, has set the total damage estimate, exclusive of
state losses, at $4.2 billion.
</TEXT>
