<DOCNO> AP891020-0204 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-89 2031EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Argentina-Military     10-20 0361</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Argentina-Military,0371</SECOND>
<HEAD>Leader of Two Army Rebellions Forced to Retire</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED McCULLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The army command forced the
retirement Friday of Lt. Col. Aldo Rico, who led two insurrections
that endangered the government of former President Raul Alfonsin.
   Gen. Isidro Caceres, appointed army commander earlier this year,
issued the order affecting Rico and four other leaders of a January
1988 revolt, the government news agency Telam reported.
   President Carlos Menem must approve the action, but he said
Thursday: ``It doesn't matter to me what names are included. I'll
sign it.''
   Rico, 44, led soldiers who took over part of the Campo de Mayo
army base on the outskirts of Buenos Aires in April 1987, and
another rebellion nine months later at the Monte Caseros base in
northeastern Corrientes Province.
   He demanded an end to trials in civilian courts of officers
accused of violating human rights during the ``dirty war''
conducted against leftists while the military ruled Argentina in
1976-83.
   Rico, Lt. Col. Arturo Gonzalez Naya and the other three were
cashiered after the revolts, but their ranks were restored later so
military courts could try them.
   Menem pardoned them Oct. 7 in a group of 39 colonels, generals
and vice admirals accused of kidnapping, torture and murder under
military rule.
   He also pardoned 64 alleged leftist guerrillas, 174 officers
accused in the rebellions and three _ including former President
Gen. Leopoldo Galtieri _ convicted of misconduct in the disastrous
Falkland Islands war with Britain in 1982.
   Menem intended the sweeping amnesty to cool passions that led to
the rebellions, street demonstrations, bitter debates in Congress
and scattered violence.
   Marta Gaston Alfonso of the Mothers of the Plaza de Mayo,
relatives whose children disappeared during the ``dirty war,'' said
1 million people had signed anti-amnesty petitions that would be
presented to Menem.
   Rico has wide support among junior officers in the 85,000-man
military, who feel the campaign against leftists was a kind of
civil war and deserves gratitude, not censure.
   An investigation conducted by Alfonsin's government found that
about 9,000 people disappeared and were presumed dead. Rights
groups say 30,000 is more accurate.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
