<DOCNO> AP891020-0205 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-89 2106EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-SFQuake-Lawsuits     10-20 0391</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SF Quake-Lawsuits,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Long Process To Sue The State, Which Has Design Defect Immunity</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If victims of the San Francisco area
earthquake decide to sue the state for injuries, losses or
relatives' deaths caused by the collapse of state-built structures,
they face a long and complex process.
   State law gives the state design defect immunity. That means the
state cannot be sued because of a basic defect in the design of a
public works project, such as a highway.
   ``That will be an issue'' in any lawsuits filed relating to the
collapses of sections of Interstate 880 freeway or the Bay Bridge,
said Alan Ashby, spokesman fir the state attorney general.
   Victims who believe the state was to blame for their losses
can't go into court as quickly as if they were suing a private
person or business.
   ``Before you can sue the state, you have to file a claim,'' said
Curt Sonderland of the state Board of Control. Nobody has yet filed
a claim with the state relating to the earthquake.
   The Board of Control staff looks at the claim, solicits a
response from the state department allegedly at fault, and makes a
recommendation to the board. The board has three members, the
director of the General Services Department, the controller and a
governor's appointee.
   The board then decides whether to pay the claim. The payment
must be approved by the Legislature.
   However, Sonderland said that the board routinely rejects a
claim, such as one that might arise from the bridge or I-880
collapse, if it is ``a complex issue of fact and-or law.''
   ``This enables the individual to sue the state and go directly
to court,'' he said.
   He said it normally takes the board 45 to 60 days to process a
claim.
   He said the board was never intended to determine complex legal
liability questions and its members are not judges.
   Civil lawsuit settlements or judgments would also have to be
approved by the Legislature, which has rejected both claims and
lawsuit judgments in the past. The plaintiff has little recourse if
the Legislature rejects the payment, said Ashby.
   The largest judgment the state has had to pay was about $4
million for damages in the 1965 Crescent City floods, he said.
Lawsuits relating to the 1986 floods are still pending, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891020-0206 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-89 1848EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-SFQuake-Bush 4thLd-Writethru a0765 10-20 1116</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SF Quake-Bush, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0765,970</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Deeply Moved' Bush Sees Quake Damage, Vows `No Red Tape' Aid</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS graf 4: ``Commenting,'' and SUBS graf 19: ``In Washington,''
with three grafs bgng: ``Bush, who,'' with Bush refusing to rule out tax
increase and to give latest damage estimate; CORRECTS spelling ``Berumen''
in 11th graf, now 12th graf: ``The president,''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush inspected the ravages of the
Northern California earthquake Friday, breathing a single word _
``Jesus'' _ when he got his first look at the collapsed freeway
still covering uncounted bodies. He promised all-out federal help
with ``no red tape.''
   ``It's been a very moving day,'' the president said at the end
of a four-hour tour of the region that gave him first-hand look at
some of the areas that were hardest hit by the quake.
   Bush said he was ``willing to do what's needed to be done,'' as
he faced repeated questions from local officials about how much
recovery money the government would provide _ and when. He offered
no details on the size of the federal contribution to relief
efforts.
   Commenting ``there's no ceiling on the compassion of the
American people,'' Bush declined on several occasions to rule out
the possibility of of tax increases to pay for recovery costs.
   San Francisco Mayor Art Agnos, one of three mayors accompanying
the president on his tour, told him: ``We need fast action. We need
checks written on the spot.''
   ``We will do what is necessary to fulfill our responsibility,''
said the president, flanked by state and federal officials.
   Bush said that government officials on all levels needed to
cooperate, that ``we've got to work with each other.''
   ``In terms of what it will cost, I don't know,'' he said. But he
added that Washington will work with local and state governments
``to see the suffering is alleviated, the restoration begins.''
   Transportation Secretary Samuel Skinner, newly designated to
head federal quake-recovery efforts, promised the U.S. government
was prepared to play ``a very very major role in helping
California.''
   Accompanied by state officials as well as the mayors of San
Francisco, Oakland and Alameda, Bush flew over some of the
hardest-hit areas by helicopter and visited the collapsed
double-decker expressway in Oakland in which an unknown number of
rush-hour motorists are feared still entombed.
   He also visited San Francisco and inspected damage in the
coastal city of Santa Cruz, near the epicenter of Tuesday's
powerful earthquake.
   The president said ``the most touching moment'' of his visit was
when he talked to the doctor who rescued young Julio Berumen from a
crushed car. The doctor had to amputate the boy's leg to get him
free.
   ``I had the opportunity to talk to the dad who was at the
bedside of this 6-year-old boy and I had a chance to tell him that
the American people were rooting for him, to tell his dad that we
all care,'' Bush said.
   In his first stop, Bush walked tieless and wearing a flight
jacket with the presidential seal slowly alongside the collapsed
freeway where workers with heavy machinery are trying to extricate
the bodies from cars crushed between the two decks.
   The ground was covered with rubble, including massive chunks of
concrete and giant fallen pillars. Twisted steel girders protruded
from the structure. Smashed cars were visible between the upper and
lower decks.
   ``I am deeply moved by this, saddened in some ways, yet very
stimulated by this team effort,'' the president said.
   He complimented rescue teams and added that he admired ``the way
this community is pulling together. ... We'll see what we can do to
be part of the answer.''
   He questioned the propriety of his own visit, saying, ``I had a
doubt, is it proper for me to come here? If you do, they say you're
getting in the way of the lifting or the building or the
fire-fighting or whatever.'' But he added, ``If you don't go _ why
it's neglect.''
   Bush also taped a public service television announcement
offering encouragement to Bay area residents and urging Americans
around the nation to contribute to volunteer organizations.
   Bush, who won office on a firm pledge of no new taxes, said,
``I'm going to do what is necessary to have the federal government
fulfill its obligation,'' and repeated substantially the same
phrase when asked if that meant new taxes.
   Gov. George Deukmejian has said he is willing to face a state
tax increase, if necessary, and U.S. House Speaker Thomas S. Foley,
D-Wash., said Thursday the House would vote relief funds regardless
of what it did to the federal deficit.
   In Washington, House Democrats are working on a $2.5 billion
relief package. But Skinner, talking with reporters aboard Air
Force One on the flight west, said, ``I don't know where they got''
that figure, and local officials had raised damage estimates to
$5.5 billion on Friday.
   Administration officials, speaking only on the condition of
anonymity, said the White House request to Congress would likely
far surpass the $1.1 billion voted to help Hurricane Hugo victims.
   In a meeting with local officials at Moffett Naval Air Station,
Bush promised the relief effort would not become bogged down in red
tape.
   ``You can't have every `t' crossed and every `i' dotted,'' Bush
said.
   San Francisco Mayor Agnos, a Democrat who had criticized Vice
President Dan Quayle for not visiting him on his trip Wednesday,
told Bush that his city was ``90 percent back to normal.'' Still,
he said, referring to the obvious damage, ``when you walk this
ground, you feel it in your gut.''
   Dennis Kwaitkowski, assistant associate director of the Federal
Emergency Management Administration, told reporters that FEMA would
likely need close to $1 billion alone for its relief efforts here _
and that doesn't include major construction repairs.
   Kwaitkowski said FEMA plans to open 10 disaster centers in the
area on Sunday _ and eventually planned to have a total of 20 open,
including three mobile units.
   California Gov. George Deukmejian called the federal response so
far ``tremendous'' but said the state's $1 billion reserve fund
would be soon depleted. ``We're probably looking at $3 billion or
so'' in total damage, he told Bush.
   Rep. Norman Mineta, D-Calif., told reporters here that the total
damage costs will run between $8 billion and $10 billion _ of which
he said the federal government should pay between $5 billion and $6
billion.
   He said he did not foresee a clash between Congress and Bush
over the amount of the aid package. ``The fact that the president
responded so quickly means that any kind of partisanship is out of
the question.''
</TEXT>
