<FIRST>r i AM-Peru-Strike     10-20 0208</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Peru-Strike,0213</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Fire on Striking Workers, 10 Wounded</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Riot troops fired on striking government
workers on Friday, wounding 10 people, including a local television
reporter, police said.
   The shooting broke out after someone in the crowd of strikers
threw a stick of dynamite that exploded near a line of policemen.
Police said the dynamite was thrown by a leftist rebel who had
infiltrated the march in downtown Lima, seven blocks from
Government Palace.
   A police spokesman initially said it was unknown who fired the
shots that wounded the 10. He said police had been ordered not to
shoot at strikers.
   But police investigators who inspected the site later said they
found shell casings that matched the type of arms used by riot
police.
   Government workers are demanding higher pay, and Friday's
protest was a rejection of a 50 percent wage increase announced by
the government Wednesday. Strikers said the increase would amount
to less than 10 percent when measured against rising inflation.
   Juan Manuel Guimarey, a reporter covering the strike for Channel
9 Television, was shot in the arm and slightly wounded by the
gunfire. A spokesman for the Lima station said Guimarey told
colleagues he did not see who shot him.
</TEXT>
