<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-89 1937EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     10-20 0372</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0382</SECOND>
<HEAD>Early Frost, Record Cold Hit South, Gulf Coast States</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Much of the South and the Gulf Coast shivered as the mercury
plunged Friday, snapping low-temperature records in 38 cities and
tying them in seven others. The chilly weather was expected to
continue into Saturday.
   The low temperatures followed a storm that dumped more than 8
inches of snow on north-central Indiana by Friday morning and 2 to
6 inches over much of Illinois, Ohio, southern Michigan and
southeast Wisconsin.
   Snow fell in the mountains of northern Georgia and North
Carolina during the morning. Snowfall was generally light, although
there was a two-inch accumulation at Beach Mountain, N.C., by
Friday afternoon.
   In the six hours ending at 2 p.m. EDT, 2 inches of snow fell in
Marquette, Mich.; 5 inches in South Bend, Ind; 3 inches in
Milwaukee and 1 inch in Fort Wayne, Ind., and Wausau, Wis.
   Snow, often mixed with rain, fell from Wisconsin and Michigan to
northern and west central Illinois. Rain, mixed with snow at higher
elevations, extended from northern Tennessee to eastern Kentucky
and southwestern West Virginia. Rain and occasional thunderstorms
reached from New York state to central New England and fell over
the northern coast of North Carolina.
   Flood watches were posted for sections of New Jersey, Rhode
Island and Pennsylvania.
   Winds gusted to around 35 mph in Knoxville, Tenn., and gusty
winds raised blowing dust in the southern San Joaquin Valley in
California.
   Low-temperature records up to 72 years old were broken or tied
across the South.
   In Lake Charles, La., the temperature hit 32 degrees, snapping
the mark of 35 degrees set in 1939 and setting a record low for the
month. It was 32 degrees in Little Rock, Ark., the earliest freeze
ever recorded in that city.
   A low of 22 degrees in Ozark, Ark., beat by 8 degrees the record
set back in 1917.
   Records were also set in Pensacola, Fla. (35 degrees, 42 in
1981), Mobile, Ala. (33 degrees, 39 in 1964) and Mena, Ark. (24, 30
in 1925 and 1966).
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 32
degrees in Kalamazoo and Marquette, Mich., to 87 degrees in Yuma,
Ariz.
</TEXT>
