<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-89 2125EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Japan-Ivory     10-20 0215</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Ivory,0223</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japan Still Undecided on Ivory Ban</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Endangered Species</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan, the world's leading buyer of ivory, is
studying whether it will join a ban on ivory trade approved this
week at a conference of 91 nations, a government spokesman said
Friday.
   The head of Japan's Environment Agency urged Cabinet members at
a meeting to support the ban to avoid ``international isolation''
on the issue.
   The government Japan is still studying the issue, Foreign
Ministry spokesman Taizo Watanabe later told reporters.
   ``We have not yet reached a conclusion, but we are aware of the
consensus in Switzerland,'' Watanabe said.
   In Lausanne, Switzerland, the Convention on International Trade
in Endangered Species voted Monday to put the elephant on the
endangered species list, thereby banning ivory trade. Japan, a
convention member, abstained from the vote.
   The convention voted Thursday to extend the ban to existing
stocks of ivory.
   Convention members have the right to ask for exemptions to
rulings and several southern African nations have indicated they
will do so.
   Japan has ``sizable stocks'' of ivory, Watanabe said. The World
Wide Fund for Nature estimates Japan has about 100 tons of raw
ivory.
   Japan has regularly purchased about 40 percent of the world's
ivory exports, the largest quantity for a single country.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
