<FIRST>u a AM-Hastings-Reax 1stLd-Writethru a0746 10-20 0685</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hastings-Reax, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0746,0705</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hastings Ouster, Announcement for Governor Bring Strong Reactions</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 5th graf, ```It's a ...,' to UPDATE with
statement by Benjamin Hooks; picks up 6th graf, `Hastings, 53 ...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hastings Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILL LESTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When federal judge Alcee Hastings' eight-year legal
battle over a bribery charge ended Friday with a U.S. Senate vote
to remove him from the bench, he immediately announced he would run
for governor.
   Hastings _ outspoken, witty and a dynamic speaker _ almost never
evokes a neutral reaction from those around him, and the latest
events were no exception.
   Hastings' ouster 10 years after President Carter made him
Florida's first black U.S. District judge sparked an angry reaction
from blacks, and his political announcement surprised Florida
politicians.
   The ouster ``sends a shocking and chilling message to black
folks all over the country that we have not overcome yet,'' said
Dorsey Miller, a Miami physician and longtime Hastings supporter.
   ``It's a definite travesty to our justice system,'' said
Roosevelt Walters, head of the Fort Lauderdale branch of the
National Association for the Advancement of Colored People. ``We
have to wonder who is next? Who will be singled out?''
   ``We must question whether justice was truly served by the
Senate action,'' Benjamin Hooks, executive director of the National
Association for the Advancement of Colored People, said in a
statement issued in Baltimore.
   Hooks said the Senate's action, ``in my view, constitutes double
jeopardy and this flies in the face of the foundation that buttress
our legal system.''
   Hastings, 53, was removed for allegedly conspiring to take a
$150,000 payoff to fix a court case.
   A federal jury in Miami acquitted him in 1983. But a subsequent
investigation led to his impeachment last year in the House, which
accused him of plotting to obtain a bribe, lying during his trial
and an unrelated charge of improperly disclosing federal wiretap
information.
   Sen. Connie Mack, R-Fla., voted for impeachment last year while
still a representative, but did not vote in the Senate. Florida's
other senator, Democrat Bob Graham, voted in Hastings' favor,
saying there was no clear and convincing evidence of his guilt.
   Hastings had said he would have announcement that could blunt
angry reaction to the Senate vote, but his gubernatorial bid was
unexpected.
   ``This ranks up there as one of the most bizarre'' political
events in Florida, said Jon Peck, a spokesman for Republican Gov.
Bob Martinez, who is up for re-election next year.
   ``Based on that track record, he's going to run for governor?''
Peck asked. ``Anybody who wants to is welcome to run for governor.
They'll have to take on an incumbent who is going to get
re-elected.''
   Martinez, who was on a glass-bottom boat off Key Largo with U.S.
Interior Secretary Manuel Lujan, laughed when told of Hastings'
announcement.
   ``You'll have to ask George Stuart and Bill Nelson about that,''
he said, referring to the Democrats in the race.
   State Democratic Party Chairman Simon Ferro had not heard of the
announcement Friday morning when asked to comment on Hastings' plan
to run for governor.
   ``Of what?'' Ferro asked.
   ``I would certainly like to sit down with him to assess his
opportunities and his chances and how they might affect the race,''
Ferro said. ``That's about as much as I can tell you at this
point.''
   Martinez faces a challenge from within his own party from state
Sen. Marlene Woodson-Howard. U.S. Rep. Bill Nelson and Orlando
attorney George Stuart are running as Democrats.
   Nelson's campaign manager, Ted Phelps, said Hastings' ouster did
not seem like an opportune time to announce for governor.
   Stuart was out of town and could not be reached for comment.
   Phelps said he believes Hastings has ``a small following'' and
will get some votes, ``but I do not think he will be a serious
contender.''
   The Senate's action saddened those who had worked with the
judge, whose outspoken style has won over many people and alienated
others.
   ``I am personally very sorry,'' said Acting Chief Judge William
Hoeveler. ``We will miss him.''
</TEXT>
