<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-89 2139EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-MetrolinerCompetition     10-20 0350</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Metroliner Competition,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three Expresses Added in Northeast Corridor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANE E. ALLEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Amtrak said Friday it will add three
high-speed express Metroliner trains between Washington and New
York to compete with the airlines.
   Some members of the New Jersey congressional delegation
immediately protested to Amtrak their state was being neglected
because none of the new trains will stop there.
   Starting Oct. 30, the new trains, one northbound and two
southbound, will make the 225-mile run in 2 hours, 35 minutes to 2
hours, 40 minutes. One will run non-stop and the other two will
make only one stop, at New Carrollton, Md., in the Washington
suburbs. The only existing express Metroliner stops only at New
Carrollton on its 2-hour, 40-minute northbound trip.
   The expresses will give out free newspapers like the shuttle.
Northbound expresses will sell New York subway tokens; southbound
expresses will sell Washington subway fare cards.
   With a fare of $74 one-way vs. the shuttle's $99 at rush hour,
Amtrak is hoping to attract more passengers. The new expresses are
15 to 20 minutes faster than regular Metroliners, 55 minutes faster
than regular trains, and are close to the time needed by air when
airport-to-city center segments are included.
   ``We feel we need to remain competitive with the airlines,''
said spokesman Clifford Black. ``We feel it will improve our
revenues,'' and the current number of Metroliner stops in New
Jersey is not being reduced.
   Still, Rep. Matthew Rinaldo, a New Jersey Republican on the
transportation subcommittee of the Energy and Commerce Committee,
said, ``They're trying to compete with Trump Airlines by blazing
through New Jersey. But the few minutes it takes to pick up
passengers in Metropark or Newark would hardly matter.''
   He said adding a New Jersey stop would add less than 10 minutes
to the journey time.
   ``This decision by your office is a short-sighted effort that
disserves the Newark-New York metropolitan area,'' Rinaldo said in
a letter to Amtrak president W. Graham Claytor Jr. that was signed
by five other members of the state's 14-member House delegation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
