<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-89 2146EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-InlandAwards     10-20 0765</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Inland Awards,0812</SECOND>
<HEAD>Durango (</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Durango (Colo.) Herald has been named
sweepstakes award winner for its coverage of environmental issues
in the Inland Press Association's 1989 Local Public Affairs News
Contest.
   Judges from the University of Wisconsin-Madison School of
Journalism and Mass Communication cited the Herald for its coverage
of threats to local drinking water supplies resulting from gas-well
drilling in the area.
   The Herald was named sweepstakes winner for its entry in the
investigative, interpretive and background reporting category for
newspapers with circulations under 10,000.
   The awards will be presented at the 104th Annual Meeting of the
Inland Press Association, which begins Sunday in Chicago.
   Inland, founded in 1885, has 436 newspaper members in 33 states,
Canada and Bermuda as well as 85 associate and university members.
   The Park Ridge, Ill.-based association also named The State
Journal of Frankfort, Ky., as winner of the association's Community
Service Award for 1989 for the paper's efforts to help fight
illiteracy in Kentucky.
   Second place for community service went to The Times of Hammond,
Ind., for pursuit of actions that led to a new state law opening
the records of county coroners. Third place went to The Patriot
Ledger of Quincy, Mass., for its work to help a rapidly expanding
Asian population and other city residents learn about each other.
   The Inland public affairs awards are made based on circulation,
with Class A 10,000 and under, Class B 10,001-25,000, Class C
25,001-100,000 and Class D more than 100,000.
   In addition to the investigative, interpretive and background
reporting category, Inland awards also are given for deadline
reporting of public affairs and general coverage of local
government.
   Here are the other winners in each award category by circulation:
</TEXT>
