<FIRST>r a AM-UAL 1stLd-Writehthru a0741 10-20 0580</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UAL, 1st Ld-Writehthru, a0741,0596</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pilot-Management Group Pursues UAL Despite British Air's Bailout</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 14th graf, ```For the ...' to CORRECT name of investment
firm to Laing and Cruickshank, sted Lain and Cruickshank. A longer version
on financial wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDA C. COLEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British Airways PLC on Friday bailed out of a
group trying to buy UAL Corp., a defection that sent UAL stock into
another tailspin and dealt the buyout plan its second stunning blow
in a week.
   The pilots union at UAL's United Airlines, which along with
management is leading the buyout attempt, quickly announced it was
developing a new plan that would include for the first time
United's flight attendants as partners.
   But some analysts and United's Machinists union, which has
opposed the buyout plan, said British Airway's departure may doom
the proposal.
   In a brief statement Friday in London, British Airways said it
``does not intend to participate in any new deal for the
acquisition of UAL in the foreseeable future.'' It didn't give
reasons, but said its marketing agreement with United would remain
in effect.
   ``We're obviously disappointed. However, we do plan to move
ahead with our new partners, the flight attendants, who joined with
us yesterday,'' said Hank Krakowski, a spokesman for the United
chapter of the Air Line Pilots Association. ALPA represents 7,000
of United's 70,000 workers.
   The Association of Flight Attendants, which represents 14,000
workers at United, issued a statement saying it would participate
with ALPA and UAL management in discussions about any new proposal.
   Joe Hopkins, a spokesman for Chicago-based UAL, said the company
had no comment on British Airways' withdrawal.
   The original pilot-management buyout proposal approved by UAL's
board of directors called for UAL workers to own 75 percent of the
company, management 10 percent and British Airways 15 percent.
   It would have been the largest employee-led buyout of a U.S.
company.
   British Airways' announcement came one week after the
pilot-management group said it had failed to secure financing for
its original $6.75 billion, $300-a-share offer, contributing to a
Friday the 13th selloff on Wall Street that resurrected fears of
the 1987 stock market crash.
   While the stock market overall has rebounded since last week,
UAL shares have continued spiraling lower, reflecting growing
pessimism among investors that any debt-financed takeover proposal
of the airline will succeed.
   UAL tumbled $21.62{ to finish at $168.50 a share Friday in New
York Stock Exchange trading, bringing its decline for the week to
about $110.
   Airline analysts in London were pessimistic about the remaining
partners' chances for success.
   ``For the time being, I think it's dead, to be honest,'' said
Nick Cunningham, of the investment firm Laing and Cruickshank.
   A spokesman for the International Association of Machinists and
Aerospace Workers at United agreed.
   ``It was not a viable proposal that would have done the
employees any good,'' said spokesman Jim Conley from the Washington
headquarters of the union, which represents 25,000 United workers.
   ``We're hoping that'll be the end of it,'' said Conley, whose
union has maintained the pilot-management proposal would saddle UAL
with a dangerous debt load.
   But airline analyst Stephen Dexter, of Kemper Financial Services
Inc. in Chicago, said British Airways may not necessarily have
pulled out for good.
   He said British Airways, which prides itself on being a
first-class carrier, is unaccustomed to the indignity of whipsawing
takeover efforts.
   But ``they have invested very, very heavily in their
relationship with United,'' Dexter said.
</TEXT>
