<SECOND>AM-BRF--Engine Shutdown,0156</SECOND>
<HEAD>American Airlines Flight Lands at O'Hare on One Engine</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American Airlines jet with 140 people aboard
landed safely at O'Hare International Airport on Friday after its
pilot shut down one of the Boeing 767's two engines, an airline
spokesman said.
   The pilot of the flight from San Diego to Chicago shut down the
jet's right engine 15 miles from the airport, said American
Airlines spokesman Tom Stack.
   The plane had 132 passengers aboard and a crew of eight, Stack
said.
   A fire crew was on standby in case of emergency, but the
wide-body plane landed safely and there were no injuries, Stack
said.
   Stack said he did not immediately know why the pilot shut down
the engine, but said American officials were investigating.
   Federal Aviation Administration regulations permit the Boeing
767 to fly up to 180 minutes on only one engine, the spokesman said.
</TEXT>
