<DOCNO> AP891020-0227 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-89 2207EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-MineExplosion     10-20 0418</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mine Explosion,0429</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mine Officials Believe Torch Sparked Explosion, Newspaper Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WHEATCROFT, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Top officials of a coal mine where 10 men
died in an explosion last month believe an acetylene torch sparked
the blast, a newspaper reported Friday.
   Federal and state investigators have not determined what ignited
methane gas that exploded Sept. 13 in the western Kentucky mine,
but The Evansville (Ind.) Press said a cutting torch is Pyro Mining
Co.'s official theory.
   Investigators recovered two cutting torches from the mine soon
after the explosion.
   Maurice Childers, chief investigator for the U.S. Mine Safety
and Health Administration, said Oct. 3 that the valves on the
torches were closed, but did not rule them out as a possible source
of ignition.
   The Press said Pyro officials have told about 25 workers about
the company's theory. The newspaper said two of those workers
talked to the Press on condition of anonymity.
   ``They're leaning toward the torches,'' the newspaper quoted one
of the Pyro employees as saying. ``They believe there might have
been a small pocket of (methane) gas (to) ignite, and it carried
into a bigger pocket of gas that exploded.''
   Charles Schulties, president of Pyro parent Costain Coal Co.,
and Costain Vice President Jim Greenlee said Wednesday they have
reached a conclusion about what caused the explosion but would not
discuss it publicly until all mine employees were notified.
   Greenlee would neither confirm nor deny the cutting-torch
theory, The Press said. Costain officials did not return telephone
calls Friday from The Associated Press.
   Officials of the federal mine safety agency have theorized that
shortly before the explosion, company workers removed a cinderblock
partition which helps direct air within the mine. That could have
pushed a pocket of methane gas into the area where the victims were
working, causing in an explosion, the agency has said.
   Costain officials have said they believe the barrier was removed
after the explosion and that it could not have been a factor even
if it had been removed before the accident.
   The William Station mine has been closed since the blast, but
MSHA will allow it to reopen as soon as three ventilation problems
are corrected, a spokesman said Friday. The problems are among some
280 citations the government has issued since the explosion.
   All but 14 of the citations have been taken care of, and none
appears related to the cause of the accident, Joey Lucas, a
spokesman for the Mine Safety and Health Administration, said in
Arlington, Va.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891020-0228 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-89 2159EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-SpaceShuttle 4thLd-Writethru a0794 10-20 1033</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Space Shuttle, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0794,1059</SECOND>
<HEAD>Atlantis Astronauts Explore the Earth with Cameras</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 9th graf, `The astronauts ...,' with 4 grafs to UPDATE
with medical demonstration; picks up 10th graf, ```We just ...,' SUBS 19th
graf, `The other crew ...,' to DELETE now-redundant first reference to
Baker, Lucid.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOWARD BENEDICT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Aerospace Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The space shuttle's astronauts were
told to conserve power Friday for a possible one- or two-day
extension of their mission due to the threat of high winds at
Atlantis' California landing site Monday.
   Mission Control directed shuttle commander Don Williams to shut
down a high-power heater on a cooling system. Williams suggested
also turning off one of three computer displays on the flight deck.
   Mission control commentator Brian Welch said NASA was trying to
trim about 600 watts of power usage to enable the shuttle to stay
in orbit longer. Without conservation, Atlantis has enough fuel,
oxygen, power and other supplies to remain aloft two days beyond
the planned five-day mission, Welch said.
   Atlantis is scheduled to land at Edwards Air Force Base in
California's Mojave Desert at 3:38 p.m. EDT.
   The possibility of a longer mission arose when a weather front
moved across the shuttle landing site. High winds following the
front could be a problem for Atlantis on Monday, forecasters said.
   Flight Director Ron Dittemore told reporters that forecasters
hope the winds will be calm by Monday, or at least calm enough to
permit landing one orbit early _ about 90 minutes before originally
scheduled _ when afternoon gusts would be less severe.
   If a Monday landing is impossible at Edwards, Dittemore said,
Atlantis would be kept in orbit at least an extra day.
   Should the winds persist for a couple days, controllers would
consider an alternate landing site, he said. The Northrup Strip at
White Sands Missile Range, N.M., would be the first choice and the
Kennedy Space Center in Florida would be second.
   The astronauts spent part of the third day of their
experiment-filled space flight demonstrating simple medical
procedures that can be done aboard the shuttle.
   In the medical demonstration, astronaut Shannon Lucid, playing
``patient,'' floated upside down while Ellen Baker, a physician,
took her temperature and examined her throat and ears. The session
was taped earlier in the day by the astronauts and later aired on
NASA satellite television.
   The shuttle's first-aid kit ``carries pretty much what any
doctor's black bag would carry,'' Ms. Baker said. It includes a
stethoscope, bandages, adhesive, aspirin and other common
medications.
   The astronauts also photographed the beauties and blemishes of
Earth for a documentary film.
   ``We just got some great shots of Central America, right over
the border between Nicaragua and Costa Rica; the city of San Jose
was completely clear,'' said astronaut Franklin Chang-Diaz, who was
born in San Jose, Costa Rica, and who has been a hero in that
country since his first space shuttle mission in 1986.
   He plans on Saturday to speak from orbit with Costa Rican
President Oscar Arias.
   But the 70mm motion pictures aren't for home movies. The crews
of several shuttle flights have been snapping thousands of feet of
film of Earth's features for a documentary called ``Exploring the
Blue Planet.''
   The large-screen film, which will debut next September at the
National Air and Space Museum in Washington, not only will show the
grandeur of the planet but also will exhibit how it is being
environmentally damaged by both man and nature.
   The IMAX Corp., which is producing the film, said it wants to
show how such things as pollution dumps into waterways,
deforestation of rain forests, storms and other phenomena have an
impact on the globe.
   The astronauts were instructed by the ground Friday to
photograph a dust storm over the African nation of Chad and
volcanoes in Japan, Indonesia, Mexico and Guatemala.
   ``We also got some good shots of the Straits of Magellan and the
Mediterranean,'' Chang-Diaz said. Other targets Friday included
Cuba and the islands of the Caribbean, the Dallas-Fort Worth area,
northwest Africa and Australia.
   The astronauts also beamed to Mission Control brilliant
television pictures of the aurora australis, or southern lights, a
luminous show created by solar radiation interacting with the
Earth's magnetic field near the South Pole.
   ``Spectacular,'' commented Chang-Diaz.
   The fifth crew member is pilot Mike McCulley.
   As the astronauts worked through a heavy schedule of medical and
science experiments, the nuclear-powered Galileo probe they
deployed about six hours after blastoff Wednesday was hurtling
across the solar system at 9,000 mph relative to the Earth and was
in ``perfect shape,'' officials reported.
   The $1.5 billion probe's course for its six-year, 2.4
billion-mile trip to Jupiter had covered nearly 500,000 miles
Friday. Once it reaches Jupiter, Galileo is to orbit the planet and
give the best look yet of another planet and find clues to the
universe's origin.
   ``The flight team is quite exulted. ... The overall assessment
is that the Galileo spacecraft is in really fine shape,'' said NASA
spokesman Charles Redmond.
   He said that on Saturday, Galileo's computer memory could be
disrupted by radiation from a solar flare that erupted on the sun
Thursday. If so, the computer should correct itself as it is
designed to do. If not, the ground will do it.
   The radiation dose should be greater than the spacecraft will
encounter at Jupiter, Redmond said, and thus will be a good test of
the vehicle. ``This will give Galileo the smart robot a chance to
prove how smart it is,'' he said.
   ``We've got a full day planned for you,'' Mission Control told
the astronauts, and even before they had breakfast, they were asked
to take pictures of the Straits of Gibraltar for the IMAX film.
   The wakeup songs were from colleges attended by the three
mission specialists on board, ``Boomer Sooners,'' ``UConn Huskies''
and ``Victory March.''
   Lucid attended the University of Oklahoma, Chang-Diaz the
University of Connecticut and Baker the State University of New
York at Buffalo.
   The crew continued experiments that measure Earth's damaged
ozone layer and study the effects of weightlessness on the human
body, the processing of polymers and the growth of corn and ice
crystals.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891020-0229 </DOCNO>
