<FIRST>r a AM-Officer-Slayings     10-20 0206</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Officer-Slayings,0215</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Officer Shoots Her Two Children, Self</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DEWEY, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A policewoman shot her two young sons to
death with her service revolver, then killed herself just as
another officer was arriving on the scene, authorities said.
   Jacqueline McMillen, a 27-year-old patrol officer for the state
Department of Public Service, shot her 3-year-old and 8-month-old
sons and then herself, Yavapai County sheriff's Capt. Bill Murphy
said.
   A DPS officer was just arriving, and had called for back-up,
said DPS spokesman Sgt. Allan Schmidt.
   Ms. McMillen, who lives in nearby Cordes Junction, brought her
children here early Friday to her estranged husband's residence
about 10 miles east of Prescott and crawled into the house after
breaking a window, Murphy said.
   Ms. McMillen then made a series of phone calls to friends and
relatives, Schmidt said. DPS officials were notified and dispatched
an officer.
   Her husband, Dennis McMillen, a 35-year-old investigative
officer in Prescott for the DPS, was in California, Schmidt said.
   The McMillens were separated and were in the process of getting
a divorce, Schmidt said.
   Jacqueline McMillen's co-workers had seen nothing to indicate
she would act violently, Schmidt said.
   ``We'll probably never know why she would do something like
this,'' said Schmidt.
</TEXT>
