<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-89 2234EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-LiverSurvivor     10-20 0347</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Liver Survivor,0355</SECOND>
<HEAD>Double Liver Recipient Celebrates Second Birthday</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CS3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN NOLAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A hospital isn't normally the ideal spot for
celebrating a second birthday, but Nancy Lopez and her son,
Joaquin, did just that Friday because she credits two liver
transplants for saving her son's life.
   ``I'm very, very happy. I think my son's life, and my life, were
saved by the operations,'' Mrs. Lopez, no relation to the
professional golfer of the same name, said at Children's Hospital
Medical Center. ``I tell you, if he wasn't alive, I wouldn't be
either, because you go through so much in something like this.''
   Joaquin was found in the first month of his life to have a
potentially fatal disease called biliary atresia, characterized by
the absence or degeneration of the liver's bile ducts and failure
of the liver.
   Surgeons at Children's Hospital performed two operations on
Joaquin in November 1988, surgically paring down larger livers to
place in his body. The first liver was rejected.
   Doctors transplanted the second liver, then removed Joaquin's
spleen a day later to prevent his body from rejecting the organ.
   Doctors and Mrs. Lopez said Friday they are pleased with the
boy's progress, even though he suffered from the flu. He will
remain on medication for life that helps keep his body from
rejecting the transplanted liver.
   Today, he is an active, normal child, his mother said. He
returns to the Cincinnati hospital for a progress checkup every
four to six weeks.
   ``He's doing great,'' Mrs. Lopez said. ``Transplantation is
making a big difference.''
   Mrs. Lopez, her husband, Joaquin, and their daughter, Beatriz,
5, moved from their native Puerto Rico to the Dayton suburb of
Centerville last year in order to be closer to the Cincinnati
hospital. They previously had been forced to make repeated trips
from Puerto Rico to Cincinnati since the boy's October 1987 birth.
   The family plans also to celebrate the son's birthday at their
home this weekend. Mrs. Lopez said relatives are flying in from
Puerto Rico for the party.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
