<FIRST>r a AM-TooMuchWapner     10-20 0382</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Too Much Wapner,0394</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judges Say Litigous Society Has Wapner on the Brain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Winning a court judgment doesn't mean you'll get
your money, because in real life things aren't necessarily as easy
as they appear on the television show ``The People's Court,'' judge
said.
   The show's popularity has made the public more aware of
small-claims court, but also has contributed to some unfortunate
misconceptions, judges said recently.
   In some metropolitan counties, the number of small claims has
more than tripled during the 1980s.
   However, the legal process is not as simple as Judge Joseph
Wapner, the black-robed hero of the TV show, sometimes makes it
look.
   Although the show may be bogging down his court with claims,
Cobb County Chief Magistrate James G. Bodiford said it's providing
him with better informed litigants.
   ``The public is getting much more intelligent about small
claims, and `The People's Court' has helped,'' he said.
   Except in collection of judgments.
   On TV, Wapner tells the winner how much money he'll collect, and
the show's producers pay him.
   Not so in real life, where the individual must collect the
judgment, sometimes by again going to court to get wages garnisheed.
   ``I remember one lady who walked up to me and said, `Judge,
which office do I go to to collect my money?''' Bodiford recalled.
``I said, `Ma'am, you have to collect the money.' She was just
incensed.''
   The National Center for State Courts says the small-claims
caseload has nearly doubled this decade. Wapner, who was in Atlanta
last summer to film a week's worth of shows with local litigants,
acknowledged that his program has influenced Americans to flock to
small-claims court in record numbers.
   ``But before our show, people didn't know that there was a
small-claims court that they can go to, and now they do,'' Wapner,
69, said from his California office. ``Now they can go to court and
have their dispute settled by a judge and not through fisticuffs.''
   In suburban Gwinnett County, Chief Magistrate Warren Davis is
getting tired of hearing about Wapner. So, he now issues a standard
warning at the start of each session in his small-claims court:
``Television is not real life.''
   ``I can't tell you how many times I've been quoted Judge Wapner
in court,'' Davis said.
</TEXT>
