<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-89 2241EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Turkey-Politics     10-20 0412</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Turkey-Politics,0426</SECOND>
<HEAD>Premier Ozal Fails in Bid to Win First Ballot</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANKARA, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Premier Turgut Ozal, running for president
in defiance of growing protests, failed to receive the necessary
majority for election Friday in a first ballot held at a parliament
session boycotted by the opposition.
   Ozal received 247 votes from the 285 deputies of his Motherland
Party in the 450-member parliament.
   This would be enough to put him over on a third ballot Oct. 31,
when a simple majority is sufficient but it fell short of the
two-thirds majority of 300 required in the first two ballots.
   Fethi Celikbas, a Motherland deputy who is the only candidate
running against Ozal, garnered 18 votes, and the rest cast empty
ballots.
   Ozal criticized the opposition boycott, saying it went against
their constitutional duty. ``They should have named their own
candidate and participated in the election,'' he told a news
conference after the balloting.
   He said he planned to designate a new premier from his party
within days after he takes over as president Nov. 9. That is when
the seven-year term of President Kenan Evren expires.
   Four Motherland deputies have resigned from the party to protest
Ozal's decision to run for president.
   Tinaz Titiz, a former tourism minister in the Ozal government,
said in his resignation statement Friday that he could not condone
an election carried out without the participation of the opposition.
   Also empty were the seats reserved in the galleries for outgoing
President Evren, leader of the 1980 military coup, and top military
officials.
   The military, always a power behind presidential elections, has
made clear it will stay out this time.
   Opposition parties and newspaper commentators claim Ozal lacks a
popular mandate since the Motherland Party suffered a major defeat
in local elections in March. The party came in third after the
Social Democrats and the centrist True Path Party of former Premier
Suleyman Demirel, winning 21.75 percent of the votes.
   They also say Ozal, the first premier attempting to ascend to
the presidency in Turkey, cannot be the nonpartisan head of state
required by the constitution.
   Erdal Inonu, leader of the Social Democrats, said they would
consider resigning from the parliament en masse if this could stop
Ozal.
   If elected, Ozal will be Turkey's eight president and the second
who is not a former military man.
   Ozal was elected premier six years ago when his newly founded
Motherland Party won the 1983 elections that restored civilian rule.
</TEXT>
