<SECOND>AM-SF Quake-Boulder Creek, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0792</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Tops with 10 new grafs to update with geologists OKing return
to homes, explaining causes of house collapses, increasing number of damaged
houses. Picks up 10th graf pvs, ``State transit ...''</HEAD>
<HEAD>Mountain Enclave, Already Damaged, Braces for More Slides After Quake</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COLLEEN BARRY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOULDER CREEK, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A weekend of rain loomed as a
threat in the mountains north of Santa Cruz where 60 houses, some
of them the dream homes of Silicon Valley commuters, have tumbled
off stilts or foundations in this hillside town and a score of
others suffered severe damage.
   On Friday, a team of geologists advised occupants of 100 other
houses that they could safely return. Fears of massive landslides
had earlier prompted official urgings to evacuate, although many
residents brushed them off.
   ``It's a dangerous area, but all my stuff is here. My dogs are
here. I figured you go down with the ship. Where do you go?'' said
Todd Viele, 27.
   The geologists determined that a jagged fissure which streaked
through yards had caused only six of the 60 ruined houses near the
top of Blue Ridge Road to tumble; the bedrock did not split, they
said. The other damaged houses were shaken off their foundations by
ground motion.
   Residents of more than 100 houses at the bottom of the road were
told Friday evening the fissure seemed unlikely to cause the
landslides that only hours before had seemed to threaten to sweep
them away.
   ``They are calling it a slight fissure where the ground opened
and shifted in a localized area,'' said Stan Robustelli, assistant
chief of the Boulder Creek fire district. ``They are not concerned
about the mountain coming down at this point.''
   The 6,800 people around Boulder Creek appear to be among the
hardest hit by the earthquake and among the least willing to leave
their homes, many of them built of redwood and glass and carrying
pricetags in the hundreds of thousands of dollars. In recent years,
the town was transformed from a mountain enclave of summer homes to
a year-round community, with many residents working in the nearby
technology corridor called Silicon Valley.
   As experts made the rounds inspecting structures Friday, they
counted 82 houses that suffered moderate structural damage to total
loss, including the 60 at the top of the road.
   ``When you start to figure percentages of people and percentages
of homes in the area compared to San Francisco, we have a greater
percentage loss here, except for loss of life,'' said Fire Chief
Bud Tomlin. ``We were very fortunate. We didn't have any deaths or
serious injuries.''
   With rain starting early Saturday morning and expected to last
through the weekend, jittery residents remained concerned about the
uncertain earth beneath their feet.
   State transit crews patched deep cracks in roads to try to
prevent rain from washing away more soil and houses.
   The 100 houses at the lower end of narrow, twisting Blue Ridge
Road were at the greatest risk because of deep cracks several
inches wide in the pavement. About 60 homes at the upper end of the
road have already shifted up to 4 feet off their foundations or
have fallen off stilts that propped them on the mountainside.
   Suzanne Bellairs, whose home is built on a concrete slab,
nevertheless was staying at a friend's trailer that officials
considered out of danger of landslides. But she was contemplating
going home, where officials warned it might not be safe.
   ``There isn't any doubt in my mind that if the mountain comes
down, we'll lose our home,'' said Bottoms.
   ``I feel safer out of it, but it's more stressful being gone,''
she said. ``We're staying in a 25-foot trailer with four adults and
four kids. It would be better to be stressed at home.''
</TEXT>
