<FIRST>r a AM-CustomsOfficial     10-20 0232</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Customs Official,0236</SECOND>
<HEAD>Customs Official Charged With Smuggling</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BROWNSVILLE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The top U.S. Customs official in this
border city was arrested Friday on felony charges he smuggled
liquor, clothing, saddles and food into the United States,
officials said.
   Fernando Macias, who directs Customs operations at two
international bridges and the Port of Brownsville, was arrested
Friday morning by agents from the agency's internal affairs
division, said Customs spokeswoman Judy Turner.
   Macias pleaded innocent before U.S. Magistrate Fidencia G. Garza
to eight charges accusing him of illegally bringing items into the
United States and a ninth count of failing to pay duty on the
liquor. He was released on a $200,000 personal recognizance bond.
   If convicted of all the charges, Macias faces up to 43 years in
prison and $2,250,000 in fines, according to Assistant U.S.
Attorney Mervin Mosbacker.
   Mosbacker refused to discuss details of the investigation that
led to Macias' indictment and arrest.
   Macias said he was innocent. ``I've been in Brownsville for nine
and a half years, I've always tried to present a positive image,''
he said. ``I've been in the (Customs) service for 20 years; I'm not
going to throw it away.''
   The indictment accuses Macias of importing merchandise from
Mexico last Dec. 7 without paying taxes, duty, bond or having it
inspected. The merchandise included saddles, food, clothing and
several bottles of liquor, the indictment said.
</TEXT>
