<FIRST>a a PM-DangeratWork-Cases Adv25   10-20 0290</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Danger at Work-Cases, Adv 25,0292</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv25</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Wednesday PMs, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Workplace Injury Prosecutions, At a Glance</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Danger at Work-Prosecutions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Criminal prosecutions have been initiated in a wide variety of
work-related deaths and injuries. Here are outlines of some recent
cases.
   MICHIGAN _ Prosecutors are awaiting a decision from the Michigan
Court of Appeals on whether there's sufficient evidence to go to
trial in the carbon-monoxide death of an employee of a company that
installed cable TV wires. Prosecutors want to try a company foreman
on involuntary manslaughter charges, claiming he knew the van the
man died in had a faulty exhaust system. Two lower courts have
ruled opposite ways on the evidence issue.
   WISCONSIN _ A jury convicted a company of reckless homicide in
the death of a man who drove a front-end loader off a 60-foot
cliff. The company, the prosecutor said, knew the man had a history
of epilepsy, provided less than 40 hours of training and had no
on-site supervisor. Another company pleaded no contest to an
endangerment charge and was fined in the death of a worker killed
in a crane collapse.
   TEXAS _ Two construction companies and one executive were
convicted of criminally negligent homicide in the deaths of three
workers in separate trench cave-ins. The three convictions were
overturned on the ground that state law was pre-empted by federal
occupational safety regulations. They are being appealed. A third
company has been charged in a similar case.
   NEW YORK _ An appeal is pending in the assault convictions of
two executives of Pymm Thermometer Corp. for exposing workers to
toxic mercury. A judge dismissed the verdict on pre-emption grounds.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Wed PMs, Oct. 25</NOTE>
</DOC>
