<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Consumer prices rose an unexpectedly modest
0.2 percent in September, the government said, soothing frazzled
financial markets.
   Investors took the report Thursday as an indication the Federal
Reserve Board has room to lower interest rates, and the stock
market rallied. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials gained
39.55 points to 2,683.20.
   Inflation, which had been rising at a 6.7 percent annual rate
from January through May, has abated to a 4.4 percent rate for the
first nine months of the year.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's 38.9 million Social Security
beneficiaries can count on a 4.7 percent benefit increase in
January that will boost the average retired worker's pension by $25
a month, the government said.
   The annual cost-of-living adjustment, the biggest in 7{ years,
will increase the typical benefit check to $566 a month, the Social
Security Administration said Thursday.
   For someone who retires at age 65 in 1990, the maximum monthly
benefit will be $975, up from $899 this year.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
