<DOCNO> AP891020-0260 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-89 0058EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-ElderlyHousing     10-20 0260</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Elderly Housing,0271</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pilot Project Outlined to Make Mortgage Money Available for Senior
Housing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thirty-nine lenders across the country will
take part in a pilot project to provide mortgages to meet the
special housing needs of senior citizens, the Federal National
Mortgage Association announced.
   Fannie Mae, as the association is known, has committed $100
million to its new Seniors' Housing Opportunities project, which
offers four types of mortgages to persons 62 years of age and older.
   ``To date, Fannie Mae has received more than 3,000 inquiries
from consumers about these mortgages,'' said Fannie Mae Senior Vice
President Larry H. Dale.
   Dale said Thursday he association would consider expanding the
project beyond the $100 million commmitment or make the loans
standard mortgage products if lenders experience heavy consumer
demand.
   The mortgages are designed to make it easier for elderly
citizens to obtain housing or maintain their current residence.
They would provide:
   _Accessory apartments, or second, completely private living
units installed in a home.
   _Elderly cottage housing opportunities, which are separate,
self-contained temporary units built on the lot of an existing home
as a residence for a relative.
   _Homesharing by two or more adults.
   _Sale-leaseback, an arrangment in which a home is sold to an
investor and then leased back to the seller.
   Fannie Mae is a congressionally chartered, shareholder-owned
company and the nation's largest investor in home mortages. It said
a list of lenders and a description of the mortgages can be
obtained by writing: Fannie Mae, P.O. Drawer SHO, 3900 Wisconsin
Avenue NW, Washington, DC 20016.
</TEXT>
