<FIRST>r f BC-SooLine 1stLd-Writethru f0150 10-20 0451</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Soo Line, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0150,0460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soo Line Receives Buyout Bid From Its Majority Owner</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf to UPDATE with closing stock price and CORRECT
52-week high. Picks up 4th graf, `A buyout ....' INSERTS 2 grafs after
7th graf pvs, `Minneapolis-based ...,' with third-quarter earnings. Picks
up 8th graf pvs, `Canadian Pacific ...'.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soo Line Corp. is considering an $82 million
buyout bid from Canadian Pacific Ltd., which already owns 56
percent of Soo Line stock, the two railroads announced Thursday.
   Canadian Pacific would pay $19.50 a share for all outstanding
common stock under the proposal. Soo Line said a special committee
of independent directors would consider the proposal.
   Soo Line stock closed Thursday at $20.25 on the New York Stock
Exchange, up up $2.75 cents a share. The stock's 52-week high was
$26.37{ and its low was $16.75.
   A buyout would be subject to the approval of shareholders
representing at least two-thirds of the 9.5 million shares of
outstanding Soo Line stock, Soo Line spokesman John Bergene said.
Approval also is needed from the Interstate Commerce Commission,
the special independent directors' committee and Soo Line's overall
board of directors, which is controlled by Canadian Pacific.
   ``I guess you would have to characterize it as friendly,''
Bergene said the buyout bid. ``Our relationship with CP has been a
close one for many years.''
   Montreal-based Canadian Pacific has controlled more than 50
percent of Soo Line stock since 1961. Soo Line acquired the
Milwaukee Road in 1985.
   Minneapolis-based Soo Line, the 10th largest rail system in the
United States, operates freight lines in 12 midwestern states. 1988
was Soo Line's first profitable year since 1984. The railroad had
net income of $15.6 million, or $1.64 a share, compared with a loss
of $8.5 million, or a loss of 90 cents a share, in 1987.
   But in the third quarter ended Sept. 30, the results of which
were announced Thursday, Soo Line had a net loss of $1.5 million,
or 16 cents a share. That compares with a profit for the same
period last year of $2.9 million, or 31 cents a share.
   For the first nine months of 1989, the railroad lost $398,000,
or 4 cents a share, the company said.
   Canadian Pacific, which earned $820.1 million in fiscal 1988 on
revenues of $12 billion, is a diversified company with holdings in
transportation, waste services, energy, forest products, real
estate and hotels, and telecommunications and manufacturing.
   Graeme McMurray, a Canadian Pacific spokesman in Montreal, said
the proposed buyout ``is the best way to rationalize the
relationship between CP and the Soo and maintain the viability of
the Soo Line.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
