<FIRST>r f BC-McCaw-LIN     10-20 0282</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-McCaw-LIN,0290</SECOND>
<HEAD>McCaw Clarifies Its Offer for LIN</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KIRKLAND, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   McCaw Cellular Communications, Inc. on
Thursday announced that it has clarified in a letter its $125 per
share offer to purchase 50.3 percent of LIN Broadcasting.
   ``We hope that our prompt, detailed response to the issues
raised by LIN will demonstrate our commitment to providing LIN
shareholders with the opportunity to fully participate in the
growth of the private market value of the company,'' said Craig O.
McCaw, chairman and chief executive of McCaw Cellular.
   ``It is important for shareholders of LIN to recognize that as
majority owners of LIN, our principal objective would be to
maximize the value of all LIN shares _ those held by the public and
those held by us.''
   McCaw on Oct. 10 offered to purchase 22 million LIN shares for
$125 per share cash. That would result in McCaw owning 50.3 percent
of LIN.
   Under the offer, continuing LIN shareholders would be protected
by a private market value guarantee, designed so shareholders could
benefit from further appreciation in the value of cellular assets
and receive a full private market price for their remaining shares
in about five years.
   In its letter, McCaw provided LIN's board of directors with
several clarifications, including that three independent directors
would be designated by the current board; LIN would have a right to
pursue all corporate opportunities to acquire U.S. cellular
interests outside of McCaw interests; and if LIN is put up for sale
in five years rather than purchased by McCaw at appraised private
market value, McCaw will not submit a bid unless the independent
directors request it, and the independent directors will run the
sale process.
</TEXT>
