<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Railroads     10-20 0320</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Railroads,0332</SECOND>
<HEAD>Union Pacific, Burlington Northern Report 3rd-Quarter Profit Declines</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Union Pacific Corp. reported a 17 percent drop in third-quarter
profit Thursday, blaming the lower income primarily on refinery
operations the company has sold. Burlington Northern Inc. also
reported a decline in profit, due mostly to income lost from
operations that have been spun off to shareholders.
   Discounting the refinery costs, Union Pacific's profits dropped
2 percent, reflecting a softening in the economy, the company said.
   Union Pacific said third-quarter earnings totaled $137.4
million, or $1.35 per share, on revenues of $1.58 billion. For the
same period last year, the company earned $165 million, or $1.44
per share, on revenues of $1.54 billion.
   The refinery operations that have been sold earned $24.9 million
in the third quarter of 1988. Subtracting that income,
third-quarter 1988 earnings were $140.1 million, or $1.23 per share.
   In May, the Bethlehem, Pa.-based company bought about 11,017
shares from stockholders, softening the drop in earnings per share.
   Union Pacific's nine-month earnings totaled $427.7 million, or
$3.98 per share, on revenues of $4.6 billion. For the same period
last year, net income was $456.4 million, or $4 per share, on
revenues of $4.9 billion. The adjusted 1988 figures were $402.7
million in profit or $3.53 per share.
   Fort Worth, Texas-based Burlington Northern reported a
third-quarter profit of $72.9 million, or 95 cents a share,
compared with $120.4 million, or $1.60 per share, in 1988's third
quarter.
   Discounting the company's natural resources division, which was
spun off to shareholders at the end of last year, Burlington
Northern earned $66.3 million, or 89 cents per share, in 1988's
third quarter.
   Severe weather, longer hauls and competition contributed to the
earnings decline, the company said.
   Adding to the net income were lower interest rates and a pre-tax
gain of $14.9 million on the sale of a partial interest in Trailer
Train Co., Burlington Northern said.
</TEXT>
