<DOCNO> AP891020-0264 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-89 0146EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-SFQuake-PacificExchange Bjt   10-20 0603</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SF Quake-Pacific Exchange, Bjt,0617</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trading Goes Well at Pacific Stock Exchange Outposts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Options dealers from the Pacific Stock Exchange may have been
suffering from a bit of jet lag, but they managed to trade
contracts at makeshift posts built with lightening speed at
exchanges in Chicago, Philadelphia and New York.
   ``It went real smooth,'' said Neal Berry, one of roughly 150
traders and support staffers who were shuttled by chartered jet to
exchanges farther East following the Bay Quake that knocked out
power at their own market in San Francisco.
   ``Customers could reach us, we could get (trades) out, though
not as timely as if we were on our own exchange,'' said Berry, who
was working at the New York Stock Exchange on Thursday.
   At the Chicago Board Options Exchange, spokesman Warren Moulds
said there were ``no hitches. Once they got oriented, it was an
easy do.''
   Volume was lighter than the usual 70,000 contracts, but traders
said they expect activity to pick up as they become more familiar
with their surroundings and also because of today's expiration of
October stock options.
   Today is the deadline for investors to renegotiate the options,
which enable them to buy or or sell specific stocks at a specific
price at a certain time.
   The Pacific exchange trades options _ which many investors use
to hedge their stock positions _ in 130 underlying stocks. Among
big-name stocks that have options traded only on the Pacific
exchange are Hilton Hotels Corp. and Compaq Computer Corp.
   The Pacific exchange was able to continue stock trading by
rerouting orders through the Los Angeles exchange. But because the
Los Angeles exchange doesn't trade options, officials took the
unprecedented step of relocating the options operation.
   Plans to transport Pacific options trading began forming shortly
after the earthquake hit late Tuesday afternoon local time,
knocking out the electricity. From then on it was an
around-the-clock effort involving a multitude of phone calls among
exchange officials and the Securities and Exchange Commission,
which sanctioned the plan Wednesday.
   At the American and New York stock exchanges, carpenters and
electricians worked through the night erecting trading areas for
the California traders. At the Philadelphia Stock Exchange,
computer experts labored marathon-style laying extra cables and
programming exchange computers to accept new issues.
   The American exchange, like the Big Board, handled hotel
accommodations for traders assigned there.
   In Chicago, where Pacific dealers arrived early enough to begin
trading at the market's 8:30 a.m. CDT opening, maps were handed out
to help them negotiate their way around the 50,000-square-foot
trading floor of the exchange.
   But in New York and Philadelphia, extra time was needed for the
traders to arrive and get settled and trading did not begin until 1
p.m. EDT. Trading was to begin at the normal morning hour today.
   Most of the traders were in good spirits, though Berry said a
house belonging to one of them had collapsed in the disastrous
quake.
   ``Exhausted? That's an understatement,'' said Berry after
trading closed Thursday.
   Exchange officials were no better rested after market events
beginning last Friday, when the Dow Jones industrial average fell
109.58 points _ a drop exceeded only by the Black Monday crash of
1987 _ panicking financial markets around the world.
   ``It's been a bad week,'' said George Kender, executive vice
president of Chicago-based Options Clearing Corp., which processes
all options trades.
   In San Francisco, building inspectors cleared the exchange's
trading floors Thursday, but spokesman Dale Carlson said options
traders would remain where they were through today. Normal trading
was expected to resume Monday in San Francisco.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891020-0265 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-89 0154EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-ConsumerFraud Bjt   10-20 0462</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Consumer Fraud, Bjt,0476</SECOND>
<HEAD>Group Says Common Practices Not in Consumers' Interest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARTON REPPERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The next time you write your phone number on a
credit card receipt or obligingly hand over a credit card when
paying by check, think twice, a consumer group says.
   The organization, Bankcard Holders of America, says these common
practices of stores and restaurants may lead to fraud and invasion
of privacy.
   ``Store clerks often pressure consumers into writing their
bankcard numbers on personal checks, but these consumers don't
realize the potential danger in doing so,'' the group's director,
Elgie Holstein, said at a news conference Thursday.
   He contended that ``mail order fraud and application fraud are
increasingly popular crimes, and placing this information (a card's
number and expiration date) on a personal check enables a thief to
make purchases or apply for credit in the customer's name.''
   ``Requiring customers to present a major credit card as
identification, or even noting on the check that the consumer holds
a Visa or MasterCard, can be an appropriate merchant practice,''
Holstein said. ``It is dangerous, however, to require credit card
numbers to be written on checks.''
   To help consumers deal with this practice, the organization is
making available a wallet-sized ``Consumer Action Card'' to present
to merchants who insist on writing credit card numbers on personal
checks. The wallet card alerts merchants that recording this
information encourages fraud and may violate a customer's privacy.
   The bank card-holders group also is concerned that merchants
frequently require consumers to write their phone numbers on credit
card sales slips when processing bank credit card transactions.
   Holstein said this is a violation of consumers' privacy rights.
Also, he said that under Visa and MasterCard operating rules,
merchants cannot refuse a customer's sale just because he or she
refuses to provide personal information on a bankcard sales slip.
   ``Merchants do not need a credit card customer's phone number
since a merchant who correctly processes a bankcard transaction is
relieved of further financial liability by the cardholder's bank,''
Holstein said.
   Bankcard Holders of America describes itself as a national
non-profit consumer education organization.
   A brochure containing the wallet-sized ``Consumer Action Card''
is available for $1.00 from BHA, 460 Spring Park Place, Suite 1000,
Herndon, Va, 22070.
   By coincidence, The Limited Inc. chain of specialty apparel
stores announced later Thursday that its stores would no longer
write credit card numbers on personal checks used for purchases and
would no longer require a customer's phone number on credit card
sales slips.
   But Alfred Dietzel, a Limited spokesman, said the company was
not motivated by concerns about fraud. He said the company is
simply hoping to serve customers more efficiently.
   He said the same-day timing of the announcement was not
intentional.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891020-0266 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-89 0205EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-PerestroikaPitfalls Bjt   10-20 0666</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Perestroika Pitfalls, Bjt,0693</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tough Start-Up for U.S.-Soviet Joint Venture</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A year ago this week, Ambassador Yuriy
Dubinin led a toast at the Soviet Embassy _ with Soviet champagne _
to a new joint venture between American investors and his
government.
   The idea was to capitalize, in the full sense of the word, on
Mikhail Gorbachev's campaign of perestroika, or economic
restructuring, by introducing Russian products such as that
champagne and beer to American consumers.
   A year later, importer Torg International, as the company was
named, has little to show for itself except difficulties here and
the pitfalls of perestroika.
   Its Englewood Cliffs office closed because of ``internal
problems'' with employees, said company president Dr. George
Carroll, a Florida-based millionaire entrepreneur with a medical
degree. Torg now has a new office in Manhattan.
   Backer Jay Chiat of the advertising agency Chiat-Day-Mojo pulled
out in May, citing frustration with progress in importing goods.
   The public relations firm hired to promote Torg,
Chiat-Day-Mojo-owned Jessica Dee Communications Inc., was dropped
because there was little for it to do, said Carroll.
   Now, Carroll and Soviet emigre Lev Model work alone with help
from consultants. Together they own 51 percent of Torg, one of the
first joint ventures between a U.S. company and the Soviet Union in
this country, Carroll said.
   He would not disclose their investment so far.
   Adding to their difficulties are problems connected with the
Soviet apparatus providing the goods.
   ``I think we were somewhat premature in blowing our horn,'' said
Carroll, speaking in an interview from his Winter Haven, Fla., home.
   ``It was perhaps unrealistic of us to think of things getting
here sooner,'' he said.
   May had been the target date for the venture's mineral water
soft drinks to be introduced, to be followed by a Soviet beer
called Zhiguli.
   But Carroll has not given up, and said Torg _ the Russian word
for trade _ will become active soon.
   A national distributor has been signed up to handle Zhiguli,
pronounced zee-GUH-lee, and should be bringing the brew to market
by year's end, said Carroll. He would not identify the distributor.
   Discussions are continuing with distributors for Soviet
champagne, wine and soft drinks made from mineral water in the
nation's Georgian region, he said.
   ``In the great scheme of life, I don't think we're way behind.''
   Carroll said Torg's efforts have lately centered mainly on
showing products to U.S. distributors. Difficulty in obtaining
samples is just one of the obstacles in Torg's way.
   He said the Soviets are not used to shipping small quantities.
Goods are also backed up at shipping points in that nation.
   Jack Brougher, a U.S. Commerce Department expert on Soviet
trade, said lack of cooperation among Soviet ministries unused to
the joint venture idea may also be holding things up.
   ``Perestroika involves decentralization of the entire foreign
trade machinery,'' added William D. Forrester, president of the
U.S.-U.S.S.R. Trade and Economic Council. ``It takes time for the
system to adjust to change. Frankly, I think they are doing
remarkably well.''
   When Torg's formation was announced, there were 110 to 115 joint
ventures with foreign companies in the Soviet Union. About a dozen
involved U.S. interests. Now, says Brougher, Americans are involved
in 90 of about 1,000 registered joint ventures, about 100 of which
are active.
   Of the American joint venturers, the 40-year-old Carroll's
background may make him standout.
   Born in Munich of Soviet emigre parents, Carroll learned Russian
so he could speak to his grandmother. He owns a weight-loss
franchise operation based in Akron, Ohio, and his previous holdings
included a surgical center and medical laboratory.
   ``He seems very suave and sophisticated,'' said someone formerly
involved in Torg who spoke on condition of anonymity. ``He's the
kind of person who exudes a lot of charisma.''
   Model has imported small amounts of Soviet products for Russian
communities in the United States for nearly two decades. He and
Carroll met through mutual friends.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891020-0267 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-89 0206EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-FTC-TitleInsurance     10-20 0191</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-FTC-Title Insurance,0199</SECOND>
<HEAD>FTC Cites Title Insurance Companies For Fee Fixing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Trade Commission has ruled that
five national title insurance companies illegally fixed title
search fees in six states.
   The FTC found Thursday that the title companies set prices for
title search and examination services by participating in a rating
bureau that pooled data on their policies and claims.
   The agency ordered them to set future rates independently in New
Jersey, Pennsylvania, Connecticut, Wisconsin, Arizona and Montana.
   The FTC had issued a complaint against the companies in 1985.
   Title insurance companies provide two basic services: they
search court records for liens or other restrictions on property
titles, and they provide insurance if there are hidden liens on
property or ownership is in doubt.
   Many firms have been offering both services for a single fee.
The FTC found that federal law exempts insurance, but not
title-searching activities, from antitrust regulations.
   The five title insurance firms ordered to change the way they
set their rates are Ticor Title Insurance Co., Chicago Title
Insurance Co., Safeco Title Insurance Co., Lawyers Title Insurance
Corp. and Stewart Title Guaranty Co.
</TEXT>
