<FIRST>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     10-20 0292</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0304</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Mixed In Listless European Trading, Gold Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was mixed in listless European trading
at midmorning today. Gold prices were lower in dull dealings.
   Foreign exchange dealers predicted a quiet day for the dollar in
the absence of new economic indicators and after recent volatility
on currency and stock markets.
   ``Technically, the dollar is looking overbought,'' one analyst
in Milan said. ``We'll probably see some corrective action in that
as people reposition themselves before the weekend.''
   A Milan trader said, ``There's very little upside potential,'' a
sentiment echoed by a Frankfurt dealer who said, ``The general
sentiment is still bearish.''
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar closed at 141.35 yen, down 0.20 yen from
Thursday's close of 141.55 yen. Later, in London, it was quoted at
a higher rate of 141.76 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Thursday's
prices, included: 1.8460 West German marks, down from 1.8525;
1.6180 Swiss francs, down from 1.6225; 6.2702 French francs, down
from 6.2875; 2.0833 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0820; 1,359.25
Italian lire, up from 1,358.50; 1.1742 Canadian dollars, up from
1.1741.
   In London, the dollar gained against the British pound. It cost
$1.5930 to buy one pound, cheaper than $1.5940 late Thursday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $366.90 a troy ounce,
down from late Thursday's $367.75. At midmorning, the city's five
major bullion dealers fixed a later recommended price of $366.70
dollars.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $367, down from $368.20 late
Thursday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $1.49 to close at a bid
$367.40. Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $5.09 a troy
ounce, unchanged from late Thursday.
</TEXT>
