<FIRST>u f PM-Japan-Markets     10-20 0404</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stocks Climb, Dollar Slips</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prices continued to climb on the Tokyo Stock
Exchange today, while the dollar slipped against the Japanese yen.
   The dollar closed at 141.35 yen, down 0.20 yen from Thursday's
close of 141.55 yen. It opened the day higher at 141.93 yen and
then ranged between 141.35 and 142.05 yen.
   On the stock market, the 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average rose
112.16 points, or 0.3 percent, to 35,486.38. It was the index's
fourth consecutive gain since Monday's plunge of 647.33 points, the
year's largest single drop.
   Dealers said orders from small-lot buyers, relieved at gains
overnight on Wall Street, streamed in continuously during the day.
   The Nikkei index, which rose to 35,611.38 soon after trading
began, lost part of its early gains toward the end of the session
due to profit taking, dealers said.
   Although the trading mood was positive throughout the day,
``Investors, especially dealers, don't want to hold a strong
position over the weekend,'' said a trader at Dai-Ichi Securities.
   Dealers said the index has bounced back steadily since Monday as
stability in the foreign exchange market and on Wall Street have
renewed investor confidence in the stock market.
   The dollar in New York fell earlier due to a
smaller-than-expected increase in the U.S. consumer price index
released Thursday but recovered later as the Dow Jones industrial
average of 30 major issues rose, traders said.
   The United States reported the nation's seasonally adjusted
Consumer Price Index rose by 0.2 percentage point in September.
   The Tokyo market had expected a 0.4-0.5 percentage point rise,
which discouraged dollar buying, a trader with a major Japanese
commercial bank said.
   ``At the same time, however, other market players reassured by
the steady recovery in the New York stock market are inclined to
buy the U.S. currency,'' he said, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   ``The dollar is likely to get weaker in the long run considering
the current slowdown in the U.S. economy,'' the trader added.
   Dealers said a number of large Japanese institutional investors
were still purchasing dollars, but selling by exporters and
speculators was holding down the U.S. currency.
   Also on Friday, the Tokyo Stock Exchange began option trading in
the Tokyo Stock Price Index for futures issues, in which
shareholders can take market action with a fixed quantity of a
security, or at a fixed price within a specified time to avoid
risks in spot trading.
</TEXT>
