<FIRST>r f PM-Qintex-Chapter11     10-20 0428</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Qintex-Chapter 11,0442</SECOND>
<HEAD>Qintex Entertainment Files for Bankruptcy Protection</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Qintex Entertainment Inc., an
affiliate of the Australian firm facing a $50 million lawsuit
related to its failed attempt to buy MGM-UA Communications Co.,
today said it has filed for protection under Chapter 11 of the
Federal Bankruptcy Code.
   The company also sought Chapter 11 protection Thursday for two
of its subsidiaries, Hal Roach Studios Inc. and Qintex Productions
Inc., the company announced in a news release this morning.
   Company spokesman Daniel Saks, reached at home by telephone,
said the bankruptcy filing was unrelated to Qintex Australia Ltd.'s
failed $1.5 billion MGM-UA acquisition, blaming it instead on the
collapse of a separate Qintex Entertainment $5.9 million loan deal.
   ``Qintex Entertainment was not a party to the merger with MGM-UA
and it was not named in the subsequent lawsuit,'' he said.
   The company also announced that David Evans had resigned as
president and chief executive officer of Qintex Entertainment, but
said he would continue as a full-time consultant until a successor
is selected.
   MGM-UA terminated the $1.5 billion acquisition by Qintex
Australia, which holds 43 percent of Qintex Entertainment's stock,
earlier this month after the company failed to provide MGM-UA with
a required $50 million letter of credit.
   MGM-UA sued Qintex Australia for alleged breach of contract and
fraud, seeking $50 million in damages. The lawsuit was pending in
Los Angeles.
   Qintex Entertainment and Qintex Australia were working with a
lender to secure more than $5.9 million needed for a distribution
agreement with Hal Roach Studios, Saks said.
   But the lender, which Saks refused to identify, declined to
provide the funds, prompting the bankruptcy filing in Los Angeles,
Saks said.
   The $5,945,000 loan was for ``a guarantee payment against MCA's
share of a distribution agreement with Hal Roach Studios,'' the
spokesman said.
   ``It was a long-standing agreement with Hal Roach Studios''
established before the MGM-UA acquisition failed, he said,
declining to elaborate further on the deal.
   At a meeting of Qintex Entertainment's Board of Directors on
Oct. 18, the bankruptcy petition was authorized to offset the loss
of corporate assets, to protect company shareholders and to deal
with creditor's claims, the company said in a prepared statement.
   The company also announced that Roger Kimmel, an independent
director of Qintex Entertainment's nine-member board, had resigned
because he was no longer needed due to the failure of the MGM-UA
acquisition.
   Officials said the company will continue to operate during
Chapter 11 proceedings. Under Chapter 11, companies are protected
from creditors while they work out financial difficulties.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
