<FIRST>r f BC-Drexel-Delaware     10-20 0244</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Drexel-Delaware,0255</SECOND>
<HEAD>Drexel To Pay Delaware $50,000 To Settle</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WILMINGTON, Del. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. will pay
Delaware $50,000 and observe certain restrictions if it decides to
do business in the state again, officials said.
   The New York secuurities firm in September pleaded guilty to six
felonies and began paying $650 million to the government to settle
securities fraud charges stemming from the government's insider
trading investigation.
   The firm said recently it expects to pay $11.5 million overall
to settle with states, avoid litigation and retain its ability to
do business.
   Drexel spokesman Steven Anreder said the Delaware agreement was
similar to those reached with 25 other states. Drexel this year
sold its retail brokerage business and Anreder said it has no plans
to do business in Delaware.
   The $50,000 payment settles any administrative charges that
would have been brought against the company by the state as a
result of its guilty plea, Attorney General Charles M. Oberlystet
III said Thursday.
   Delaware had the authority to suspend Drexel's operating license.
   ``Some states are taking a harder line, but we considered our
enforcement priorities in making this settlement,'' Hubbard said,
noting that Drexel does not have a Delaware office.
   If Drexel decided to do business in Delaware it would have to
``give us notice and get a law firm to certify that they have a
compliance procedure'' to assure the state that Drexel would obey
state and federal securities laws, Hubbard said.
</TEXT>
