<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-89 1149EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f BC-CreditMarkets Adv23   10-20 0768</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Credit Markets, Adv 23,0797</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv23</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Monday, Oct. 23</HEAD>
<HEAD>No Quake Fissures in Huge California Muni Bond Market</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BART ZIEGLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   California's municipal bond market, the nation's
largest, felt barely a ripple from the earthquake last week, though
some of the roads, bridges and buildings financed by the bonds
sustained damage.
   Prices of the bonds were virtually unaffected by the quake.
Mutual fund operators said they received few panicky calls from
investors in California-based municipal bond funds, and almost none
of the investors pulled out.
   One reason for the complacency is that precautions for an
earthquake were built into most of the bonds. Another less
reassuring reason is that information about the extent of quake
damage to facilities built by the bonds was sketchy.
   Bond experts expect few problems with California municipal bond
issuers making interest payments in the short term.
   However, over a longer period of time, there could be defaults
when reserve funds or insurance policies designed to make
short-term payments in such an emergency run out, experts said last
week.
   ``We don't really know the extent of all the damage that has
taken place. It's not inconceivable that there could be
interruptions in even some of the tax-supported debt,'' said Peter
Schmitt, chief operating officer of Financial Guarantee Insurance
Co., a bond insurance firm.
   Among the bond issues most at risk, experts said, are ones sold
by small municipalities to pay for non-essential facilities, such
as secondary hospitals, that may not be rebuilt if found damaged.
   Also at risk are bonds that financed port facilities. If any
were damaged extensively, there's a chance the operators may not
rebuild since there is strong competition from more modern ports in
the Northwest, Schmitt said.
   A third area of concern are the so-called tax increment
districts in California. These districts were established to
promote industrial development, and taxes from the new industry go
to pay off bonds that were sold to build highways and other
infrastructure improvements in the areas.
   If any of these areas were damaged by the quake, there's no
guarantee the industries would rebuild, which means the revenue to
pay off the bonds could drop, said Hyman C. Grossman, a managing
director at Standard &amp; Poor's Corp., a credit-rating agency.
   About 30 percent of California municipal bonds issued so far
this year carry bond insurance that guarantees interest and
principal payments will be made for the life of the bond, Schmitt
said.
   Of the remainder, many contain other provisions to ensure
payments, such as earthquake insurance on facilities funded by the
bonds, short-term work-stoppage insurance contracts, and a reserve
fund equal to one year's interest payments, he said.
   Another protection in some issues involves the combination of
several revenue sources to ensure that if one facility built by
bonds is damaged, related facilities would continue providing
revenue.
   For example, Grossman said, though the Bay Bridge was seriously
damaged by the quake, revenue from other toll bridges in the area
is tied into the same revenue stream and should provide enough
money to make payments on the bonds that built the bridges.
   But not all municipal bonds carry such protections. ``By process
of deduction there probably are some bonds out there that will have
some interruption of payment,'' Schmitt said.
   Grossman said he was more concerned with the longer-term
economic disruptions the quake may have caused. If residents aren't
spending as much money due to highway damage, for example, local
sales tax revenue could drop, lowering the ability of
municipalities to make bond payments.
   But another effect may be that sales tax revenue will jump when
people start buying construction materials and other goods to
rebuild, he said.
   Investors appeared unfazed by the quake. Though there were
isolated bond issues from the quake area that declined in value
last week, most California municipal bond prices moved with the
municipal market as a whole.
   Franklin Resources Inc., operator of the nation's largest mutual
fund composed entirely of California municipal bonds, said it
received few calls from investors concerned about the fund's fate.
   One reason could be that phone lines into the company's San
Mateo, Calif., headquarters were affected by the quake, said
Charles Johnson, Franklin's marketing director. But he said he
believed the main reason was that investors realized the
diversified, $9 billion fund would not be affected, since it is
composed of bond issues from throughout the state.
   Officials of Putnam and Dreyfus Corp., two other mutual fund
operators, also reported few investor inquiries about their
California muni funds.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Monday, Sept. 23</NOTE>
<TEXT>
