<FIRST>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   10-20 0326</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0338</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Weaken Slightly After Soviet Corn Sale</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices were mostly
lower in early dealings today on the Chicago Board of Trade as corn
traders followed the old market adage, ``Buy the rumor, sell the
fact.''
   An Agriculture Department announcement late Thursday that the
Soviet Union had bought 1.2 million metric tons of U.S. corn
confirmed rumors of a Soviet corn deal that had strongly supported
the grain markets in Thursday's trading session.
   Thursday's speculation about the size of the sale had ranged as
high as 2 million metric tons.
   Increased foreign demand for U.S. grains and soybeans has been a
key factor in this week's across-the-board gains. But the higher
prices have encouraged farmers to sell more of their grain, and
that was another reason for today's early decline.
   Forecasts for improved harvesting weather in the Midwest next
week also discouraged buying of futures this morning.
   In early trading, wheat futures were 1\ cents lower to { cent
higher with the contract for delivery in December at $4.06{ a
bushel; corn was 1{ cents lower to 1 cent higher with December at
$2.42{ a bushel; oats were { cent lower across the board with
December at $1.45{ a bushel; soybeans were 3{ cents lower to 1 cent
higher with November at $5.63\ a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mostly lower in early trading on
the Chicago Mercantile Exchange in cautious trading ahead of this
afternoon's quarterly USDA cattle-on-feed report.
   Live cattle were unchanged to .37 cent lower with October at
74.05 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .05 cent to .35 cent lower
with October at 82.65 cents a pound; live hogs were .10 cent to .40
cent lower with October at 48.50 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies
were .03 cent to .35 cent lower with February at 51.77 cents a
pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled mixed on Thursday.
</TEXT>
