<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-89 1236EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>s f BC-GlobalMarkets Adv22   10-20 0944</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Global Markets, Adv 22,0973</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv22</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Sunday Oct. 22</HEAD>
<HEAD>U.S. Stock Market Jolts the World Again, But Not with Disastrous
Results</HEAD>
<HEAD>Graphic in AP Access as GLOBALMKTS</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM BUERKLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Like the earthquake that jolted Northern
California, the U.S. stock market's big drop sent a tremor through
the global financial system last week.
   The sudden plunge didn't appear to do lasting damage, but it did
show Wall Street as an unstable bellwether for the world's equity
markets. Its foundations look all the more creaky compared with the
Tokyo stock market, the world's biggest and richest. Tokyo slipped
modestly after New York's plunge but quickly recovered and ended
last week on its customary note _ higher.
   That performance is convincing many analysts that far from being
a bubble about to burst, Japan's stock market _ like its economy _
is a bedrock of stability that's a growing influence on world
markets.
   ``The Tokyo market, despite the fact that we've all been saying
that it's overpriced and it's gone up too much, performs when the
chips are down,'' said Barton Biggs, chief investment strategist at
Morgan Stanley &amp; Co. and chairman of the firm's asset management
arm.
   The chips have been down in a big way twice in the past two
years, and each time Japan has led the world's equity markets back
from the brink.
   Before Black Monday wiped out nearly a quarter of this country's
stock market values on Oct. 19, 1987, many analysts regarded Tokyo
as the global markets' weak link. Share prices in relation to
earnings were at least three times as high as in New York and
Europe, seemingly unsustainable heights.
   But Tokyo not only didn't trigger the crash, its decline was the
smallest of any major stock market, and Japanese stocks regained
their pre-crash levels months before any others. The Japanese
market did it again last week as the Nikkei index erased Monday's
1.8 percent decline in just two days while other markets, including
New York, curbed losses but remained down.
   ``It's certainly a safer place,'' says Rudiger Dornbusch, an
economist at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology. ``I think
the Japanese know better how to manage their economy and their
markets. We make a culture out of financial vulnerability and
volatility.''
   Dornbusch blames much of Wall Street's whipsaw action on
investor demands for instant returns _ buying a stock in hopes of
selling it at a higher price within days or weeks, perhaps amid
takeover fever, rather than looking at a company's long-term
earning potential.
   That tendency ``really goes right to the heart of problems of
American competitiveness and manufacturing performance,'' he says,
especially vs. Japan. ``Our horizon is lunchtime. Theirs is 10
years.''
   Japan also has money on its side, says Robert Brusca, chief
economist at Nikko Securities Co. International in New York. The
cash generated by Japan's seemingly limitless exports of cars,
stereos and computer chips gives the Tokyo market a strength that
New York cannot match because of the big U.S. trade deficit.
   ``The United States has the potentially fragile market because
we are the ones that are relying on continuous inflows of capital
from abroad,'' he contends.
   Japan's buoyant economy adds an ``inherently stabilizing
feature'' to the market, says Geoffrey Dennis, economist with James
Capel &amp; Co. in New York. Japan adjusted quickly to the sharp rise
in the yen in 1986 and 1987 by relying more on domestic demand for
growth rather than exports.
   Peter Davies, assistant vice president at Nomura Securities
International Inc. in New York, said the firm's research arm
forecasts Japan's economy will grow 4.8 percent this year and 4.4
percent in 1990, compared with 2.9 percent and 1.8 percent,
respectively, for the United States.
   All those economic strengths haven't enabled Tokyo to replace
New York as the leading influence on world equity markets, however.
Indeed, notwithstanding Tokyo's relatively modest decline last
Monday, European markets plummeted initially and rallied only when
New York rebounded.
   In part, European traders ignored Tokyo's calmer reaction
because it was expected, says Tim O'Dell, international market
strategist at Phillips &amp; Drew in London. Unlike regulatory
authorities in the United States and Europe, Japanese authorities
can put pressure on the country's securities firms, banks,
insurance companies and pension funds to avoid a selloff.
   Tokyo's sky high prices also aren't seen as relevant to New
York, London or Frankfurt, where dividend income plays a bigger
role in valuing stocks. Japanese shares are trading at prices that
are nearly 60 times annual earnings, compared with multiples of
about 13 in New York and 12 in London and Frankfurt.
   What's more, European stock markets historically have moved more
closely in step with Wall Street than with Tokyo, says Davies.
   All of which creates a kind of ``Mars effect'' that sets Japan
apart from other financial centers, Nikko's Brusca says. ``The
Tokyo market sets the same kind of precedent that events on Mars do
for everyone else.''
   So Tokyo may not be a bellwether, but its ability to withstand
the turbulence emanating from New York makes it an attractive play
for investors looking to diversify, says O'Dell.
   ``It is not like Wall Street and London,'' he says. ``It
actually does reduce risk.''
   Morgan Stanley's Biggs said that fact should help Tokyo, which
represents about 40 percent of the world's stock market by value,
to garner a bigger share of global investment funds compared with
New York, which accounts for about 33 percent of world equities.
   ``You'd have to say that capital is going to tend to flow
towards the stable environment rather than the unstable one.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End adv for Sunday Oct. 22</NOTE>
