<FIRST>r f AM-LincolnS&amp;L     10-20 0141</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lincoln S&amp;L,0146</SECOND>
<HEAD>Earthquake Prompts Postponement of Lincoln S&amp;L Hearing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The San Francisco earthquake caused the House
Banking Committee on Friday to reschedule its second hearing
investigating the failure of Lincoln Savings and Loan Association.
   The hearing into what is expected to be the nation's largest
thrift failure was moved from Oct. 24 to Oct. 26.
   ``The transportation and communication disruptions have made it
difficult for witnesses to prepare properly for the Tuesday hearing
and the committee investigative staff and personnel from the
General Accounting Office have been unable to collect documents and
complete pre-hearing interviews,'' the panel chairman, Rep. Henry
B. Gonzalez, D-Texas, said in a statement.
   Much of the committee investigation is focusing on the
difference of opinion between Washington-based regulators and
thrift examiners in San Francisco concerning the condition of the
Irvine, Calif., S&amp;L.
</TEXT>
