<FIRST>u f AM-Ford-Saab     10-20 0272</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ford-Saab,0283</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ford and Saab End Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford Motor Co. and Saab-Scania AB said Friday
they were calling off talks analysts said might have been aimed at
developing a European truck operation for Ford.
   The companies said in a joint statement that the discussions
were friendly but produced no agreement ``that could make long-term
business sense for both parties.''
   Though it was rumored that Saab had sought a buyer to help its
troubled passenger car division, the companies themselves said only
that they were discussing possible cooperation in various areas.
   Ford already is a strong seller of cars in Europe but lacks a
widespread medium- and heavy-duty truck operation there, leading
U.S. analysts to pinpoint Saab's Scania truck division as Ford's
probable target.
   ``There are a number of things that we discussed with Saab, but
both companies signed a confidentiality agreement on the subjects
we were discussing and that will remain in force,'' Ford spokesman
Bert Serre said.
   The discussions went on for several months, he said, though he
wouldn't say how often meetings were held or who took part.
   Ford has its own Swedish operation, Ford Motor Co. AB, founded
in Stockholm in 1924 to market Ford products in that country.
   Ford announced Sept. 19 that it intended to acquire a 15 percent
share of British luxury automaker Jaguar PLC, and said Monday its
share had reached 10.9 percent. Serre wouldn't comment on whether
Ford's holdings remained at that level Friday.
   He did say Ford considered the Jaguar and Saab talks separate,
and progress of the Jaguar move didn't lead to the end of
discussions with Saab.
</TEXT>
