<HEAD>Eds: AMs version expected by 5:30 p.m. EDT.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar made small gains in Europe Friday as
the market's recent interest in stocks started to fade and
attention refocused on U.S. economic fundamentals.
   Dealers reported that the shift in focus encouraged some
investors who had been betting on a weaker dollar to cover their
short positions, which had the effect of driving the dollar higher.
   In Tokyo, the dollar closed at 141.35 yen, down 0.20 yen from
Thursday's close of 141.55 yen. Later in London, it was quoted at
142.30 yen.
   The British pound sold for $1.5885 in London, down from $1.5940
late Thursday.
   Other late dollar rates late Friday in Europe compared with late
Thursday's rates included: 1.8535 West German marks, up from
1.8525; 1.6255 Swiss francs, up from 1.6225; 6.2962 French francs,
up from 6.2875; 2.0973 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0820; 1,363.65
Italian lire, up from 1,358.50; and 1.1732 Canadian dollars, down
from 1.1741.
   Gold traded in London late Friday at $366.75 a troy ounce, down
$1 from Thursday. In Zurich, the bid price was $366, down from
$368.20 late Thursday.
   Gold in Hong Kong dropped $1.49 to close at a bid price of
$367.40 per troy ounce.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $5.09 a troy
ounce, unchanged from late Thursday.
  
