<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-89 1509EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-ThiokolBoard     10-20 0203</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Thiokol Board,0213</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Astronaut Armstrong Named to Thiokol Board</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Neil Armstrong, the first man to walk on
the moon, is joining the board of directors of Thiokol Corp., whose
rocket was blamed in the 1986 explosion of the space shuttle
Challenger.
   Armstrong and several other directors were elected Thursday in
the first shareholders' meeting of the company since the separation
of Morton Thiokol Inc. into Thiokol and Morton International Inc.
in July.
   The explosion of Challenger was blamed on a faulty O-ring seal
on one of the shuttle's solid-fuel booster rockets, which were
built by Morton Thiokol. Seven astronauts died in the explosion.
   Thiokol was involved in the redesign of the rockets and since
the redesign there have been six successful missions, U. Edwin
Garrison, chief executive officer of the company, told shareholders.
   Garrison said in his annual report that Thiokol has 40 percent
of the solid rocket propulsion market in the United States.
   Thiokol operates a sprawling solid-fuel rocket production and
testing facility about 40 miles northwest of Ogden, the company's
headquarters.
   ``Thiokol is well-positioned for the future with a backlog of $4
billion in work,'' Garrison said.
   Thursday's meeting was conducted under tight security.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
