<DOCNO> AP891020-0293 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-89 1524EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Discovision     10-20 0210</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Discovision,0219</SECOND>
<HEAD>IBM, MCA to Sell Discovision Associates</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COSTA MESA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pioneer Electronics Corp. of Japan has
agreed to buy a laser disc pioneer, Discovision Associates, for
$200 million.
   The deal to sell Discovision was announced Thursday by its
co-owners, International Business Machines Corp. and MCA Inc.
   Discovision began researching and making laser video disks in
the 1960s and holds more than 1,400 patents and patent applications
at the heart of compact disc player, video disc player and related
technologies. Discovision no longer manufactures anything, and the
patents are its sole assets.
   Discovision President James N. Fiedler said the company was not
seeking a buyer, but that Pioneer ``offered a price we were not
prepared to refuse.''
   Pioneer, the leading seller of optical disc systems in the
United States, appears to have achieved a major coup over its Dutch
rival, NV Philips, said Linda Helgerson, editor of CD Data Report,
a newsletter based in Falls Church, Va.
   She noted that while Philips is credited with inventing many of
the basic laser disc technologies, the company agreed last year to
pay a ``significant sum'' to license technologies from Discovision.
   All the world's major manufacturers of laser disc systems,
including Sony Corp. and Hitachi Ltd., are licensees of Discovision.
</TEXT>
