<DOCNO> AP891020-0294 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-89 1541EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-CocoaCrop     10-20 0330</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Cocoa Crop,0341</SECOND>
<HEAD>Record World Crop and Further Price Fall Forecast</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: For release 6 p.m. EDT; time set by source.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The prospect of another record world cocoa crop
this season points to further downward pressure on prices, which
are already at their lowest in 14 years, a leading international
cocoa merchant said Friday.
   In its first forecast for the year beginning this month, Gill
and Duffus Ltd. put production at 2.386 million metric tons,
231,000 tons in excess of consumption.
   This would be the sixth consecutive season of overproduction,
lifting world stocks to a record high of 1.305 million tons and
exacerbating current storage problems, the company said.
   ``The analysis of supply-demand fundamentals points to further
downward pressure over the next 12 months,'' it added.
   Cocoa prices, once adjusted for inflation, are at their lowest
level of the post-World War II period, severely damaging the
economies of the Ivory Coast, Ghana and other exporting countries
that rely on the export of beans for foreign exchange earnings,
analysts said.
   Stocks are already at their highest level ever, following the
estimated addition of a record 314,000 tons last season, when
production rose by 198,000 tons to 2.375 million tons, according
Gill and Duffus's estimates.
   It put the 1988-89 harvest in the Ivory Coast at 810,000 tons,
the biggest ever and 145,000 above 1987-88.
   Ghana's crop rose to 305,000 tons last season from 188,000,
Nigeria's to 160,000 from 150,000 and Indonesia's to a record
65,000 from 49,000, while Brazil recorded a fall to 333,000 from
342,000 and Malaysia to 220,000 from a record 222,000 in 1987-88.
   The company's crop estimates for 1989-90 include the Ivory Coast
730,000 tons, Brazil 345,000, Ghana 330,000, Malaysia 255,000,
Nigeria 185,000, Cameroon 110,000, Indonesia 85,000, Ecuador
75,000, Colombia 52,000, Mexico 45,000 and Papua New Guinea 38,000
tons.
   International talks here last month on a producer-consumer deal
to support the market ended in failure and no further meetings on
the issue are currently scheduled.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
