<FIRST>r f AM-IntegratedResources     10-20 0231</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Integrated Resources,0240</SECOND>
<HEAD>Investment Firm Resumes Talks for Selling Core Businesses</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Integrated Resources Inc. said Friday it has
resumed negotiations with an unnamed party to buy its core
financial services in an attempt to raise money to help pay off
$1.75 billion in debt.
   Integrated had said Tuesday that the talks had ended. It said
then that a group of its senior executives was considering making
an offer.
   The struggling investment concern, which defaulted on debt
payments in June, had been negotiating to sell key assets to raise
money to pay some of its outstanding debt and avoid a bankruptcy
filing.
   Integrated's main financial businesses are Integrated Resources
Equity Corp. of Englewood, Colo., its principal broker-dealer
subsidiary; Resources Trust Co.; and Integrated Resources Asset
Management Corp., an investment adviser.
   The firm also is seeking to sell two of its life insurance
companies, Integrated Resources Life Insurance Co. of Des Moines,
Iowa, and Capitol Life Insurance Co. of Denver.
   Negotiations for the businesses came after a $310 million deal
with Whitehall Financial Group fell through. Whitehall cited
worsening conditions in the debt markets amd concerns over the
value of the businesses.
   Integrated has not paid any principle or interest to bondholders
since June, when it said it would have to default because of
troubles stemming from its difficulty in diversifying out of real
estate into financial services.
</TEXT>
