<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0216</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crop Futures End Lower On Profit-Taking</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices closed slightly
lower Friday on the Chicago Board of Trade, reflecting pre-weekend
profit-taking after a week of substantial gains in the corn and
soybean markets.
   Forecasts for improved harvest weather next week also put
pressure on crop prices, analysts said. The wintry weather that
blasted the Midwest this week slowed the harvest and contributed to
the corn and soybean rally.
   Friday's losses were limited by expectations that the
Agriculture Department will confirm further corn sales to the
Soviet Union. The Soviet purchase of 1.2 million metric tons that
was announced Thursday fell short of the 2 million tons that
traders had expected.
   Rumors persisted that the Soviet Union was seeking to buy U.S.
soybean meal, but no sales were confirmed before the close of
trading.
   At the close, wheat futures were unchanged to 1\ cents lower
with the contract for delivery in December at $4.07 a bushel; corn
was unchanged to 3 cents lower with December at $2.41 a bushel;
oats were 1 cent to 1{ cents lower with December at $1.44} a
bushel; soybeans were \ cent to 2{ cents lower with November at
$5.63 a bushel.
