<FIRST>r f AM-Warner-Sony     10-20 0367</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Warner-Sony,0383</SECOND>
<HEAD>Warner Bros. Takes Further Legal Action Against Sony</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Warner Bros. has stepped up its efforts to
prevent Sony Corp. from hiring producers Peter Guber and Jon Peters
to head the entertainment company Sony plans to acquire, Columbia
Pictures.
   A motion for a preliminary injunction, filed Thursday in Los
Angeles Superior Court, asks a judge to bar Sony from hiring the
``Batman'' producers, who are trying to get out of a five-year
contract they signed with Warner earlier this year.
   The action follows a $1 billion lawsuit filed last week by
Warner against Sony, and a $100 million countersuit Sony filed
against Warner.
   Terry Christensen, an attorney for Guber and Peters, said he
believed Warner filed the suit for publicity and bargaining
purposes.
   ``I don't think it's real,'' Christensen said. ``It's a further
attempt to hammer Sony.''
   The producers contend they had a verbal agreement with Warner
that they would be allowed out of their contract if a chance to run
a big studio came along. But in affidavits filed Thursday, top
Warner executives denied that was true.
   The motion for an injunction also is meant to allow Guber and
Peters to keep working for Warner while the opposing lawsuits go
through the legal system, a process that could take years, Warner
attorney Stuart Robinowitz said.
   Guber and Peters have about 50 projects planned for the next few
years, including sequels to the megahit ``Batman.''
   Without the injunction, the producers could possibly find
themselves unable to work for either company during the litigation,
Robinowitz said.
   Sony recently announced plans to put Guber and Peters, whose
credits also include ``Rain Man,'' in charge of Columbia after it
acquires the entertainment company in a $3.4 billion tender offer.
   Sony also plans to acquire Guber-Peters Entertainment Co. for
about $200 million, or $17.50 per share.
   But Warner contended in court papers the move to hire away Guber
and Peters would violate its five-year exclusive production
contract with the producers.
   A hearing on the injunction was scheduled for Nov. 2.
   The filing for the injunction came on the heels of lawsuits Sony
and Warner filed against each other last week in Los Angeles
Superior Court.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
