<HEAD>Dollar Up, Gold Little Changed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Precedes LONDON BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar ended higher Friday in quiet trading
following a mixed performance overseas.
   Gold prices were little changed. On the Commodity Exchange in
New York, gold for current delivery settled at $367.30 a troy
ounce, up 20 cents from Thursday. Republic National Bank of New
York quoted a late bid for gold at $366.50 an ounce, unchanged.
   Currency traders attributed Friday's rise largely to internal
market influences in the absence of any new market-moving news.
They said the market was awaiting the release of the September
durable goods report on Tuesday and the preliminary report on the
third-quarter gross national product on Thursday.
   However, Earl I. Johnson, a trader with Harris Trust &amp; Co. in
Chicago, said prospects for increased demand for dollars by the
Japanese were giving some support to the currency.
   ``There seems to be fairly steady demand from institutions, such
as large insurance companies, over there. They seem to like the
(U.S.) bond market,'' Johnson said.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar closed at 141.35 yen, down 0.20 yen from
Thursday's close. It was quoted at 142.30 yen in London, and at
142.425 yen in New York, up from 142.00.
   The dollar was higher against the British pound. Sterling sold
for $1.5885 in London, down from $1.5940 late Thursday. In New
York, each pound bought $1.5885, down from $1.5975.
   Other late dollar rates in New York compared with Thursday's
quotes included: 1.8578 West German marks, up from 1.8500; 1.6285
Swiss francs, up from 1.6205; 6.3105 French francs, up from 6.2789;
1.17415 Canadian dollars, up from 1.17345; and 1,395.875 Italian
lire, up from 1,360.75.
   Late dollar rates Friday in Europe compared with Thursday:
1.8535 West German marks, up from 1.8525; 1.6255 Swiss francs, up
from 1.6225; 6.2962 French francs, up from 6.2875; 2.0973 Dutch
guilders, up from 2.0820; 1.1732 Canadian dollars, down from
1.1741; and 1,363.65 Italian lire, up from 1,358.50.
   Gold traded in London at $366.75 an ounce, down $1 from
Thursday. In Zurich, the bid price was $366 anounce, down from
$368.20.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold dropped $1.49 to close at $367.40 an
ounce.
   Silver prices held steady. On New York's Comex, silver bullion
for current delivery settled at $5.089 a troy ounce, up from $5.080
Thursday. Silver closed at $5.09 an ounce in London, unchanged.
</TEXT>
