<HEAD>Oil Futures Prices Slip</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil futures prices dipped in light trading
Friday, led by a big drop in the expiring crude contract.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the November contract for
West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark U.S. grade of crude oil,
fell 44 cents to finish at $19.98 a 42-gallon barrel. The contract
slid 14 cents on Thursday.
   Analysts said the decline came from investors liquidating their
positions on the final trading day of the contract.
   ``There was no indication of new factors in the market,'' said
Bob Baker, analyst with Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. ``There
was selling because it was overbought.''
   Crude contracts for delivery after November showed smaller
declines.
   Among refined products traded on the exchange, wholesale
unleaded gasoline for November delivery lost 0.14 cent to close at
54.51 cents a gallon after edging up 0.07 cent on Thursday. The
December contract fell 0.43 cent to 53.88 cents a gallon with later
contracts showing similar declines.
   Domestic heating oil for delivery in November dropped 0.45 cent
to 60.44 cents a gallon while the December contract declined 0.52
cent to 60.84 cents.
