<FIRST>r f AM-GM-Minorities     10-20 0245</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-GM-Minorities,0255</SECOND>
<HEAD>Smith Says Prosperity Affects Extent of Minority Programs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BIRMINGHAM, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Motors Corp.'s prosperity
determines how much help it can give minority businesses, GM
Chairman Roger Smith said Friday.
   GM has several programs aimed at increasing its dealings with
minorities, such as its ``statement of fair-share principles''
agreement with the National Association for the Advancement of
Colored People, Smith said.
   Smith told a National Business League breakfast in Birmingham,
Ala., that the world's largest auto company hopes to start more
programs.
   ``But I must tell you our ability to make these kinds of
investments _ and to fulfill our fair-share commitments _ depends
pretty heavily on the health and profitability of our business,''
Smith said, according to a GM news release.
   GM spokesman Chuck Licari said Smith wasn't casting doubt on the
future of current programs, but pointing out that auto companies
are in a competitive pinch. ``All those programs are going
forward,'' Licari said.
   The fair-share agreement encourages GM dealings with minority
operations in purchasing, banking, insurance, advertising and other
areas.
   GM also has a minority small-business investment company, Motor
Enterprises Inc., that has provided nearly $8 million in financial
assistance to about 250 minority companies, Smith said.
   GM has 208 minority-owned car and truck dealerships, has
deposited more than $900 million in minority-owned banks, has
nearly $14 billion in property damage insurance with minority-owned
brokers, and placed $7.7 million in advertising last year with
minority-owned media, he said.
</TEXT>
