<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-89 2025EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Paramount-MCATV     10-20 0524</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Paramount-MCA TV,0542</SECOND>
<HEAD>Paramount, MCA Explore Offering Prime-Time Programming</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The television arms of Paramount Communications
Inc. and MCA Inc. have described to some station executives a plan
to offer prime-time programming two nights a week as a step toward
creating a fifth TV network, industry executives said Friday.
   The network the executives said was described by Paramount and
MCA would compete with NBC, ABC, CBS and Fox Broadcasting Co.
   Reports of plans for the network were carried first by Daily
Variety, the trade newspaper, earlier this week and several major
newspapers subsequently carried similar accounts of the plans.
   But the Los Angeles Times reported Friday that the deal
apparently had fallen apart.
   Citing an unidentified source familiar with the deal, the Times
said there was a ``so-called programming service that had been on
the boards, but a snag developed in the agreement between Paramount
and MCA, as a result of which this activity has been discontinued.''
   A spokeswoman for Paramount said from Los Angeles that her
company does not comment on rumors or speculation. A call was
placed to Shelly Schwab, president of MCA TV in Los Angeles, but it
was not returned and others in the company said they were not
authorized to comment on any of the reports.
   Brad Turell, a spokesman for Fox Broadcasting in Los Angeles,
said ``some of our affiliates have been contacted'' by Paramount
and MCA about whether they would be interested in carrying some
prime-time programming.
   Michael Fisher, president and general manager at KTXL in
Sacramento, Calif., and head of the Fox affiliates board, said at
least one Fox affiliate who he declined to identify told him that
Paramount and MCA executives had described plans to make two nights
of prime-time programming available starting Jan. 1, 1991.
   The plans were to program movies on Wednesday nights and offer
TV series on Friday nights, he said. The plans were to make a third
night of programming available about six months later, Fisher said.
   Fisher, who said he was not approached by Paramount or MCA, said
he was told Paramount and MCA were interested in starting a fifth
network.
   But Fisher said he thought it was unlikely that any Fox
affiliates would defect. ``They have been with Fox for three years
and Fox has done precisely what they said they were going to do,''
he said.
   Fox offers network programming on three nights and claims 127
affiliate stations. It plans to add two additional nights of
programming next year and offer programming on all seven nights a
week in 1992.
   Turell said top Fox Broadcasting executives planned to meet with
Fox affiliates in a series of six regional meetings next week to
reaffirm the company's plans.
   MCA owns WWOR-TV in New York and Paramount last month agreed to
buy a 79 percent stake in the TVX Broadcast Group, which owns five
stations.
   Those stations could form the core for a new network.
   Last month, Paramount and MCA announced a joint venture called
Premier Advertiser Sales, to sell advertising in programs they
syndicate.
   Those shows include ``Star Trek: The Next Generation'' and
``Charles in Charge.''
</TEXT>
