<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-89 1735EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-CapitalGains Bjt   10-20 0374</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Capital Gains, Bjt,0386</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Leader Doubts Congress Will Approve Bush Capital-Gains Cut</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate Majority Leader George J. Mitchell said
Friday he doubts Congress will vote to cut capital gains this year.
   President Bush has been pressing hard for a capital-gains tax
cut.
   Mitchell, a Maine Democrat, told reporters it is difficult to
predict a vote on the issue because there is no certainty what type
of capital-gains cut the Senate will be considering.
   Sen. Bob Packwood, R-Ore., said Thursday that he can count 55 to
58 votes _ a majority _ for his own capital-gains proposal.
   That is not necessarily in conflict with what Mitchell said.
Democrats, most of whom stiffly oppose any cut in capital-gains
taxes, might filibuster against Packwood's plan, and it would take
60 votes to shut off debate.
   Packwood and Sen. Bill Roth, R-Del., are sponsoring a plan to
exclude between 5 percent and 35 percent of capital gains from
taxation, depending on how long an asset was owned before it was
sold. The bill also would let workers set up Individual Retirement
Accounts that would allow tax-free withdrawals for medical
expenses, education, home-buying or retirement.
   The Packwood-Roth plan is backed by the Bush administration. The
president also supports a less-ambitious capital-gains cut that has
been passed by the House over opposition of the Democratic
leadership.
   Mitchell, a Maine Democrat, said the Packwood-Roth plan ``raises
real questions about fiscal responsibility.''
   Tax benefits for IRAs are going to cost the same whether the
benefits are provided at the time a contribution is made _ as under
current law _ or when a withdrawal is made from an IRA, as Packwood
and Roth are recommending, Mitchell said.
   ``The only question is which generation is going to pay for
it,'' Mitchell said.
   The Democratic leader took a swipe at Bush for pressing so hard
for the capital-gains cut that he promised in last year's
presidential campaign.
   ``I would like to see the president devote as much time to
presidential policy in response to historic events in Western and
Eastern Europe,'' Mitchell said. ``I'd like to see him devote a
fraction of the time to that, that he is to this capital-gains
debacle.''
</TEXT>
