<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-89 1754EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-SFQuake-PacificExchange     10-20 0285</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SF Quake-Pacific Exchange,0295</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pacific Stock Exchange Plans to Resume Operations Monday</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pacific Stock Exchange said Friday it would resume normal
trading at its San Francisco home on Monday after the Bay Quake
shut it down and traders were dispatched around the country to keep
the market alive.
   ``Our facilities are intact,'' exchange chairman Maurice Mann
said in a statement. ``Public safety authorities and building
inspectors have examined our options trading floor in San Francisco
and declared it sound structurally and safe for occupancy.''
   Mann also said the exchange's equities trading floor and other
facilities were safe and the opening bell would ring Monday at 6:30
a.m. PST.
   About 150 Pacific options traders and support staffers were sent
to exchanges in New York, Chicago and Philadelphia on Thursday and
Friday to trade stock options that are listed solely on the Pacific
exchange.
   Some trading occurred Wednesday, the day after the Bay area's
devastating earthquake, at the exchange in San Francisco, where
dealers worked with the aid of flashlights and candles, rerouting
trades via phone through Los Angeles.
   The traders were relocated east because the Los Angeles exchange
does not trade options.
   The Pacific exchange trades options _ which many investors use
to hedge their stock positions _ in 130 underlying stocks, with
some 70,000 contracts changing hands on an average day.
   Among big-name stocks that have options traded only on the
Pacific exchange are Hilton Hotels Corp. and Compaq Computer Corp.
   ``On Monday we will have business as usual on all of our trading
floors,'' Mann said. ``Markets will be made, orders will be filled
and the PSE will continue to meet its public responsibility as a
securities marketplace.''
</TEXT>
