<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     10-20 0730</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0755</SECOND>
<HEAD>Copper Futures Plummet On Canadian Strike Settlement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Copper futures prices plummeted to new lows for the month Friday
as a 3{-month strike at a large Canadian copper mine ended and
Mexico's biggest copper mine reportedly prepared to reopen after a
two-month shutdown.
   On other commodity markets Friday, precious metals were nearly
flat; energy futures fell; grains and soybeans retreated; livestock
and meat futures were mixed; and stock-index futures advanced.
   Copper futures settled 2.9 sents to 4.5 cents lower on New
York's Commodity Exchange with the contract for December delivery
at $1.2345 a pound, its lowest price since Sept. 29.
   Union workers at the Highland Valley copper mine in British
Columbia ratified a new contract Thursday night, ending a strike
that began July 6, and were to report to work Saturday, said
company spokesman Rod Killough.
   The mine is capable of producing 180,000 tons of copper
annually, more than 3 percent of the world's output. Analysts said
new supplies from Highland Valley could begin reaching copper
consumers within a month.
   A wire-service report that Mexico's state-owned Cananea mine may
reopen within a week helped further to ease the tight-supply fears
that have supported the copper market for about four months. The
160,000 tons-per-year mine closed Aug. 20, allegedly due to
financial mismanagement.
   Another major copper mine, the Bougainville mine in Papua New
Guinea, remains shut down due to terrorist activity.
   But even that situation appears to be improving, three months
after the mine closed, said Craig Sloane, a metals analyst with
Smith Barney, Harris Upham &amp; Co. in New York.
   ``There's some talk that the landowners are trying to hold out
an olive branch to meet with the rebels,'' Sloane said. ``It's hard
to say if we're really near any kind of resolution but one can say
it's a little more optimistic than it looked before.''
   Gold futures settled unchanged on the Comex with December at
$370.60 a troy ounce; silver was 0.7 cent to 0.9 cent higher with
December at $5.14 an ounce.
   Oil futures prices dipped in light trading on the New York
Mercantile Exchange, led by a 44-cent drop in the expiring November
crude contract to $19.98 a barrel.
   Other West Texas Intermediate crude oil futures settled 27 cents
lower to 4 cents higher with December at $20.15 a barrel; heating
oil was .37 cent to .52 cent lower with November at 60.44 cents a
gallon; unleaded gasoline was .14 cent to .45 cent lower with
November at 54.51 cents a gallon.
   Grain and soybean futures finished slightly lower on the Chicago
Board of Trade, reflecting pre-weekend profit-taking after a week
of substantial gains in the corn and soybean markets.
   After the close, the Agriculture Department announced a sale of
2.8 million metric tons of corn and 160,000 metric tons of soybean
meal to the Soviet Union.
   Wheat futures settled { cent to } cent lower with December at
$4.07 a bushel; corn was unchanged to 2{ cents lower with December
at $2.41{ a bushel; oats were 1 cent to 1{ cents lower with
December at $1.44} a bushel; soybeans were 1 cent to 2{ cents lower
with November at $5.63{ a bushel.
   Cattle futures settled lower on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange
ahead of the USDA's quarterly cattle-on-feed report while pork
futures advanced
   The report showed 6 percent fewer cattle being fattened for
slaughter as of Oct. 1 compared to a year ago in the 13 largest
cattle-producing states. The number was lower than anticipated and
is likely to prompt some buying of cattle futures on Monday.
   The October live cattle contract expired 1.17 cents lower at
73.25 cents a pound; the October live hog contract expired .30 cent
lower at 49.05 cents a pound.
   Other live cattle contracts settled .03 cent to .27 cent lower
with December at 75.02 cents a pound; feeder cattle were unchanged
to .20 cent lower with October at 82.80 cents a pound; hogs were
.15 cent to .35 cent lower with December at 46.80 cents a pound;
frozen pork bellies were .75 cent to 1.05 cents lower with February
at 52.85 cents a pound.
   Stock-index futures rose modestly on the Chicago Merc, where the
contract for December delivery of stocks tracked by the Standard &amp;
Poor's 500 index settled .85 point higher at 350.45. The contract
is valued at $500 a point.
</TEXT>
