<FIRST>u f AM-Bonds     10-20 0417</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bonds,0437</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bond Prices Finish Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government bond prices finished lower Friday in
sluggish trading, weighed down by concerns about a heavy supply of
new issues.
   The 30-year Treasury bond lost \ point, or $2.50 for each $1,000
in face amount, after being up as much as $3.75 earlier in the day.
Its yield rose to 7.98 percent from 7.96 percent late Thursday.
   Analysts said the market's early rise was an extension of
Thursday's rally, which saw 30-year bond prices rise by about $8
for every $1,000 in face value due to a report of a
smaller-than-expected rise in consumer prices last month.
   But they said prices gave ground in slow activity in the
afternoon as traders apparently took profits on the recent runup in
prices and others looked toward a large supply of new issues that
is to be auctioned next week.
   In the secondary market for Treasury securities, prices of
short-term governments fell 5-32 point, intermediate maturities
lost 6-32 point and long-term issues dropped as much as \ point,
according to Telerate Inc., the financial information service.
   The movement of a point is equivalent to a change of $10 in the
price of a bond with a $1,000 face value.
   The Shearson Lehman Hutton Daily Treasury Bond Index, which
measures price movements on all outstanding Treasury issues with
maturities of a year or longer, fell 1.79 to 1,187.63.
   Moody's Investment Grade Corporate Bond Index, which measures
total return on a portfolio of 80 corporate bonds with maturities
of five years or longer, rose 0.05 to 337.85.
   In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively
traded municipal bonds fell 11-32 point to 92 17-32. The average
yield to maturity rose to 7.34 percent from 7.31 percent late
Thursday.
   Yields on three-month Treasury bills rose to 7.80 percent as the
discount rose 1 basis point to 7.56 percent. Yields on six-month
bills fell to 7.95 percent as the discount lost 1 basis point to
7.55 percent.
   Yields on one-year bills held steady at 7.87 percent as the
discount was unchanged from Thursday's auction level at 7.34
percent.
   A basis point is one-hundredth of a percentage point. The yield
is the annualized return on an investment in a Treasury bill. The
discount is the percentage that bills are selling below the face
value, which is paid at maturity.
   The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between
banks, was quoted at 811-16 percent, the same as Thursday's late
rate.
</TEXT>
