<FIRST>r f AM-BritishPetroleum-CRA     10-20 0339</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-British Petroleum-CRA,0353</SECOND>
<HEAD>BP Sells Australian Coal Interests to CRA</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British Petroleum Co. PLC said Friday it has
agreed to sell its Australian coal business to CRA Ltd. for $275
million in cash, as part of a recently announced restructuring of
the London-based company.
   The deal, announced after a meeting of British Petroleum
executives and securities analysts in New York, is expected to be
closed on Nov. 30. The sale is subject to approval by government
regulators.
   ``This is the first step in the divestment of our worldwide coal
interests,'' said Patrick Gillam, a BP managing director.
   CRA Ltd. is a mining and minerals company based in Melbourne,
Australia. BP Australia Ltd. currently has about 770 million tons
of extractable reserves, the company said.
   On June 15, BP announced it would put up for sale the major part
of its worldwide coal interests, including assets and operations in
the United States, Australia, South Africa and Europe.
   The sale is part of a previously announced restructuring of
British Petroleum, the world's fourth largest oil concern. In
addition to reorganizing its exploration and production operations,
the company is also reducing its work force by 17 percent, or 1,700
jobs.
   British Petroleum said it would use the proceeds from the coal
sale to ``strengthen our balance sheet and to take advantage of
investment opportunities for our other businesses.''
   Analysts estimate BP's long-term debt will be about $8.8 billion
at the end of 1989. BP has sold approximately $6.5 billion in
assets this year alone.
   Last month, BP announced it was selling a portion of its North
Sea properties as well as exploration assets in six countries to
Oryx Energy Co. of Dallas for $1.31 billion.
   John Ralph, managing director and chief executive of CRA, said
the sale was a good move for the Melbourne company.
   ``The purchase of BP Australia's coal business...will fit well
with CRA's existing coal business,'' he said. ``It will strengthen
the group's base in the coal business and contribute to its
profitable growth.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
