<FIRST>r f BC-BusinessHighlights     10-20 0832</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Business Highlights,0871</SECOND>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British Airways PLC has bailed out of a group
attempting to buy UAL Corp., a defection that sent UAL stock into
another tailspin and dealt the buyout plan its second stunning blow
in a week.
   The pilots union at UAL's United Airlines, which along with
management is leading the buyout attempt, quickly announced Friday
it was developing a new plan that would include for the first time
United's flight attendants as partners.
   In a brief statement, British Airways said it ``does not intend
to participate in any new deal for the acquisition of UAL in the
foreseeable future.'' It didn't give reasons, but said its
marketing agreement with United would remain in effect.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Treasury Secretary Nicholas F. Brady,
reflecting on stock market plunges two years apart, said the more
the federal government coordinates its regulation of financial
markets, ``the better off we're going to be.''
   In his first extensive discussion of last week's sudden market
drop, Brady said Friday there was no ``air of panic'' within the
administration after the Dow Jones average dropped 190 points last
Friday.
   He said he spent much of Monday _ when the market rebounded
sharply _ personally monitoring market developments.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pacific Stock Exchange said it would
resume normal trading at home Monday after the Bay Quake shut it
down and traders were dispatched around the country to keep the
market alive.
   About 150 Pacific options traders and support staffers were sent
to exchanges in New York, Chicago and Philadelphia on Thursday and
Friday to trade stock options that are listed solely on the Pacific
exchange.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texaco Inc. said it has agreed to acquire Tana
Production Corp. in a deal valued at $476.5 million.
   The deal Friday was part of a continuing effort to expand oil
and gas reserves and Texaco's first major purchase since completing
a massive restructuring earlier this year.
   The merger with Corpus Christi, Texas-based Tana Production, a
subsidiary of TRT Energy Holdings Inc., includes the purchase of
435 billion cubic feet of natural gas and about 4 million barrels
of oil located in 17 South Texas fields, Texaco said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>KIRKLAND, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   McCaw Cellular Communications Inc. said
it has received commitments from three banks to provide $1.2
billion in financing for its $2.75 billion offer for a majority
interest in LIN Broadcasting Corp.
   LIN has taken no position on the offer, and is already committed
to a separate deal in which it plans to merge its cellular
operations with those of BellSouth Corp., the regional telephone
company based in Atlanta. McCaw made the announcement Friday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The television arms of Paramount Communications
Inc. and MCA Inc. have described to some station executives a plan
to offer prime-time programming two nights a week as a step toward
creating a fifth TV network, industry executives said.
   The network the executives said was described by Paramount and
MCA on Friday would compete with NBC, ABC, CBS and Fox Broadcasting
Co.
   Reports of plans for the network were carried first by Daily
Variety, but the Los Angeles Times reported Friday that the deal
apparently had fallen apart.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Warner Bros. has stepped up its efforts to
prevent Sony Corp. from hiring producers Peter Guber and Jon Peters
to head the entertainment company Sony plans to acquire, Columbia
Pictures.
   A motion for a preliminary injunction, filed Thursday in Los
Angeles Superior Court, asks a judge to bar Sony from hiring the
``Batman'' producers, who are trying to get out of a five-year
contract they signed with Warner earlier this year.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford Motor Co. and Saab-Scania AB said they were
calling off talks analysts said might have been aimed at developing
a European truck operation for Ford.
   The companies said in a joint statement Friday that the
discussions were friendly but produced no agreement ``that could
make long-term business sense for both parties.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British Petroleum Co. PLC said it has agreed to
sell its Australian coal business to CRA Ltd. for $275 million in
cash, as part of a recently announced restructuring of the
London-based company.
   The deal, announced Friday after a meeting of British Petroleum
executives and securities analysts in New York, is expected to be
closed on Nov. 30. The sale is subject to approval by government
regulators.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market posted mixed results Friday, closing out a week
of record-setting recovery from the scary selloff of Oct. 13. The
Dow Jones industrial average rose 5.94 to 2,689.14, stretching its
gain for the week to 119.88 points.
   The dollar ended higher in quiet trading.
   Government bond prices finished lower.
   Copper futures prices plummeted to new lows for the month;
precious metals were nearly flat; energy futures fell; grains and
soybeans retreated; livestock and meat futures were mixed; and
stock-index futures advanced.
</TEXT>
