<DOCNO> AP891020-0325 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-89 2115EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Earns-Pittston     10-20 0228</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earns-Pittston,0236</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pittston Earnings Drop 79 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GREENWICH, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pittston Co. on Friday reported
third-quarter earnings fell about 79 percent to $3.1 million from
$14.7 million during the same period last year, a decrease
primarily caused by losses in the company's strike-bound coal
division.
   Earnings per share fell to 8 cents during this year's third
quarter from 38 cents during the third quarter of 1988, the company
said. Revenue edged down to $395.3 million from $398.3 million a
year earlier.
   Losses at the Pittston Coal Group increased to $9.8 million in
the third quarter, up from $3.6 million in the second quarter, as
the strike of Pittston coal mines widened. The company said it has
spent $20 million since the strike began to protect its employees
and property from strike-related violence.
   But while Pittston Coal's earnings fell, another Pittston
division, Burlington Air Express, had $9.2 million in earnings in
the third quarter, up from $3.8 million during the same period last
year, the company said.
   Third-quarter earnings at Pittston's Brink's division were $7.1
million, virtually unchanged from the same quarter last year, the
company said.
   For the first nine months of its fiscal year, Pittston said
earnings fell to $22.6 million, or 60 cents a share, from $33.4
million, or 87 cents a share, a year earlier. Revenue rose to $1.23
billion from $1.17 billion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891020-0326 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-89 1942EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-QintexChapter11     10-20 0545</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Qintex Chapter 11,0562</SECOND>
<HEAD>Qintex Entertainment in Chapter 11</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By E. SCOTT RECKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Qintex Entertainment Inc. said
Friday it had filed for bankruptcy protection, 10 days after its
Australian parent's $1.5 billion deal to buy MGM-UA Communications
Corp. collapsed over a missed $50 million down payment.
   The announcement crushed Qintex Entertainment stock, which lost
more than 60 percent of its value Friday. It fell $2.62{ to $1.50
in over-the-counter trading.
   The television production and distribution company was unable to
make an overdue payment of $5.9 million by a key Thursday deadline,
a lapse that could have triggered a devastating wave of demands
from creditors, the company said.
   Qintex Entertainment is 43 percent owned by Qintex Australia
Ltd., which had provided about $110 million in capital to the
American company over the past four years.
   Qintex Entertainment's chief financial officer, John Lloyd, said
the American company had been assured by its Australian parent that
it would get the $5.9 million by the deadline Thursday.
   But at a board meeting Wednesday, Qintex Australia indicated it
was ``unable or unwilling'' to help Qintex America make the
payment, Lloyd said.
   The payment was related to a distribution deal involving MCA
Inc. and Hal Roach Studios Inc., a Qintex Entertainment subsidiary.
The Roach studios and Qintex Productions Inc., the company's other
operating subsidiary, also filed for protection from creditors
under protection of federal bankruptcy law.
   The announcement underlined the difficulty that Qintex Australia
faces in reviving a bid for MGM-UA. The Australian company had
approached NBC and several foreign companies about helping finance
the takeover.
   Qintex Entertainment had been expected to be part of the
emerging company, but officials said they now envision Qintex
Entertainment going its own way if it can successfully reorganize
under protection from its creditors.
   ``We think we have a very viable company here, but we had to do
this to protect our shareholders,'' Lloyd, the chief financial
officer, said in a telephone interview.
   ``We do not believe at this time that the company will require
additional financing while in Chapter 11,'' Lloyd said.
   He said production would continue on such programs as the
syndicated sports and variety program ``Roller Games'' and a
Hallmark Hall of Fame two-hour special starring Walter Matthau,
``Incident at Lincoln Bluff.''
   The company expects to have about $100 million in revenues this
year. Its other programs include ``Kids Incorporated,'' in its
sixth season on the Disney Channel, and ``The New Leave It to
Beaver'' syndicated show.
   As of the end of its third quarter April 30, Quintex had
liabilities of $155 million and assets of $218 million.
   MGM-UA had agreed to be acquired by Qintex Australia, but broke
off the deal Oct. 9 after Qintex missed the $50 million down
payment. MGM-UA also filed a $50 million breach-of-contract suit in
federal court, accusing Qintex of interfering with an earlier $1.4
billion bid for MGM-UA by Rupert Murdoch's News Corp.
   Qintex Entertainment was not a party to the formal merger
agreement with MGM-UA and is not named in the lawsuit.
   Qintex Entertainment also announced that David Evans had
resigned as president and chief executive officer of Qintex
Entertainment, but said he would continue as a full-time consultant
until a successor can be named.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
